<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conservative Party leaders says Bush can't make dinner  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush won't attend the
Conservative Party's May 17 fund-raising dinner in New York City
where he was to have been the main speaker, but the head of the
third party says he's gotten a rain check.
</P>
<P>
   State party Chairman Michael Long said Wednesday that the
development was the result of a scheduling conflict and not the
rift between Long and New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Bush's
favored candidate in the New York Senate race against Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has nothing to do with the Senate thing,'' Long said after
several telephone conversations with top Bush adviser Karl Rove.
</P>
<P>
   And, Long said, Rove has assured him that Bush, the presumptive
Republican presidential nominee, would instead attend a
Conservative Party event in June or July.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are considering a later date. We're taking a look at the
schedule,'' Bush campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said when asked
about the governor's inability to attend the May 17 dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Long is courting Giuliani alternatives to run on the
Conservative Party line in large part because the mayor is an
abortion rights supporter. No Republican has won statewide office
in New York without Conservative Party backing since 1974. On
Tuesday, Long and millionaire New York philanthropist Virginia
Gilder said they were in discussions about a possible Senate run by
her.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of March, Long had announced that Bush was coming to
the May 17 dinner only to have aides to the Texas governor say that
while the invitation was under consideration, no decision had been
made on attending the event.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, Long sent out 12,000 invitations to the party's
annual fund-raising dinner listing Bush as the guest speaker. The
party leader said Wednesday he must now decide whether to postpone
the event until Bush can make it or go ahead with a Bush surrogate
for the dinner and plan a separate event with the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really is a legitimate screw-up,'' Long said. ''He's going
to be on the West Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the Conservative Party dinner presents several
problems. In addition to helping raise money that could then be
used by the Conservative Party to help a candidate who could hurt
Giuliani, the Conservative Party dinner comes at a time when Bush
is seeking to move toward the political middle as he prepares for
the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Long said none of that will keep Bush away.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a firm commitment,'' he said. ''They will come in here
for me, for the Conservative Party, in either June or July.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's coming in because he wants our endorsement, he wants to
be on our (ballot) line and I play hardball,'' the party chairman
added.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to
also run on third-party ballot lines and add the votes up.
</P>
<P>
   Not having the Conservative Party line could make things even
tougher for Bush in New York than they already are. Democrats enjoy
a 5-3 edge in enrollment and no GOP presidential contender has
carried the state since Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984. In fact,
some GOP strategists have said they don't expect Bush to even
contest New York. The Bush camp denies that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-20-00 0013 </TRAILER>
