<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget to include funding for farm energy aid, barn preservation  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Farmers will get some relief from the recent
hikes in energy costs under a new program that state legislators
have agreed to include in the 2000-01 state budget.
</P>
<P>
   The $2 million Farm Energy Assistance Program would help offset
rising gas, diesel and electricity costs farmers have to pay to
keep farms running, said state Sen. Nancy Larraine Hoffmann,
chairwoman of her chamber's agriculture committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Farmers don't have the luxury of being able to milk in
off-peak hours. Cows have a regular schedule,'' said Hoffmann, a
Syracuse-area Republican and beef cattle farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, eligible farmers will be able to submit
their energy bills to the state and receive a percentage of their
payment back. Specific eligibility requirements and the exact
percentage to be refunded are still being worked out, but Hoffmann
said that for large farms, ''that could mean many hundreds of
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Energy and Research Development Authority will
administer the funds in conjunction with the state Department of
Agriculture and Markets. The aid will take effect in May and
farmers will receive quarterly checks. If the program is
successful, Hoffmann said she expects the program to continue in
future years.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Gregg, a spokesman for the Department of Agriculture and
Markets, said high energy prices come at an especially bad time as
the spring planting season begins. Most of the trucks and tractors
run on diesel fuel and ''they suck up a lot of fuel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy farmers are even harder hit, he said, because milk prices
are extremely low.
</P>
<P>
   ''Income is a third of what it was six months ago and now their
fuel costs twice as much. I'm certain that the math is not on their
side,'' Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers also have to pay for transporting their goods, meaning
more dollars spent on fuel, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coventry Transport Services, which hauls milk for dairy farmers
in upstate New York, has added about 10 cents per 100 pounds of
milk in surcharges to its customers since January to cover rising
fuel costs, owner Tom Tripple said. The company, based in Chenango
County, had previously charged farmers $1 for every 100 pounds of
milk transported.
</P>
<P>
   Tripple said an average-size farm transports about 10,000 pounds
of milk every two days.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Reed of the New York Farm Bureau said it's too early to
tell what impact the program will have on farmers, but added,
''Anything to help farmers is good news.''
</P>
<P>
   The new budget would also include $3 million for a new Historic
Barn Preservation Program, Hoffmann said.
</P>
<P>
   The program would provide financial aid mostly to farmers who
are making structural repairs on old dairy barns that are a part of
the rural New York landscape. The barns, which used to store hay on
top and house cattle below, can no longer accommodate new farming
technology, but Hoffmann said they should still be preserved for
their historic and tourism value. While many programs exist for
preserving historical districts in urban areas, ''rarely has there
been a program designed to do something in the historic
preservation vein in rural areas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''These barns are like cathedrals. They're built by craftsmen
with ingenuity ... long before there were cranes,'' she said.
''They have an incredible amount of history embedded within them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffmann said with farmers already struggling to make ends meet,
many don't have the resources to make capital improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The program would provide funds to eligible farmers under a
cost-sharing structure and the renovated barn could be reused for
agricultural purposes. A point system will be established to
determine eligibility, Hoffmann said. That system would take into
account the barn's historic value, architectural uniqueness,
vulnerability to the effects of weather and proximity to other
tourism areas.
</P>
<P>
   The state Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation
and the Department of Agriculture and Markets will oversee the
program.
</P>
<P>
   New York's budget, for the fiscal year that began April 1, is
late for the 16th straight year. On Wednesday, state lawmakers
began what amounts to a 10-day spring vacation. Despite not having
completed work on the state budget, they aren't due back at the
state Capitol until May 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
