<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders and governor fail to finalize agreement on budget  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Gov. George Pataki and the state
Legislature's top Democrat were on the verge of announcing a
tentative agreement for a new state budget until the devil in the
details got in the way.
</P>
<P>
   New York's budget, for the state fiscal year that began April 1,
is late for the 16th straight year.
</P>
<P>
   In a flurry of activity, Pataki's office announced the governor
would hold a Wednesday morning news conference on the budget. State
Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver scheduled his own news conference
to follow the governor's, also to talk about the tentative
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But just before the scheduled 10 a.m. start of the governor's
event, it was postponded, as was Silver's. Later, both news
conferences were canceled. Republican Pataki flew off to the
Southern Tier to announce that Nucor Corp. would build a $50
million steel plant in Chemung and create 300 jobs. Democrat Silver
left for the Jewish Passover celebrations that began at sundown.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the tentative agreement had appeared set after
legislative leaders agreed with the governor on a package to reform
New York's borrowing practices. The plan called for adoption of a
state constitutional amendment that would limit how much debt the
state could take on.
</P>
<P>
   But in drafting the language for the agreement, snags developed.
</P>
<P>
   ''You start and you stop. You start and you stop,'' state Senate
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, a Republican, told Albany's WROW-AM
radio.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, state lawmakers began what amounts to a 10-day
spring vacation. Despite not having completed work on the state
budget, they aren't due back at the state Capitol until May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of legislation adopted at the end of 1998, lawmakers
aren't getting their paychecks until the new budget is adopted.
Last year, the paycheck suspension lasted until Aug. 4 when the
budget was finally approved. The base salary for New York's
lawmakers is $79,500 a year, although most receive extra pay for
committee work or other duties. They get the paychecks they missed
once the new budget is approved. They missed their first checks on
Wednesday of last week because of the pay suspension law. Their
next payday is April 26.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving town, lawmakers passed a temporary bill to keep
state government operating and other checks flowing through April
30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-20-00 0014 </TRAILER>
