<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York's lieutenant governor divorced  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- After more than 15 years of marriage, Lt.
Gov. Mary Donohue and her second husband have divorced.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor's chief of staff, Eileen Long, said
Wednesday that the uncontested divorce was granted April 6 and was
based on an earlier separation agreement. Donohue's first marriage
also ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor and Troy attorney Brian Donohue have
been separated since January of last year when state police
responded to what they said was an emergency 911 call about ''an
active domestic dispute'' at the couple's rural Brunswick home
outside Troy. Police said the dispute had been resolved by the time
they arrived at the home.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor subsequently moved into a house in Troy
and is now renting a house in Brunswick. She has a 21-year-old
daughter from her first marriage and a 12-year-old son from her
second marriage. The Donohues share joint custody of their son.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Donohue and the future lieutenant governor met when they
were both students at Albany Law School. They were married in 1984,
a year after they graduated. Their fathers were both prominent
judges in Troy, which is just a few miles north of Albany and
across the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   The lieutenant governor is a former state Supreme Court justice
and former Rensselaer County district attorney. As district
attorney from 1993-96, Donohue made domestic violence a priority of
her office.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Donohue was selected by Pataki to become his running mate
after he had a very public falling out with then-Lt. Gov. Betsy
McCaughey Ross. McCaughey Ross eventually switched parties and
after losing a Democratic primary for governor in 1998 stayed in
the race against Pataki as the Liberal Party's candidate. Pataki
easily won re-election.
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey Ross is in the midst of divorce proceedings against
Wall Street financier Wilbur Ross. Her first marriage ended in
divorce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
