<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, April 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Appeals Court Keeps Elian in U.S. For Now
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Chastising the government for ignoring the wishes of a
6-year-old boy, a federal appeals panel on Wednesday ordered that Elian Gonzalez
must remain in the United States until the court decides whether he should get
an asylum hearing. The court action, extending an earlier stay granted by one of
the judges, marked the latest in a series of victories for Elian's Miami
relatives, who have been battling his Cuban father in an international
tug-of-war over the child. The order, however, does not prevent the government
from reuniting father and son in the United States.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gunman Kills One in Arizona
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. (AP) -- A man armed with a rifle and handguns walked into a
meeting at a retirement community recreation center and opened fire Wednesday,
killing one person and injuring four others. Police arrested Richard Glassel, a
former resident at Ventana Lakes community in suburban Phoenix. Neighbors and
witnesses said Glassel had past run-ins with the community association meeting
at the center and was known to berate other residents. Glassel was tackled and
subdued by people in the center when his gun jammed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Calls Memorial Site 'Sacred'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- On a day of sad memories, President Clinton today knelt
among 168 empty chairs memorializing each victim of the Oklahoma City bombing
and declared the site ''sacred ground'' in the soul of America. Five years after
the deadliest terrorist attack in U.S. history, Clinton helped dedicate the
Oklahoma City National Memorial at the site where a bomb ripped off the face of
the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building and killed 19 children and 149 men and
women.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
RJR To Test Reduced-Smoke Cigarette
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- R.J. Reynolds Tobacco will test-market a reduced-smoke
cigarette with advertising that for the first time claims it is safer than other
cigarettes. At its annual meeting Wednesday in Winston-Salem, N.C., the nation's
second-largest cigarette-maker called its Eclipse brand ''a cigarette that
responds to concerns about certain smoking-related illnesses.'' Eclipse, which
heats instead of burns the tobacco, lowers smokers' risk of cancer, chronic
bronchitis and possibly emphysema, according to the company's testing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
At Least 9 Columbine Suits Filed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- A police sharpshooter was refused permission to shoot
Columbine High School gunman Dylan Klebold through a library window during the
rampage, a lawsuit alleged Wednesday. A second lawsuit alleged one student was
killed by police gunfire. The lawsuits were among at least nine that have been
filed against the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department alleging deputies
mishandled the rescue and ignored advance warnings of the attack. The lawsuits
were filed one day before the anniversary of the April 20, 1999, attack in which
Klebold and Eric Harris killed 12 classmates and a teacher and wounded about two
dozen before they committed suicide.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Prison Population at New High
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of imprisoned American adults hit a record high
of 1.86 million, the Justice Department said today. With this latest increase of
nearly 60,000 prisoners, the United States may have matched or even surpassed
Russia as the country with the highest rate of incarceration. As of June 1999,
prisons and jails held 1,860,520 people, according to a Bureau of Justice
Statistics report. That's an increase of more than a million people since 1985,
when the figure was less 800,000.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Crash Follows Call for 737 Redesign
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAMAL, Philippines (AP) -- Wednesday's crash of an Air Philippines Boeing 737
comes days after a U.S. Federal Aviation Administration panel recommended
redesign of the rudder assembly of the jetliner. The 737 rudder system, which
controls left-right movement of the plane, came under close scrutiny after the
crash of USAir Flight 427 near Pittsburgh, Pa., in 1994, which killed all 132
people aboard. The Davao-city bound flight was carrying 131 passengers when it
crashed early Wednesday in what was the Philippines' worst air disaster.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP)-- The Nikkei, which was down some 85 points early in the session,
reversed into positive territory, gaining 81.72 points to points toe end the
morning session at 19,168.34.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senators 2, Maple Leafs 1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KANATA, Ontario (AP) -- Andreas Dackell scored twice as the Ottawa Senators
beat the Toronto Maple Leafs 2-1 Wednesday night to even their NHL playoff
series. Dackell scored his first two goals of the series on near-identical
2-on-1 breaks in the second and third periods. The first-round Eastern
Conference best-of-seven series is tied 2-2 heading into Game 5 in Toronto on
Saturday night.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
