<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> An Oddity in a Time of Prosperity  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CUNNIFF, AP Business Analyst
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In a profound irony, this happens to be National
Savings Month 2000, so declared by broker Merrill Lynch to raise
public awareness of the need to develop good financial habits.
</P>
<P>
   Need you be reminded it is the same month in which some small
investors lost their savings in the stock market? And the same
month, of course, in which many people had to borrow to pay their
taxes?
</P>
<P>
   It also used to be the month when Americans could feel relieved
of their tax burdens, having worked long enough and earned enough
to cover their federal, state and local tax liabilities for the
year.
</P>
<P>
   That latter pleasure is not, however, to be enjoyed in April
anymore, with the so-called Tax Freedom Day having been pushed back
all the way to mid-May, at least as the Tax Foundation calculates
it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the savings rate bobs just a bit above or below zero,
the latter rate being a consequence of borrowing rather than
saving. Your grandparents couldn't possibly understand it.
</P>
<P>
   The vital question for policy-makers and others involved in this
situation is whether it is a just a bad habit that must be
corrected -- or is it a sign of stress on the modern American's
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The bad-habit theorists contend that the problem goes way back
to childhood and poor parental training. Advertisers develop and
promote the habit, they say, and moneylenders make it possible.
</P>
<P>
   Plausible arguments can be developed to support such views, but
debaters can develop equally convincing positions that suggest
saving, not spending, is inborn or developed early in many people.
</P>
<P>
   The Merrill Lynch survey suggests there is some truth in this,
citing the findings in a study of 515 youngsters aged 12 to 17. It
showed 59 percent saved half of what they earned, either in jobs or
through allowances for duties performed, and spent the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Based on any standard, a 50 percent savings rate is quite good,
but teen-agers don't have the financial obligations of adults. They
aren't, for example, faced with the adult-size tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   Taxes now claim a greater share of the median two-income
family's taxes than the combined total of money spent on food,
clothing, housing and transportation -- all necessities.
</P>
<P>
   And the tax portion is rising. Nobody yet is making the claim
that it is in direct proportion to the slowdown in savings, but it
is probably only a matter of time before they do.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Tax Foundation studies, families in 1958 saved a
greater percentage of their incomes than in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier year, federal taxes accounted for 14.2 percent of
incomes, and state and local taxes 3.7 percent. And the savings
rate was 6.5 percent. In 1998, federal taxes represented 25.9
percent of incomes and state and local taxes were 13.1 percent. The
savings rate was under 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The comparability of such numbers is lessened by social changes.
Workers do save more now than before with contributions to Social
Security. And they have 401(k)s and corporate pension not included
in savings rates.
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard to deny taxes have something to do with the lack
of savings in conventional formats, and why, according to Merrill
Lynch, half of American families have less than $1,000 in net
savings and investments.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than bad habits or early training or some other cause,
the answer to that perplexing question of why Americans do not save
might be an inability to save, odd as that might seem in an age of
incredible wealth and prosperity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 0104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000420.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White Zimbabwe Farmers Feel Alone  </HEADLINE>
By RAVI NESSMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- With their president excoriating them
and the police unwilling to help, Zimbabwe's 4,000 white farmers
feel abandoned and nearly defenseless as the two-month occupation
of hundreds of their farms turns increasingly violent.
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe has called the occupations a legitimate
protest against the ownership of one-third of the country's
productive farmland by white farmers. He also has said that
Britain, the country's former colonial ruler, reneged on an
agreement to help pay for land reform in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, which pledged nearly $55 million for land reform at
independence, delivered nearly 90 percent of that money before
freezing the fund in 1990 when it said Zimbabwe violated the
agreement by forcing unwilling farmers to sell to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Violence on occupied farms throughout the country has flared in
recent days, with two farmers killed, at least six others badly
beaten and several farmhouses burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're scared. We've got nobody to look after us,'' farmer
Martin Pereira said. ''We are totally alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Worried about threats of violence on his farm 40 miles east of
Harare, Pereira, 52, and his wife, Jan, left their house Tuesday
night and sat in the bush for about an hour -- just to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no police. There's no support from the president at
all,'' said Pereira, whose farm has not been occupied. ''We just
have to trust in what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the leaders of the occupation promised to end the
violence, though not the occupations, after meeting with Mugabe and
farm leaders Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have agreed hostilities should cease and we should work
toward a solution,'' said Chenjerai Hunzvi, the militant leader of
a group of veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war, who are among
the squatters.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe blamed the farmers for provoking the violence and said
they behaved as ''enemies of Zimbabwe'' who tried to ''reverse our
revolution and our independence'' with their opposition to a failed
constitutional referendum that would have allowed the government to
seize their farms without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling party-dominated parliament subsequently passed the
law on its own.
</P>
<P>
   The courts have repeatedly ruled in favor of the farmers and
ordered the police to remove the squatters. But the police have
appealed those rulings, arguing that they do not have the resources
to carry them out and fear violence if they tried to evict the
armed men.
</P>
<P>
   Many farmers lost their remaining faith in the police after
militants on Saturday abducted five farmers, reportedly from a
police station. The farmers were later found alive, but badly
beaten. A sixth farmer who they had been trying to rescue was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers also reported that the scores of attackers armed with
Kalashnikov rifles who killed farmer Martin Olds on Tuesday were
allowed to drive through police roadblocks on their way to and from
his farm in western Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Farm union officials have advised farmers to evacuate their
wives and children from the western province of Matabeleland, where
Olds was killed, and the neighboring province of Midlands, David
Hasluck, director of the Commercial Farmers Union, said Wednesday.
Another 80 families remained evacuated from the Macheke area, where
the Saturday attack occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we can keep on like this. There's a limit to how
well you can run a farm when you can't get onto the farm,'' said
Hamish Turner of Mount Hampden, 10 miles northwest of Harare.
''Sooner or later you have to say, 'We can't do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 70,000 whites who make up 0.5 percent of Zimbabwe's
population, 20,000 are eligible for passports from Britain.
</P>
<P>
   But Pereira, who could get a passport because his father is
British, said it's nearly inconceivable that he would leave
Zimbabwe. ''I have a life here,'' he said. ''What can I do in
England? Live on the dole?''
</P>
<P>
   The farmers have rejected the use of weapons for fear that the
killing of a squatter could spark far greater violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's worse than the Wild West, frankly, because they can't
even defend themselves,'' said David Coltart, an official with the
opposition Movement for Democratic Change.
</P>
</TEXT>
