<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment in Calif. Decreasing  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG WILLIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- California's soaring economy has
reduced unemployment to its lowest level in 31 years and state
revenues are expected to be $10 billion greater than fiscal experts
estimated just a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But economists warn that California's good fortune is overly
dependent on the increasingly volatile stock market, and that the
extra revenue could evaporate if the ''new economy'' slows down
significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ''The concern is, when consolidation in e-commerce happens, when
there are shakeouts or that part of the economy slows down, income
tax revenues are going to mirror that trend as well, which could
sharply reduce revenues, or at least reduce revenue growth,'' said
Jean Ross, who directs the California Budget Project, a fiscal
watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   Economists raised similar warnings a decade earlier about
California's excessive dependence on the defense industry. When
post-Cold War military cutbacks finally hit in the early 1990s, the
impact rippled outward from aerospace and other defense-dependent
industries throughout the state's economy, eliminating jobs and
slashing earnings in construction, manufacturing and service
sectors as well.
</P>
<P>
   Other states' revenues also are increasingly dependent on
companies based in California, which would be the world's
seventh-largest economy if it were a nation, and is home to leading
Internet commerce, biotechnology, entertainment and communications
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a third of the estimated $36.3 billion the state will
collect this year in personal income taxes -- California's biggest
revenue source -- is tied to the stock market. That includes capital
gains on stock investments, employee bonuses and stock options,
venture capital investments and initial public offerings of stocks
which are cashed out.
</P>
<P>
   ''In recent years, capital gains have done nothing but go up,''
said Brad Williams, a senior economic forecaster for the state
Legislature. ''No other source of revenue has quadrupled in four
years, and they're almost all taxed at the highest marginal tax
rate, which is very key to the importance of capital gains in the
overall revenue picture.''
</P>
<P>
   The same phenomenon has occurred nationwide, but no other state
is as exposed as California.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent comparison, which doesn't reflect the state's
surge in tax revenues during the past 18 months, shows California
was 40 percent above the national average in the importance of
capital gains on state revenues, said Elizabeth Davis, senior
policy analyst at the Nelson A. Rockefeller Institute of Government
in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, capital gains accounted for just 8 percent of state
personal income tax receipts, $1.5 billion out of $18.6 billion,
compared to about 30 percent of personal income tax revenue this
year.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Nasdaq Stock Market's recent gyrations have had no
direct effect on state tax coffers, which are filling up from the
1999 gains. But a long bear market for the Nasdaq could lead to a
chill in investments, and ultimately cause the flow of capital
gains revenue to dry up.
</P>
<P>
   California has seen economic booms end suddenly before -- such as
10 years ago, when defense contracts were cut back and military
bases closed following the collapse of the Soviet Union and end of
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The moderate recession nationwide was a major economic
catastrophe in California. More than 400,000 Californians lost
their jobs, and those who kept them suffered as well.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment -- which is 4.6 percent today -- rose by two-thirds
to 10.1 percent statewide during the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a $10 billion deficit in a $50 billion operating
budget, the state increased sales, income, vehicle and other taxes,
doubled college fees and cut services from health care and welfare
grants to library hours.
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated $10 billion of the state's $84 billion in
total revenues this year coming from taxes on stock transactions,
California is as dependent on the rich continuing to get richer
today as it was on defense spending 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, political leaders of both parties have been
cautious about increasing the permanent level of state spending.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Leiser, executive director of UCLA's Anderson School
economic forecasting program, also urges caution in spending
increases, even though he forecasts the state economy to expand
through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''I take some encouragement from the fact that people seem to
have their eyes open,'' Leiser said. ''We haven't had a stock
market boom like this before, particularly one in which
California's role was so prominent. I think it's generally
recognized that this is a risky thing, that it's not long-term
money.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The California Legislative Analyst's publication ''2000-01
Budget: Perspectives and Issues'' can be found at
http://www.lao.ca.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
