<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fox, MSNBC Learn From CNN Troubles  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Fox News Channel and MSNBC began operating
within months of each other in 1996, at a time many people wondered
if there was room for one, much less two, networks to compete with
CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, CNN has yet to conquer its longtime bugaboo:
its failure to attract an audience consistently when there's no
big, breaking story. Viewership fell a precipitous 31 percent in
the first quarter of this year compared to the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's two news rivals have taken completely different lessons
from those problems and, after a few years of bitter competition,
are following separate paths.
</P>
<P>
   Fox senses a vulnerable CNN, and is attacking directly with
breaking news and political talk. Its ratings are steadily rising,
with prime-time talk shows ''The O'Reilly Factor'' and ''Hannity &AMP;
Colmes'' leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC believes it needs an identity separate from breaking news
and must bring in a younger audience. The network is producing
biographies, documentaries and reality programming that can air
repeatedly during slow periods.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're diverging in terms of strategy,'' said Erik
Sorenson, vice president and general manager of MSNBC. ''We're
definitely diverging in terms of audience.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN's average audience of 365,000 during the first quarter of
this year still dwarfed its rivals. MSNBC's average of 161,000
viewers was down 3 percent from 1999, while Fox News Channel had
135,000 viewers, an 11 percent increase. CNN is available in 78
million homes, MSNBC in 55 million and Fox in 47 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings for CNN have sunk partly due to the slow news period --
President Clinton's impeachment drama was ending during the same
period last year -- and because CNBC has eaten away at many of its
business-focused viewers during the day.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have the most audience so we have the most audience to lose
during slow news periods,'' CNN spokeswoman Christa Robinson said.
She noted that prime-time ratings are up since the last three
months of 1999, and that CNN has launched eight new programs in the
last year.
</P>
<P>
   In prime-time, Fox's audience is slightly bigger than MSNBC's.
But an MSNBC viewer is more likely to be younger than 55.
</P>
<P>
   John Moody, Fox News Channel's vice president for news, keeps
the three television sets in his office pointedly tuned to Fox
News, CNN -- and CNBC. People at Fox are fond of saying they don't
consider MSNBC competition anymore; their eyes are on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Despite CNN's 15-year head start, bigger staff and reputation as
the place the public will turn to in a crisis, Moody said Fox is
growing faster than CNN at a comparable point in its development.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have respect for what CNN does,'' he said. ''I don't scorn
them in any way. I think, though, that they are tired, they are not
innovative, and the innovations they have tried have not been
particularly successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox strives for a more flexible daytime schedule than its rivals
to respond to stories, and brags when it has beaten them -- if only
by seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're succeeding because we're sticking to news, we're
sticking to hard news,'' he said. ''We're sticking to topics that
people really want to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox has shown the most growth in the evening, when talk is king.
Political shows with Brit Hume and Bill O'Reilly have grown in the
ratings while similar fare on CNN and CNBC haven't.
</P>
<P>
   That's a savvy strategy, since Fox doesn't have nearly the
resources of CNN for covering news, said Ed Turner, a former CNN
executive. Fox's weakness is evident when a major story breaks
internationally, he said.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC's Sorenson commends Fox for the loyalty of its audience.
But he said he's not jealous.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I had Fox's audience pattern, I wouldn't be sitting here
right now,'' Sorenson said in an interview in his office. ''(NBC
President) Bob Wright and (NBC News President) Andy Lack would be
showing me the door.''
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC is after youth, because it's what advertisers crave and
provides opportunity for future growth.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising money has helped MSNBC turn a profit faster than it
expected, despite lackluster ratings. And it partly explains why
MSNBC's New Jersey office is filled with contractors, hurriedly
making room for new employees.
</P>
<P>
   The cable network has added 150 people in the past year, none
more important than Mike Cascio, who used to oversee the
''Biography'' series on A&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   Under Cascio's direction, MSNBC is churning out news
documentaries, like a two-hour look at airline safety dramatically
titled, ''Why Planes Crash.'' It has retrospectives on the Vietnam
and Persian Gulf wars in the works. A new series, ''Crime Files,''
will look back at dramatic criminal cases, and ''Missing'' will
focus on children and adults who are lost. The ''Today'' show's
Matt Lauer is host of a ''Biography''-like profile series.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenson sees the strong ratings that cable networks like
Discovery and VH1 get for non-fiction programming, and he wants
some of those numbers at MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to smooth out the traditional peaks and valleys in
cable news network ratings. ''I would rather not be held hostage by
waiting for the world to conspire to do something awful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to be CNN when there's big, breaking news,'' Sorenson
said. ''But we want to be Discovery and A&AMP;E when there's not a big,
breaking story.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger in this strategy was evident on the nights of the New
Hampshire and Super Tuesday presidential primaries this year. On
these competitive evenings for news networks, Fox had a bigger
audience than MSNBC, even though MSNBC had the entire NBC News team
at its disposal.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC runs the risk of clouding its image by trying to be
different things at different times.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've got to be careful they don't lose their news edge,''
Turner said. ''If you're calling yourself a news channel and have
that mantle, you better be damn sure you're doing news.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sorenson said the strategy is clear. ''No one's ever done
this before so there is understandably some discomfort. Will it
confuse the audience? Will they know to come to us for breaking
news? So far, they've been coming.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- David Bauder can be reached at
dbauder''at''ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
