<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boy readies for surgery to reconstruct ears  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- Doctors believe that one day Kenny
Willis will hear; but first they must give him ears.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old has Goldenhar's syndrome, a birth defect which
gained attention in the last decade after an alarming number of
Gulf War veterans' children were born with deformities.
</P>
<P>
   Where Kenny's left ear should be, he has a tiny flap of skin.
</P>
<P>
   ''This,'' he proclaims, ''is my baby ear.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of his head, he has cartilage, the framework
for an ear, but no opening to his eardrum.
</P>
<P>
   To hear, Kenny wears a headband device that vibrates his skull
and produces a distant, echoing sound similar to what an average
person hears underwater. When that doesn't work, he reads lips.
</P>
<P>
   But Kenny's parents, Lori Barringer and Timothy Willis Sr., want
their son to have plastic and reconstructive surgery. If the
surgeries are successful, Kenny could have hearing in at least one
ear.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists say it could take five to eight operations costing
as much as $125,000. Cigna, Kenny's insurance provider, vows to
cover all of the surgeons' bills, and most of the hospital bills.
Kenny's family must pay the $250 co-pays for his hospitalization
and follow-up care, along with thousands of dollars in travel
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The first procedure will be next month at the University of
Virginia Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Goldenhar's is marked by asymmetrical faces, receding jaws,
deformed palates, milky white cysts in the eyes and misshapen
organs. While an estimated five in every 100,000 children are born
with Goldenhar's, the rate in infants born to Gulf War veterans is
20 per 100,000, according to the Association for Birth Defect
Research for Children.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Mekdeci, founder of the association, believes there is
evidence linking Goldenhar's to exposure to certain toxic chemicals
and pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny's parents did not serve in the military, but Kenny's
mother wonders if paints and chemicals she used in her home before
she knew she was pregnant harmed him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I always tell him how proud I am that he's my boy,'' said
Willis, Kenny's dad. ''I try to concentrate on what he can do,
rather than what he can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny plays T-ball, after years of physical therapy improved his
muscle tone and coordination. His classmates at Osborne Hill School
in Fairfield have also embraced him. His teacher wears a microphone
around her neck to amplify her voice for Kenny.
</P>
<P>
   But Kenny's parents want the surgeries to ensure the boy will
remain comfortable as his classmates get older and become more
aware of his defects.
</P>
<P>
   ''Will they taunt him? Or tease him? Kids can be so cruel,''
Barringer said. ''If there is anything that I can do to improve his
life, I'm gonna do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Donations toward Kenny's medical expenses can be sent to The
Kenny Willis Fund, account number 9425262920 at Fleet Bank, 2574
East Main St., Bridgeport, CT 06610.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-20-00 0140 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000420.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge to rule on Peeler's motion to dismiss murder charge  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Lawyers for a man charged in the
killings of an 8-year-old witness and his mother are hoping a
change in the story of the state's star witness will be enough to
persuade a judge to dismiss the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler Jr., 28, faces the possibility of the death
penalty in the Jan. 7, 1999, slayings of Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr.
and his mother, Karen Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Peeler masterminded the killings to prevent the
boy from testifying against him in an earlier murder case. Peeler's
brother, Adrian, 25, is also charged in the murders, accused of
gunning down mother and son in their Bridgeport home.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Peeler's lawyers argued that the charges should be
dismissed because the state's key witness appears to have recanted
at least some of what she originally told police.
</P>
<P>
   In statements to police and in a videotaped deposition she gave
in November, Josephine Lee said she acted as a lookout and
witnessed the murders. But in December, she wrote a letter to her
lawyer, claiming she lied. At the same time, Lee wrote three
separate letters to Bridgeport police officers in which she
apologized for her role in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Superior Court Judge G. Sarsfield Ford
rejected defense requests for a mistrial, adjournment or
continuance in the case based on Lee's letter.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler's lawyers argued Wednesday that the charges should be
dismissed because the arrest warrant for Peeler was based largely
on Lee's version of events, which they claimed had changed
substantially in three earlier interviews with police.
</P>
<P>
   The judge who signed the arrest warrant did not know she had
given three inconsistent statements, Peeler's lawyers argued. They
said that her most recent statements -- in the letter to her lawyer
-- erode whatever probable cause originally existed to support
Peeler's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport State's Attorney Jonathan Benedict said Lee's varying
statements do not destroy the basis for the arrest warrant.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is complained of here is no more than a prior
inconsistent statement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said he would rule on the motion today, when jury selection
is scheduled to continue. Twelve regular jurors and five alternates
have been chosen. Ford has said he wants to pick one additional
alternate.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he will set a date today for when testimony will
begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-20-00 0140 </TRAILER>
