<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another New Milford police officer convicted of a serious crime  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW MILFORD, Conn. (AP) -- This has been a year of unwanted
''firsts'' for the police force in this small community: the first
Connecticut police officer ever tried for murder in the line of
duty and the first officer ever charged with negligent homicide in
the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks ago, former officer Scott Smith was convicted of
manslaughter for having fatally shot an unarmed suspect at
point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the police department suffered another blow when a
popular 14-year veteran of the police force was convicted on a
negligent homicide charge stemming from the June 1998 death of a
teen-ager whose car was struck by his speeding cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Arthur Peitler could not be reached for comment Wednesday
evening. Colin McCormack, the acting police chief, issued a brief
statement saying he feels sympathy for the victims of the cruiser
crash, but is not happy with the outcome of Officer William
Scribner's trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we as citizens are disappointed by the jury's decision
to convict Officer Scribner, we as members of a law enforcement
agency must respect and abide by our system of justice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The six-member jury deliberated for less than two days before
returning the verdict against Scribner, 39, of Bethel. He is
scheduled to be sentenced on June 14 and faces up to six months in
prison and a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, 17-year-old Angela D'Aquila, a girl known by many
town residents, was killed when Scribner's cruiser, its lights
flashing and siren screaming, raced through a New Milford
intersection and smashed into her car. Caroline LaVoie, 18, a
passenger in D'Aquila's car, suffered a collapsed lung, broken
ribs, a fractured clavicle and a sprained spine.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely been a long 2{ years,'' LaVoie said outside
Litchfield Superior Court where the trial was held. ''I think we're
all happy that this is done and over with and justice is served.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kelly, Scribner's attorney, said his client had hoped the
jury would recognize the officer was only doing his duty when the
accident occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here's a man with 14 years on the job, with an unblemished
record, legitimately responding to an emergency and a tragic
accident occurs and now he's convicted of a motor vehicle
offense,'' Kelly said. ''So he's very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Scribner was responding to a disturbance call when his cruiser
struck D'Aquila's car. Prosecutors conducted a yearlong
investigation and finally concluded that Scribner hadn't slowed
down before going through the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   The defense had maintained Scribner followed police procedure.
Scribner's attorney argued that D'Aquila caused the accident by
making an improper left turn into the path of the cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Karla Trombetto, a New Milford convenience store clerk, said her
customers were all discussing the case.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some feel one way, some feel the other, but they all have an
opinion,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Scribner turned down the state's offer to place him on a special
one-year probation, after which his record would have been wiped
clean. He remains free on a promise to appear pending sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is scheduled to be sentenced on May 5. This week,his
attorney filed a motion asking that his conviction be overturned
because the jurors acted improperly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-20-00 0141 </TRAILER>
