<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regulators set down rules for sale of nuclear plants  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Interested buyers can bid on Northeast
Utilities' Connecticut nuclear plants individually or as a group,
state regulators have ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Public Utility Control on Wednesday set
ground rules for the sale of the Millstone nuclear power plants, as
required under the electric deregulation law.
</P>
<P>
   NU subsidiary Connecticut Light &AMP; Power Co., the majority owner
of the plants, asked regulators to require all three plants to be
sold as a package, including Millstone Unit 1, which is being
decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
   New Haven-based United Illuminating Co.. which owns 3.7 percent
of Millstone 3, did not want Unit 1 included in the auction for
Unit 3.
</P>
<P>
   CL&AMP;P said a potential owner would prefer to control the entire
Waterford campus, instead of having sections owned by different
companies. CL&AMP;P also said a new owner could save money by operating
Unit 2 and Unit 3 together.
</P>
<P>
   The DPUC, however, ruled that buyers may see Unit 1 as a
detriment.
</P>
<P>
   ''The value of Millstone Unit 1 to prospective buyers is
uncertain. No decommissioned facilities have been sold in the U.S.;
therefore, there is no market that the Department can evaluate to
determine the value of the unit to prospective buyers,'' the DPUC
ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's ruling allows bidders to include Unit 1 if they
wish. The plant is owned by CL&AMP;P and the Western Massachusetts
Electric Co., another subsidiary of Berlin-based NU.
</P>
<P>
   Terrence McIntosh, a spokesman for NU, said the company accepted
the ruling despite its initial request that the units be sold
together.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just going to see what the market has to say about it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are designed to get the highest price for the plants,
while generating the lowest possible expense for ratepayers of
Connecticut Light &AMP; Power and United Illuminating.
</P>
<P>
   The DPUC also said it would review potential buyers' safety
record and ability to run nuclear plants, although the license to
operate the plants is issued by federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Northeast Utilities, the parent company of CL&AMP;P,
said Wednesday they were satisfied with the ruling. The Connecticut
Coalition Against Millstone, which has lobbied for the closure of
the Waterford complex, protested the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Burton, the group's lawyer, said the state's promise of a
safety review was meaningless because it did not set down specific
health or environmental standards.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without standards, there's nothing to measure up against,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1998 law, the plants must be auctioned by Jan. 1,
2004. Regulators and the plants' owners hope to complete a sale
well before then. A consultant will be hired to run the auction.
</P>
<P>
   The DPUC also decided that the sale of CL&AMP;P's interest in
Seabrook Station, a nuclear power plant in New Hampshire, should
not be included in the Connecticut auction.
</P>
<P>
   NU is working through a settlement with New Hampshire regulators
over their deregulation law. The DPUC said it does not want to hold
up the Connecticut sale while the New Hampshire issues are worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut attorney general and the Office of the Consumer
Counsel wanted to delay the auction until the Seabrook interest
could be included. They argued the Seabrook interest would be
attractive to bidders.
</P>
<P>
   ''Waiting to sell the plants probably would have meant a higher
price because the market for nuclear plants is improving as
deregulation is implemented,'' Attorney General Richard Blumenthal
said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency adopted additional protections for nuclear plant
workers when the plants are sold. The law requires new plant owners
to offer jobs to existing non-managerial workers at the same pay.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, CL&AMP;P got the DPUC to agree that a new owner must
offer to keep on employees for a year at comparable salaries and
benefits. Any workers laid off after that first year of new
ownership would get a help finding a new job and a $3,000 education
or training stipend.
</P>
<P>
   To address nuclear safety concerns, the DPUC agreed to have the
auction consultant screen bidders' safety records. Such information
will be considered when the DPUC reviews the winning bid for
approval.
</P>
<P>
   The new owner of the plants must get licenses from the U.S.
Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-20-00 0142 </TRAILER>
