<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Giuliani trade barbs over campaign donations, environment  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTINGTON, N.Y. (AP) -- On a day when polls showed Rudolph
Giuliani's approval rating at its lowest level ever, the Republican
senatorial candidate sparred with Democrat Hillary Rodham Clinton
over campaign financing and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's campaign issued press releases questioning Clinton's
environmental record, as well as fund-raising tactics, while the
first lady held a Long Island press conference where she sought to
deflect questions over returning a $22,000 campaign donation to a
woman with ties to a drug smuggler.
</P>
<P>
   A new Quinnipiac College Poll released Wednesday showed that
just 37 percent of New York City voters approve of Giuliani's
performance while 57 percent disapprove and six percent are
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The poll surveyed 816 registered voters and has a margin of
error of 3.4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's poll numbers have dropped over the past two years
from an approval rating of 74 percent in February 1998, shortly
after his November 1997 re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton brushed aside questions about Wednesday's poll, saying
''I'm only focusing on what I'm doing. ... I have a lot of work to
do to earn the trust and the vote of every New Yorker that I can
possibly reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, she sought to shift the focus of questions about her
campaign's refund of a questionable $22,000 donation by suggesting
that Giuliani give back $100,000 from a man she called ''the
biggest polluter in America.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the mayor's Washington-based Giuliani Victory
Committee, set up to accept soft money donations which legally
bypass federal fund raising restrictions, should return $100,000
from the Renco Group.
</P>
<P>
   Renco is run by Ira Rennert, who has caused an uproar on eastern
Long Island by building the largest house in the Hamptons -- a
100,000-square foot beachfront complex in Sagaponack that features
29 bedrooms, 40 bathrooms, two bowling alleys and a movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   Among Renco's holdings is the Utah-based Magnesium Corporation
of America, which was cited in a 1998 federal Environmental
Protection Agency report as the nation's top dumper of toxic
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just want him to answer a simple question: Is he going to
keep or is he going return $100,000 from the biggest polluter in
America,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Serafin, a spokeswoman for Giuliani's campaign, declined
comment, saying, ''The contribution was given to the NRSC and
you'll have to call them for comment.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the national Senate fund-raising committee,
Stuart Roy, said because it was a corporate contribution it was
immediately transferred from the Giuliani Victory Committee to the
NRSC. As for returning the money, Roy said, ''I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, another Giuliani campaign spokeswoman, Juleanna
Glover Weiss, noted that Rennert had been a visitor to the Clinton
White House and that he had donated $25,000 to the Democratic
National Committee in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really shouldn't surprise New Yorkers that Mrs. Clinton
will take any position, pander to every group, and cash any check
from any source in her quest to reinvent herself,'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton said a $22,000 check had been returned to
Vivian Mannerud, whose Airline Brokers Co. runs charter flights
between Cuba and Miami. Mannerud has been linked to Jorge Cabrera,
who in 1995 made a $20,000 contribution to the Democratic National
Committee from a bank account in which he kept profits from drug
trafficking. The DNC eventually returned that donation.
</P>
<P>
   Cabrera later pleaded guilty to smuggling 6,000 pounds of
cocaine into the United States and was sentenced to 19 years in
prison and fined $1.5 million. Mannerud was never charged with any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns also sparred over the environment, with Clinton
claiming that New York City was guilty of polluting the East River,
Long Island Sound and Jamaica Bay. Clinton also suggested that
Giuliani had been lax about protecting New York City's watershed in
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Clinton's environmental record consists of protecting
Tyson Chicken from government efforts to end its pollution of the
waterways in Clinton's home state of Arkansas,'' said Caroline
Nolan, another Giuliani campaign spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the Tyson accusations, Clinton said, ''I don't
recall being the mayor of Tyson chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said her former law firm had represented the chicken
company in Arkansas, but when she was asked if she was ever
personally involved in that litigation, she said: ''No, I wasn't.
You know this is 25 years ago. To the best of my memory, no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
