<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bombing Families Welcome Memorial  </HEADLINE>
By TIM TALLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- In the last remaining moments of daylight,
Glenna Rusch stood at the west end of a reflective pool taking
photographs of the Oklahoma City National Memorial
</P>
<P>
   Like hundreds of others, she seemed to be in no hurry to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been waiting to see the memorial ever since they started
building it,'' the Tulsa resident said Wednesday. ''It's amazing
how something so beautiful came out of something so tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   On the fifth anniversary of the bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah
Federal Building, 168 sculpted chairs sat filled with flowers and
other mementos as families of the victims made their way onto the
memorial site that marks the most deadly terrorist attack on
American soil.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will never forget our loved ones who died that day,'' said
Jeannine Gist, the mother of bombing victim Karen Gist Carr.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton walked with representatives of families,
survivors and rescuers through the 168 chairs, stopping to touch
the calm water of the reflecting pool that flows where a truck bomb
carved a crater into the street.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know there are still days when tears fill your eyes, when
you think your heart will surely break,'' Clinton said. ''On those
days in the future, I hope you can come here and find solace in the
memory of your loved ones, in the honor of your fellow citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope you can find the strength to live a full and loving
life, free of hatred, which only cripples.''
</P>
<P>
   Florence Rogers, former president of the Federal Employees
Credit Union, said the memorial proves ''that acts of terrorism
will not dampen the American spirit -- not in Oklahoma City, not
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   A bronze entrance gate inscribed with 9:01, the time just before
the blast, glowed in the evening sun as Clinton officially opened
the memorial by untying symbolic colored ribbons: white for
innocence, purple for courage, yellow for hope and blue for
statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, bells tolled at 9:02 a.m., the exact moment
when the fuel-and-fertilizer truck bomb exploded and stripped the
face from the building, turning its nine floors into a tomb of
concrete and steel.
</P>
<P>
   After the names of the victims were read, family members,
survivors and rescuers stepped through one of two golden gates
marking the entrance to the memorial. There were 149 big chairs for
the adult victims and 19 little ones for the children who died.
</P>
<P>
   Joyous music was carried on a gentle Oklahoma breeze as people
made their ways onto the site.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said she was thankful for the towering bronze gates that
stand at the memorial's entrances for ''telling the world why we
come here.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was thankful for the so-called Survivor Tree, an
American elm across the street from the federal building that
survived the bombing, ''for watching over this place and for being
the symbol of continuing life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who lost 18 employees in the blast, said she was most
thankful to have known the victims as well as survivors and rescue
workers who are honored by the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank you for the opportunity we had to know you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, appearing with Attorney General Janet Reno, called the
bombing an ''attack on all America and every American.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said Oklahoma City residents showed Americans ''how to
stand up to evil.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In the face of evil, an evil that staggers the soul, you've
demonstrated the triumph of the human spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Just blocks away, Terry Nichols sat isolated in an Oklahoma
County Jail cell awaiting an August preliminary hearing on 160
state counts of first-degree murder in the attack. Nichols and
Timothy McVeigh were convicted in federal court. McVeigh, who was
sentenced to death, is in a federal prison in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City National Memorial:
http://connections.oklahoman.net/memorial/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 0147 </TRAILER>
