<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Faces Challenge in Elian Case  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- April again is presenting Janet Reno with
tough choices now that a federal appeals court has dumped the
volatile issue of who should care for 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez
back into her lap.
</P>
<P>
   On her first April 19 as attorney general, in 1993, some 80
people died as the Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas,
burned after an FBI tear gas assault she ordered. Two years later
on the same date, two men angered by Waco bombed the Oklahoma City
federal building, killing 168 in the most deadly terrorist attack
in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Five years to the day later, Wednesday, Reno was en route to
Oklahoma City to help dedicate a memorial to the bombing victims
when the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ordered her Justice
Department to keep Elian in this country while it considers an
appeal by his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Justice will obey, Reno said. After all, the government and the
boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, already had offered to keep the
boy here until the court rules next month, even though Juan Miguel
came to the United States to take Elian home to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But the court in Atlanta ducked the separate issue of who has
custody of Elian in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   So now Reno must decide whether or when to use force to reunite
Elian and Juan Miguel at the risk of triggering violence by Cuban
exiles in Miami, where she grew up and served 15 years as an
elected prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Reno canceled a planned visit today to a Montana Indian
reservation so she could return to Washington for the Elian case.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court did offer its mediators to help settle the
dispute -- a new option that may attract an attorney general who
earlier Wednesday signaled her willingness to use force -- but only
as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Cuban exiles who fled to Miami from Fidel Castro are
the relatives who have cared for Elian since he was found in the
Atlantic last Thanksgiving. His mother had drowned when the boat on
which they escaped Cuba sank.
</P>
<P>
   Since last Thursday, those relatives have defied Reno's order to
return Elian to Juan Miguel. Earlier they spurned Reno's
face-to-face entreaties to turn over the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court order does not preclude me from placing Elian in his
father's care while he stays in the United States,'' Reno said,
promising to ''consider all our options.''
</P>
<P>
   She provided clues to her thinking earlier Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   She is ''dead set and determined'' to enforce immigration law
and reunite father and son ''the right way, the safest way, the
least violent way and the soonest way I possibly can under the
law,'' Reno told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was willing to use force to extract the boy from
his great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez's Miami home and hundreds of angry
Cuban exiles surrounding it but only ''when there is no other
alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, the 11th Circuit encouraged both sides to try
another peaceful alternative -- using its mediators.
</P>
<P>
   Mediators try to find common ground to reach voluntary
settlements, so Reno could accept them without the problem of
subordinating federal law that might be posed by arbitrators, who
decide cases. By agreeing to mediation, Reno would put the ball in
the relatives' court.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel's attorney, Gregory Craig, demanded Wednesday
afternoon that she act immediately to end Elian's stay in what
Craig and a pediatrician working for the government called an
abusive environment.
</P>
<P>
   She could do that now. A sketchy government plan calls for U.S.
marshals and immigration agents in minimum force and civilian
clothes, with no drawn guns, to go to the house to get Elian. But
the crowd of exiles motivated by hatred of Castro has vowed to form
a human chain to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   Reno could ask a federal court to reinforce her order to Lazaro
to give up the boy, but she already asked the three 11th Circuit
judges to do that and they declined to get into the question.
Justice officials say her order has the force of law anyway.
</P>
<P>
   She could just delay as she did when Lazaro refused to obey her
order to turn the boy over to immigration officers last Thursday.
She could hope that time or an appeals ruling in May changes the
atmosphere in Miami's streets or persuades Lazaro and his family to
negotiate a peaceful transfer.
</P>
<P>
   She bristled when a reporter asked if memory of the Waco deaths
had stayed her hand too long in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Waco, you had people who had killed federal officers and
who had injured others,'' Reno said. ''There's a lot of
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   She concluded: ''If the criticism of me is that I'm trying to
avoid that little boy being hurt or being snatched in a way that
can scar him further, I plead guilty. But at the same time ... I'm
going to enforce the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
