<DOCNO> APW20000420.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Set To Shell Out More Money  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN WILSON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Summer Olympic sports are due for a
sizable increase in their share of revenues from the Sydney Games,
with track and field again taking the biggest slice.
</P>
<P>
   The 28 sports federations represented on the program in Sydney
were to meet with International Olympic Committee leaders today to
find out how much money they will get from television and marketing
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1996 Atlanta Games, the federations -- then numbering 26
-- received $88.6 million from the IOC. This time, the figure will
be well over $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997-2000 period covering the Sydney Games has generated
more than $3.5 billion in revenues from television rights,
sponsorships and other marketing ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of the total goes to the Sydney organizing
committee, with the rest divided among the IOC, national Olympic
committees and sports federations.
</P>
<P>
   Not all sports are equal.
</P>
<P>
   For Atlanta, $56.6 million in TV revenue was divided equally
among the 26 sports. But $32 million in marketing funds was split
into four categories based on television ratings, ticket sales and
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The International Amateur Athletic Federation, track and field's
world governing body, was in the premier category and received
$8.675 million from the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball, soccer, gymnastics, swimming and volleyball were in
the second group, with each getting $4.675 million.
</P>
<P>
   The third bracket consisted of rowing, cycling, equestrian,
handball, tennis and field hockey. Each was given $3.175 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sports in the fourth and last tier got $2.675 million each. They
were badminton, baseball, boxing, canoeing, fencing, judo,
wrestling, modern pentathlon, sailing, softball, table tennis,
archery, shooting and weightlifting.
</P>
<P>
   Triathlon and taekwondo are the two new sports for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades, the Association of Summer Olympic Federations
(ASOIF) was led by Primo Nebiolo, the autocratic Italian who was
president of the IAAF.
</P>
<P>
   Nebiolo lobbied aggressively for more money for the federations
and particularly for track and field, considered the marquee sport
at the summer games. He described the IAAF's share from Atlanta as
''peanuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebiolo died last year. His elected successor as ASOIF
president, rowing federation president Dennis Oswald of
Switzerland, has taken a much more conciliatory approach in
negotiations with the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   According to Olympic sources, the increases for Sydney will
range from 56 percent for sports in the bottom group to 100 percent
or more for the IAAF.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the IOC announced that independent observers will
monitor drug testing during the Sydney Games in a move to eliminate
suspicions of coverups and faulty procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The observers will be appointed by the new World Anti-Doping
Agency to watch over the entire drug testing system during the
Sept. 15-Oct. 1 games.
</P>
<P>
   The observers will be present at all stages, including the
collection and analysis of urine samples and disciplinary hearings
for athletes who test positive.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first time that independent delegates will
observe testing at the Olympics. Until now, the IOC has been the
sole overseer of drug controls.
</P>
<P>
   ''Athletes want controls to be fair,'' said Jacques Rogge, vice
chairman of the IOC medical commission. ''They feel that doping
controls are generally not correct. They fear cover-ups. There is a
general suspicion among athletes and part of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC also promised to speed procedures to introduce blood
tests in Sydney if a reliable method for detecting the banned
endurance-boosting hormone EPO is developed.
</P>
<P>
   Australian researchers have told the IOC they can produce a
reliable test by early July. If that's the case, there could still
be enough time to complete scientific and legal validation of the
test before the start of the games.
</P>
<P>
   ''The odds are 50-50 we'll have an EPO test for Sydney,'' Rogge
said. ''It's a race against time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
