<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs, Hornets Clinch Homecourt  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS SHERIDAN, AP Basketball Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs and Charlotte Hornets will open the
playoffs at home, and the Detroit Pistons will get the postseason
matchup they wanted -- Miami rather than Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, Hornets and Pistons were among the few teams with
something to gain on the final night of the regular season, and all
of them did.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio overcame a 17-point fourth quarter deficit to beat
the Los Angeles Lakers 103-98 in overtime despite the absence of
Tim Duncan. The defending champions will open the best-of-five
first round at the Alamodome against the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets also needed a victory to clinch homecourt advantage
for their series against Philadelphia, and the Hornets got it by
defeating the Miami Heat 83-73.
</P>
<P>
   It was Charlotte's 30th home win of the season against 11
losses, and coach Paul Silas said he hoped to continue that
dominance in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not too many teams won 30 games at home this year,'' he said.
''Getting the homecourt advantage is good, but you still have to
play. We've got to maintain a homecourt edge that we have right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons needed only to beat the Chicago Bulls to lock up the
seventh seed, and they did it with ease, 112-91.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what we wanted -- a trip to Miami,'' said Jerry
Stackhouse, who led Detroit with 21 points and seven assists.
''We've got some guys who are banged up, and they will feel a lot
better hanging out in the sun than in the cold. Hopefully, that
will be enough to give us a lot of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit (42-40) went 2-2 against Miami and 1-3 against
top-seeded Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons wanted the matchup with Miami because Heat point
guard Tim Hardaway is expected to miss the series with a foot
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we can start concentrating on Miami,'' Pistons coach
George Irvine said. ''That's a great team. You have to focus on
Alonzo (Mourning), but I respect the whole team. Their bench can do
a lot of damage.''
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs begin Saturday with Heat-Pistons, SuperSonics-Jazz,
Suns-Spurs and 76ers-Hornets. Sunday's games are Lakers-Kings,
Trail Blazers-Timberwolves, Pacers-Bucks and Knicks-Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   None of the statistical races was up for grabs on the final
night.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal won the scoring title going away over Allen
Iverson of Philadelphia, finishing with a 29.7 average to Iverson's
28.4. The two had been neck-and-neck in the scoring race through
March, but Iverson's production was limited over the last several
games by foot and elbow injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carter scored only 13 points in Toronto's game at Orlando
to drop from third in the scoring race to fourth -- one-tenth of a
point behind Detroit's Grant Hill's 25.8 average.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Hornacek of Utah finish with the third-highest free-throw
percentage in league history behind Calvin Murphy's .958 in 1980-81
and Mahmoud Abdul-Rauf's .956 in 1993-94, going 3-for-3 against
Sacramento to finish 171-for-180 (95.0 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Davis of Dallas did not attempt a 3-pointer in the
Mavericks' final game and finished with a league-leading percentage
of .491.
</P>
<P>
   Dikembe Mutombo of Atlanta won his first career rebounding
title, while Jason Kidd led the league in assists, Eddie Jones in
steals and Alonzo Mourning in blocks.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, Charles Barkley made one last appearance for the
Rockets and had two points, one rebound, one assist and a blocked
shot in six first-half minutes. He suffered what was thought to be
a career-ending knee injury in early December, but recovered
quickly enough to go out on his own terms -- standing up rather than
being carried off the court.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a sad day for me, I've been playing basketball since I
was nine years old and now I'm not going to be playing anymore,''
Barkley said.''
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to the sidelines for the second half, a fluffy
recliner awaited him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
