<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Nations Urged To Pressure Iraq  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan has urged
Arab countries to keep up pressure on Iraq to account for the 605
Kuwaitis missing since Baghdad invaded the small state in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The recent exchanges of Iraqi and Iranian prisoners of war
''gives a beam of hope that similar developments may happen in
regard to those missing in the aftermath of the Gulf War,'' Annan
said Wednesday in a report to the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   The report was Annan's first since he appointed a special
coordinator on the issue, former Russian Ambassador Yuli Vorontsov,
in February to try to energize efforts to account for the missing.
</P>
<P>
   Vorontsov visited Kuwait this month and met with families of the
605 people still missing from Iraq's seven-month occupation. Iraq
has not responded to Vorontsov's requests to visit.
</P>
<P>
   Baghdad maintains that it has released all war prisoners, but
lost track of 127 in an uprising after the war. It has withdrawn
from an international committee looking into the issue, accusing
Kuwait of failing to account for 1,150 missing Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait says it has received case files on only 70 Iraqis and is
investigating those, even though the government does not consider
itself legally responsible for Iraqis who disappeared while Kuwait
was under occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Annan noted that Arab officials told Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein ''that progress in solving the issue of Kuwaiti missing
persons would improve Iraq's stance in the world and, in
particular, ameliorate the political climate among the Arab
states.''
</P>
<P>
   In his report, Annan urged the Arab states to ''continue through
all available channels their efforts aimed at the speediest
resolution of the humanitarian issue of missing persons.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan also said Wednesday that he had urged Iraqi officials to
meet with the new chief weapons inspector, but they refused, saying
it would signal acceptance of a U.N. plan to resume arms searches.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general said he raised the issue during talks last
week with Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahaf in Havana,
where both were attending a summit of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   Annan noted that Iraq has ''rejected'' the December resolution
creating the new weapons inspection agency, headed by Hans Blix of
Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. weapons inspectors left Iraq in December 1998 ahead of U.S.
and British airstrikes, launched to punish Iraq for failing to
cooperate with the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Top Iraqi officials have said Baghdad would not accept new U.N.
weapons searches, but others have left open the possibility of
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council created the U.N. Monitoring, Verification
and Inspection Commission to replace the U.N. Special Commission,
which was tarnished by allegations that its inspectors spied on
Iraq on behalf of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Special Commission had been verifying the destruction of
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction. Sanctions imposed after Iraq
invaded Kuwait cannot be lifted until Iraq is reported free of its
banned weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 0159 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000420.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, April 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reno Takes Center Stage in Elian Saga
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- For the first time in days, the next step in the Elian Gonzalez
custody dispute belongs to Attorney General Janet Reno. In the latest victory
for Miami relatives of the 6-year-old boy, a three-judge panel of the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals said Elian must remain in the United States until the
court decides whether he should get an asylum hearing. The order, however, does
not prevent the government from reuniting Elian with his father in the United
States. The father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, has been waiting in Washington since
April 6.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Italy Set for New Leadership
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Emboldened by gains in local races and eager to parlay those
victories into national power, Italy's conservative opposition is pushing for
early elections now that Premier Massimo D'Alema has quit. The decision belongs
to President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, who accepted D'Alema's resignation Wednesday.
Ciampi, however, has said he wants a May 21 referendum on changing the electoral
system to go forward. Since a national election would block the referendum,
Ciampi is expected to search instead for a new premier. The president plans to
spend Thursday and Friday consulting with Italy's political leaders.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gunman Kills One in Arizona
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. (AP) -- A man armed with a rifle and handguns walked into a
meeting at a retirement community recreation center and opened fire Wednesday,
killing one person and injuring four others. Police arrested Richard Glassel, a
former resident at Ventana Lakes community in suburban Phoenix. Neighbors and
witnesses said Glassel had past run-ins with the community association meeting
at the center and was known to berate other residents. Glassel was tackled and
subdued by people in the center when his gun jammed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Calls Memorial Site 'Sacred'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- On a day of sad memories, President Clinton today knelt
among 168 empty chairs memorializing each victim of the Oklahoma City bombing
and declared the site ''sacred ground'' in the soul of America. Five years after
the deadliest terrorist attack in U.S. history, Clinton helped dedicate the
Oklahoma City National Memorial at the site where a bomb ripped off the face of
the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building and killed 19 children and 149 men and
women.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
RJR To Test Reduced-Smoke Cigarette
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- R.J. Reynolds Tobacco will test-market a reduced-smoke
cigarette with advertising that for the first time claims it is safer than other
cigarettes. At its annual meeting Wednesday in Winston-Salem, N.C., the nation's
second-largest cigarette-maker called its Eclipse brand ''a cigarette that
responds to concerns about certain smoking-related illnesses.'' Eclipse, which
heats instead of burns the tobacco, lowers smokers' risk of cancer, chronic
bronchitis and possibly emphysema, according to the company's testing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
At Least 9 Columbine Suits Filed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- A police sharpshooter was refused permission to shoot
Columbine High School gunman Dylan Klebold through a library window during the
rampage, a lawsuit alleged Wednesday. A second lawsuit alleged one student was
killed by police gunfire. The lawsuits were among at least nine that have been
filed against the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department alleging deputies
mishandled the rescue and ignored advance warnings of the attack. The lawsuits
were filed one day before the anniversary of the April 20, 1999, attack in which
Klebold and Eric Harris killed 12 classmates and a teacher and wounded about two
dozen before they committed suicide.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Prison Population at New High
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of imprisoned American adults hit a record high
of 1.86 million, the Justice Department said today. With this latest increase of
nearly 60,000 prisoners, the United States may have matched or even surpassed
Russia as the country with the highest rate of incarceration. As of June 1999,
prisons and jails held 1,860,520 people, according to a Bureau of Justice
Statistics report. That's an increase of more than a million people since 1985,
when the figure was less 800,000.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP)-- The Nikkei, which was down some 85 points early in the session,
reversed into positive territory, gaining 81.72 points to points toe end the
morning session at 19,168.34.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Capitals 3, Penguins 2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rookie Jeff Halpern scored the game-winning goal on a
rebound with 7:05 remaining -- on a power play resulting from Ron Tugnutt's
careless slashing penalty -- as the Washington Capitals prevented a series sweep
with a 3-2 victory over the Pittsburgh Penguins on Wednesday night. Washington
overcame two disallowed goals and numerous other missed rebound chances
resulting from Tugnutt's near inability to make clean saves.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
