<HEADLINE> Black DAR Member Challenges Efforts  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A black member of the Daughters of the
American Revolution says the organization has reneged on an
agreement she made with it nearly 16 years ago to document black
veterans of the Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here it is, 16 years and they haven't finished the job,'' Lena
Santos Ferguson said as the DAR opened its annual ''Continental
Congress'' in the capital this week.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson and the organization agreed that the DAR would complete
research on black veterans of the Revolution when she joined in
1984. The DAR was supposed to identify the estimated 5,000 black
American soldiers who served during the war but it has identified
less than 30 percent of them, said Maurice A. Barboza, Ferguson's
nephew and spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The DAR said it was working on bringing about greater awareness
of black contributions to the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although the publication project is still ongoing, the
National Society of the DAR has genuinely attempted and continues
to promote the awareness of the contributions of black patriots,''
DAR lawyer Christine Kearns said. ''The NSDAR has met each and
every one of its commitments to Ms. Ferguson.''
</P>
<P>
   The DAR has published nine booklets on the military service of
blacks in the revolution. A tenth, covering the state of
Pennsylvania, goes to print soon, and one will be completed soon on
New York state, Kearns said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1890, the DAR brings together women whose ancestors
served in or helped George Washington's army win independence from
Britain more than a century earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The British also used black troops, recruited with a promise of
the freedom they only won in the United States in 1865.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, a retired parochial school administrator from
Washington, was denied membership when she first tried to join in
1980 and says it was because she is black.
</P>
<P>
   Her great great great great grandfather -- ''four greats,'' she
says -- was Jonah Gay, who died in 1795, a member of the Committee
of Correspondence in Meduncook, Maine. These committees kept up
contacts before the Revolution among resisters to British rule.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was white -- my grandfather was white,'' she said in an
interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   She was admitted to the DAR after media reports of her failed
attempts to join the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The DAR has 172,000 members, but officials say they do not know
how many are black. Applications for membership have no question
about a candidate's race, said Mary Ann Wright of the DAR
Development Department. Officials noted that black members took
part in this week's Congress and call Ferguson a ''valued'' member.
</P>
<P>
   The DAR's headquarters near the White House includes a museum, a
genealogical library and Constitution Hall, where the current
meeting is taking place.
</P>
<P>
   In 1939 the DAR refused to let contralto Marian Anderson sing in
Constitution Hall because she was black. First lady Eleanor
Roosevelt resigned from the organization in protest and Anderson
gave her recital to an audience of 75,000 at the Lincoln Memorial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
