<HEADLINE> Panel: US Needs New Security Plan  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Changes in U.S. security strategy are needed
to prepare America for new threats in the 21st Century, an
independent advisory panel told the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   ''Americans are far less secure today than they believe
themselves to be,'' former Sen. Warren Rudman of New Hampshire,
co-chair of the U.S. Commission on National Security, said in
releasing the report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It said U.S. forces need to be able to deploy quickly and be
able to handle missions ranging from humanitarian assistance and
disaster relief to major wars.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the Pentagon strategy for fighting two wars at
once, such as in the Persian Gulf and in Korea, is outdated and
leaves America unready to deal with those '''varied and complex
contingencies now occurring and likely to increase in the years
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The world is changing fast and if the U.S. government does not
change with it, it may find itself forced into one bewildered
reaction after another,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ''America must not exhaust itself by limitless commitments,''
the report said. In particular, the United States must use ''a
finer calculus'' to decide whether the benefits of military
intervention abroad make the action worth it, it said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's defense policy has been under
attack in Congress from those who feel that the increasing use of
U.S. troops on overseas humanitarian or peace-keeping missions has
sapped the military's readiness for waging war.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the United States needs:
</P>
<P>
   --Nuclear capabilities to deter and protect the United States and
its allies from attack.
</P>
<P>
   --Conventional forces for major wars.
</P>
<P>
   --Rapidly deployable, lighter forces for smaller conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   --A homeland security force.
</P>
<P>
   --Units trained for peacekeeping and humanitarian missions.
</P>
<P>
   The report is the second in a three-phase study on security for
the 21st century. Last year the commission outlined a vision of the
future and next year it is to give specific recommendations on how
U.S. security structures should be changed to meet future needs.
</P>
<P>
   Established by Congress in 1998, the panel also includes former
senator Gary Hart of Colorado, former Defense Secretary James
Schlesinger, former U.N. Ambassador Andrew Young and retired Army
Gen. John Galvin.
</P>
<P>
   They made several dozen policy suggestions, including that the
United States make nonproliferation of weapons a high priority,
strengthen cooperation with other nations against terrorism, build
a domestic defense against missile attacks and draw other nations,
especially China, Russia and India, more into the ''mainstream of
the emerging international system.''
</P>
<P>
   On the home front, the report said the nation ''must make it a
national priority to improve the quality of primary and secondary
education, particularly in mathematics and the sciences.'' And the
National Guard must be trained and equipped to assume ''a
significant role in defending the homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The strategy outlined here ... differs from the strategic
habit of the past half-century,'' the commission concluded. ''It
attempts to clarify U.S. strategy and purposes and to match them
with a prudent sense of limits.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. Commission on National Security site:
http://www.nssg.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
