Italy Set for New Leadership
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ROME (AP) -- Emboldened by gains in local races and eager to parlay those
victories into national power, Italy's conservative opposition is pushing for
early elections now that Premier Massimo D'Alema has quit. The decision belongs
to President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, who accepted D'Alema's resignation Wednesday.
Ciampi, however, has said he wants a May 21 referendum on changing the electoral
system to go forward. Since a national election would block the referendum,
Ciampi is expected to search instead for a new premier. The president plans to
spend Thursday and Friday consulting with Italy's political leaders.
</P>
