</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- On a day of sad memories, President Clinton today
knelt among 168 empty chairs memorializing each victim of the Oklahoma City
bombing and declared the site "sacred ground" in the soul of America. Five years
after the deadliest terrorist attack in U.S. history, Clinton helped dedicate
the Oklahoma City National Memorial at the site where a bomb ripped off the face
of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building and killed 19 children and 149 men and
women.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
RJR To Test Reduced-Smoke Cigarette
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- R.J. Reynolds Tobacco will test-market a reduced-smoke
cigarette with advertising that for the first time claims it is safer than other
cigarettes. At its annual meeting Wednesday in Winston-Salem, N.C., the nation's
second-largest cigarette-maker called its Eclipse brand "a cigarette that
responds to concerns about certain smoking-related illnesses." Eclipse, which
heats instead of burns the tobacco, lowers smokers' risk of cancer, chronic
bronchitis and possibly emphysema, according to the company's testing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
At Least 9 Columbine Suits Filed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- A police sharpshooter was refused permission to shoot
Columbine High School gunman Dylan Klebold through a library window during the
rampage, a lawsuit alleged Wednesday. A second lawsuit alleged one student was
killed by police gunfire. The lawsuits were among at least nine that have been
filed against the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department alleging deputies
mishandled the rescue and ignored advance warnings of the attack. The lawsuits
were filed one day before the anniversary of the April 20, 1999, attack in which
Klebold and Eric Harris killed 12 classmates and a teacher and wounded about two
dozen before they committed suicide.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Prison Population at New High
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of imprisoned American adults hit a record
high of 1.86 million, the Justice Department said today. With this latest
increase of nearly 60,000 prisoners, the United States may have matched or even
surpassed Russia as the country with the highest rate of incarceration. As of
June 1999, prisons and jails held 1,860,520 people, according to a Bureau of
Justice Statistics report. That's an increase of more than a million people
since 1985, when the figure was less 800,000.
</P>
