<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 09:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tremor shakes parts of upstate New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWCOMB, N.Y. (AP) -- A strongest earthquake in years shook life
in parts of eastern New York from the Adirondacks to the Mohawk
Valley this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was incredible,'' said John Alden of the Adirondack town of
Indian Lake. ''It scared the hell out of me. At first I thought it
was a logging truck, but then the whole building started shaking.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was like being next to a shuttle launch,'' said Alden, who
used to live in Florida not far from the launch site. He was at his
computer working before his Snowy Mountain Inn restaurant opened
when the quake hit. In eight to 10 seconds, he leaped to his feet
and ran outside because he feared the furnace below him was about
to explode. Yet he sees no damage to his home or business.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries or major damage was reported in the quake that was
greater than usually felt in upstate New York. Aftershocks today
are possible, a researcher said.
</P>
<P>
   The tremor was recorded at about 4:45 a.m., with the epicenter
in the town of Newcomb in Essex County, about 95 miles north of
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The quake shook homes in an area stretching from northern New
York to Fulton and Montgomery counties along the Mohawk River and
counties around Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents say the quake was strong enough to crack wall
paint and shake items off shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The National Earthquake Information Center says the quake that
measured 3.7. A researcher at the State University of New York at
Potsdam said earthquakes in this area between 2.0 and 4.0 are
common and happen about 10 or 12 times a year. A magnitude of 4.0
can cause moderate damage and 5.0 can cause considerable damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is pretty normal,'' said Frank Revetta, a geophysicist
and professor and director of the Seismic Network at the State
University of New York at Potsdam 63 miles northwest of the
epicenter.
</P>
<P>
   His initial recordings show a quake with a magnitude of 3.7 to
4.2 centered in the central Adirondacks near Long Lake and Saranac
Lake, one of the areas that attracts the most tourists in warmer
months.
</P>
<P>
   Revetta said an earthquake with a magnitude of 5.2 was recorded
in northern New York in October 1983. Today's quake appears to have
been the strongest in several years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said what would probably be minor aftershocks are possible
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
