<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teen son charged in father's death after shallow grave uncovered  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   VASS, N.C. (AP) -- Results of an autopsy on a man authorities
believe was killed by his teen-age son and buried in a shallow
grave for two years are expected next week, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The Moore County Sheriff's Department on Friday unearthed Paul
Purvis' body from a grave behind a camper where his family lived.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death will help determine the severity of the
murder charge brought against William Purvis, said assistant
district attorney Alan Greene.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators first tried to find Paul Purvis in January 1999
after his wife, Elizabeth McCracken, shot herself at the home. They
were suspicious and searched the isolated, wooded 25-acre property
near Vass for his body, but found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   William Purvis was charged Monday in New Jersey with killing his
father in April 1998. He is confined to a youth detention center in
Monmouth County, N.J., while authorities in North Carolina seek
extradition.
</P>
<P>
   The boy and his sister have lived with their grandmother in New
Jersey since their mother's death.
</P>
<P>
   McCracken shot herself in the chest with a handgun on New Year's
Eve 1998 while talking to a friend on the phone. Investigators said
the gun she used was the same one that killed Purvis, but that they
have no reason to reexamine McCracken's suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Purvis and McCracken moved their family to Vass around 1997
after pleading guilty in New Jersey to possession and distribution
of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Colts Neck, N.J., who found the plants in a backyard
garden in 1991, also accused the couple of endangering the welfare
of children. Investigators found animal feces throughout the house,
which contained 21 dogs, seven parrots and rats.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said McCracken had inherited a large amount of money and
that neither she nor her husband worked. The couple raised
Australian terriers and traveled around the country for dog shows.
</P>
<P>
   Marge Reignier, a friend and fellow breeder from Green Bay,
Wisc., said McCracken told her Purvis had abandoned the family in
April 1998. Reignier said she was suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew it wasn't like him,'' she said, adding that she thinks
McCracken knew her husband was dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
