<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 17; Nasdaq Off 7  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today, with
blue-chips getting a lift from the string of strong first-quarter
earnings that have come out this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 17.07 at 10,692.03.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 3.30 at 1,430.77, but the
Nasdaq composite index was down 7.01 at 3,699.40.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the focus was on earnings reports. Companies are
nearing the peak of the reporting season, and most companies have
reported strong profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   United Parcel Service gained 2 11/16 to 61} after the company
reported earnings that topped expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce One, which provides electronic-commerce software and
services, rose 8 13/32 to 56[, also on better-than-expected
results.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were lingering concerns about whether the economy
is growing too fast.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department reported today that unemployment benefits
plummeted last week to the lowest level in nearly 27 years,
indicating that businesses are scrambling to find workers.
</P>
<P>
   There have been concerns that the tight labor market will spur
higher inflation because employers have to recruit workers with big
increases in wages and benefits, increasing costs that companies
could pass along to consumers in the form of higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve policy-makers, fearful that too-rapid economic
growth could revive, have raised interest rates five times since
June. Many investors worry that continued signs of brisk growth
will spur the Fed to raise rates a number of times more this year.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 142.72 million shares
in the early going, up from Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was expected to slow as the day progressed ahead of the
holiday weekend. Financial markets will be closed Friday for the
observance of Good Friday, and bond markets close early this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 1.35 at 487.58.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.66 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.59 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.85 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
