<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine TV Restraint Sought  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With the wounds still fresh for many victims and
their families, television networks returned to Colorado today to
mark the first anniversary of the massacre at Columbine High
School.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the community had pleaded with the media to show
restraint, and producers of this morning's news shows said they
tried to weigh the need for compassion with the need to cover the
story.
</P>
<P>
   After some debate, NBC's ''Today'' show producers sent Katie
Couric to anchor the show today from Littleton, Colo., this
morning. CBS's ''The Early Show'' sent co-host Jane Clayson.
</P>
<P>
   But ABC's ''Good Morning America,'' which sent Charles Gibson to
Oklahoma City on Wednesday for the fifth anniversary of the federal
building bombing, decided not to send an anchor to Columbine. It
did have a reporter on the scene for stories.
</P>
<P>
   Clayson interviewed attorneys who alleged, in a lawsuit, that
one of Columbine's victims was killed by a law enforcement
officer's bullet. Couric did five Columbine segments, including one
where she revisited last year's emotional interview with the
parents of a victim.
</P>
<P>
   Parents of some of the Columbine victims told the media that
some of their stories would be painful. Students and school
officials in Littleton, Colo., had asked that cameras and all
outsiders be kept away from Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a lot of sensitivity and a lot of care and concern
for these families from this show,'' said Shelley Ross, executive
producer of ''Good Morning America.'' ''These are tough decisions
to make. I'm sure there are a lot of people who just wish we would
go away.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials in Littleton persuaded a homeowner near
Columbine not to allow ''Good Morning America'' to set up a camera
on his property. Ross said she didn't know about the request.
</P>
<P>
   CNN is ''not trying to wallow in what happened a year ago'' and
decided against a prime-time special on the anniversary, said Sid
Bedingfield, executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   But the network is airing an interview with shooting survivor
Patrick Ireland and will include the wrenching footage of his
bloody escape through a school window.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today'' show decided to send Couric after debating whether to
go, said Jeff Zucker, executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We decided that we could be both respectful of the day and the
people and still be there,'' Zucker said. ''This is probably the
story that has gripped the country the most within the past year.
So it's important to take another look at what has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS won't speak to anyone who doesn't want to be on camera, but
it can't ignore the story, said Marcy McGinnis, the network's vice
president of news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Networks also had to decide how much file footage of the
massacre to show. Fox News Channel, for example, will show
terrified children fleeing the school but won't air footage with
bodies, said Alicia Acuna, a correspondent based in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of difficult to mark an anniversary without showing
what it is you're marking,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS sorted through its footage to determine what to show,
McGinnis said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In television, the way you tell a story is with pictures,''
she said. ''I know it brings back a lot of memories, but we're in a
medium that is picture-oriented.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 1035 </TRAILER>
