<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All-Century Baseball Stamps Near  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Now pitching, Cy Young. Babe Ruth is at bat
with Jackie Robinson on deck followed by Honus Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   That could be the lineup for baseball fans as the U.S. Postal
Service issues a new set of 20 stamps remembering players honored
on Major League Baseball's All-Century Team.
</P>
<P>
   The stamps will be unveiled May 4 at Busch Stadium in St. Louis
and will go on sale July 6 as part of baseball's all-star
festivities in Atlanta. They will be available nationwide starting
July 7.
</P>
<P>
   The post office plans to print 200 million of the self-adhesive
33-cent stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the set are stamps honoring:
</P>
<P>
   --Roberto Clemente, who helped the Pittsburgh Pirates to two
world championships and became the first Hispanic elected to the
baseball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   --Ty Cobb, the ''Georgia Peach,'' who won nine straight American
league batting titles in his 24-year career, 22 with the Detroit
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   --Mickey Cochrane sparked the Philadelphia Athletics'
championship teams of 1929-1931 with his bat and skill behind the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   --Eddie ''Cocky'' Collins played for 25 seasons, a 20th century
record for nonpitchers. His baserunning and batting helped four
teams win world championships.
</P>
<P>
   --Dizzy Dean, fastball-throwing member of the St. Louis
Cardinals' Gas House Gang, once held the modern single-game record
of 17 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   --Jimmie Foxx, one of the top sluggers of all time, hit 30 or
more home runs for 12 seasons in a row. Playing for the
Philadelphia Athletics in 1933, he led the American League in home
runs, batting and RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   --Lou Gehrig, first baseman for the New York Yankees, played in
2,130 consecutive games. In 1934 the ''Iron Horse'' led the
American League in batting average, home runs and RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   --Josh Gibson was among the biggest draws in the Negro leagues
and is generally considered one of the most prodigious power
hitters in the history of professional baseball.
</P>
<P>
   --Lefty Grove, one of the finest left-handed pitchers in history,
went 31-4 for the 1931 Philadelphia Athletics. In the process, he
put together a 16-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   --Rogers Hornsby won seven batting championships and managed the
1926 St. Louis Cardinals to their first world championship.
</P>
<P>
   --Walter ''Big Train'' Johnson used a sweeping sidearm motion to
fire fastballs over home plate. In 21 years with the Washington
Senators he fanned 3,509 batters, won 417 games and pitched a
record 110 shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   --Christy Mathewson won 20 games for the New York Giants in 1901.
With his ''fadeaway'' pitch, he posted three consecutive 30-victory
seasons and in the 1905 World Series threw three shutouts in only
six days.
</P>
<P>
   --Satchel Paige, a legend after two decades in the Negro leagues,
signed with the Cleveland Indians in 1948. At age 42, this
''veteran-rookie'' helped his team win the American League pennant.
</P>
<P>
   --Jackie Robinson broke the major league color barrier when he
came to the Brooklyn Dodgers in 1947. Two years later, he hit a
league-leading .342, drove in 124 runs, and was voted the most
valuable player in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   --Babe Ruth was the most celebrated athlete of this time. Before
beginning play with the New York Yankees in 1920, the ''Sultan of
Swat'' was a successful pitcher for the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   --George Sisler won two batting titles while playing for the St.
Louis Browns and produced a 41-game hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   --Tris Speaker revolutionized outfield play by positioning
himself in shallow center field. As a result, this Cleveland Indian
recorded more assists than any other outfielder in baseball
history.
</P>
<P>
   --Pie Traynor of the Pittsburgh Pirates was one of the finest
third basemen of all time. His defensive prowess often overshadowed
his strong hitting.
</P>
<P>
   --Honus Wagner, the Pirates' star shortstop, also was a
league-leading batter and base stealer. The ''Flying Dutchman''
enjoyed 15 consecutive .300 seasons, eight as the National League
batting champ.
</P>
<P>
   --Cy Young, christened Denton True Young, was nicknamed Cy for
Cyclone. He won 511 games in his 22-year career -- almost 100 more
than any other pitcher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 1054 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
