<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 94; Nasdaq Down 18  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with blue-chips getting
a lift from the string of strong first-quarter earnings while
technology shares fell to profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 94.63 at 10,769.59.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 4.22 at 1,431.69, but the
technology-laden Nasdaq composite index was down 18.80 at 3,687.61.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the focus was on earnings reports. Companies are
nearing the peak of the reporting season, and most companies have
reported strong profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   United Parcel Service gained 2\ at 61 5/16 after the company
reported earnings that topped expectations. Commerce One, which
provides electronic-commerce software and services, rose 8] to 56[,
also on better-than-expected results.
</P>
<P>
   ''The strong earnings have been a very pleasant surprise to this
market,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, director of market analysis at
A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. Louis. ''Those companies with the
best earnings prospects is where the money is going now.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares came under some selling pressure as investors
cashed in on the market's recent gains. On Monday and Tuesday, the
Nasdaq rose a total of 472 points, with record point gains each
day, and the Dow average gained 461.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp rise earlier this week wiped out a portion of the
crushing losses sustained during last week's devastating selloff.
</P>
<P>
   JDS Uniphase was down 5 7/16 at 86 1/16 today, while Intel lost
1 at 118 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   While stocks have generally moved this week, there remains
lingering concerns about whether the economy is growing too fast.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department reported today that unemployment benefits
plummeted last week to the lowest level in nearly 27 years,
indicating that businesses are scrambling to find workers.
</P>
<P>
   There have been concerns that the tight labor market will spur
higher inflation because employers have to recruit workers with big
increases in wages and benefits, increasing costs that companies
could pass along to consumers in the form of higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve policy-makers, fearful that too-rapid economic
growth could revive, have raised interest rates five times since
June. Many investors worry that continued signs of brisk growth
will spur the Fed to raise rates a number of times more this year.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 307.29 million shares
at late morning, down from 309.6 million shares on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was expected to slow as the day progressed ahead of the
holiday weekend. Financial markets will be closed Friday for the
observance of Good Friday, and bond markets close early this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 1.74 at 484.49.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
