<DOCNO> APW20000420.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Patient Deaths Inquest Sought  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, England (AP) -- A coroner wants to hold inquests into
the deaths of 23 more suspected victims of a doctor convicted of
murdering 15 female patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harold Shipman, whose one-man practice was in Hyde, near the
northwest England city of Manchester, was sentenced in January to
15 life terms for injecting the women with lethal doses of heroin.
</P>
<P>
   John Pollard, the coroner for South Manchester, has written to
the British government seeking permission to open inquests into the
deaths of 23 more patients. Pollard said he was unable to proceed
with inquests without permission because the bodies had all been
cremated.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed that the inquests were not intended to determine
liability, but rather exactly what caused the women's deaths.
</P>
<P>
   During Shipman's trial, investigators said they feared the
doctor -- already among Britain's most prolific serial killers --
might be responsible for many more deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would not be unreasonable to say a figure of 150 would be a
realistic, possible estimate,'' Pollard said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In February, police announced they had enough evidence to
prosecute Shipman for the deaths of 23 more patients, but the Crown
Prosecution Service advised them not to bring further charges
because Shipman could not be guaranteed a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard said Thursday he decided to write to Home Secretary Jack
Straw because ''the families and relatives of these deceased are
anxious for the evidence related to their deaths to be heard and
tested by way of inquest.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue McAlpine, whose mother, Irene Heathcote, is one of the 23
women, said she would be happy for an inquest to be held.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not wholly satisfactory, but at least it would help me
find out what happened to my mother,'' McAlpine said.
</P>
</TEXT>
