<HEADLINE> State Officials To Plot EPA Strategy  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- State environmental officials disgruntled with
the Clinton administration's tough air quality standards for
industry plan to meet next week to plot strategy for dealing with
the next president.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering of regulators struggling with current
Environmental Protection Agency air pollution standards was
arranged by Michigan Gov. John Engler's top environmental official,
Russ Harding.
</P>
<P>
   Engler is a top supporter of Republican George W. Bush's
presidential bid. But Ken Silfven, spokesman for the Michigan
Department of Environmental Quality, said the meeting is not
connected to any campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He characterized the planned gathering as a policy discussion
among officials who believe the EPA's air quality standards are too
cumbersome for industries to comply with or for states to
implement.
</P>
<P>
   ''It isn't a G.W. or an Al Gore meeting,'' Silfven said today.
''The fact is that there is an upcoming election and there will be
new members of Congress, regardless of party, and a new
administrator, regardless of party, obviously the timing is
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee, is the
administration's point man on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   Harding invited top regulators from 17 other states involved in
major policy fights with the EPA to the April 27 conference in
Detroit. Representatives of auto makers, utilities, paper and oil
industries plan to meet at the same hotel on the same day, then
come together for a brief meeting with the state officials.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett, spokesman for Bush's campaign, said they were not
involved in planning the meeting or even aware of it until they got
a call from The Detroit News, which disclosed the meeting in
Tuesday editions.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation calls for ''a framework for this reform that can
be considered by the next U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
Administration and/or the next Congress.'' The invitation list
includes officials from seven Democratic and 10 Republican state
administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Silfven said representatives of Iowa, Kentucky, South Carolina,
Texas and West Virginia had accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Harding had suggested the utility industry help pay for the
meeting, but backed off after several states expressed concern
about the funding.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Fenech, a senior vice president at Detroit-based Consumers
Power Corp. who is coordinating the industry representation at the
meeting, said the proposals would have a better chance if Bush were
elected.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to come up with a plan that will work under a Bush or
a Gore administration,'' he told the Detroit News. ''A Republican
administration probably would give it a broader look.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups have been critical of the meeting. The
Washington-based Environmental Working Group sent a letter to
Harding, requesting that citizens and public interest groups be
allowed to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you are going to talk about how you are going to undermine
critical health standards on behalf of polluting industry
lobbyists, you wouldn't want to exclude members of the public,''
said Mike Casey, a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.epa.gov
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Working Group: http://www.ewg.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 1231 </TRAILER>
