<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daft Declares 'New Day' at Coke  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN BACHMAN, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- Discussing his company's prospects after
a dismal financial year, Coca-Cola chairman and chief executive
Douglas Daft told shareholders ''it's a new day'' at the beverage
giant.
</P>
<P>
   He could have been describing the company's new public stance on
diversity and inclusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as Daft led his first annual shareholders meeting
at the Playhouse Theatre here, Coke executives stressed their
resolve to improve the diversity of the company's ranks and to make
Coke's corporate culture friendlier for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must respect, value, celebrate and connect with local
people and cultures wherever we operate,'' said Daft, an Australian
who spent much of the 1970s overseeing Coke's Asian and Pacific
operations. ''Not only is diversity an important value, it's an
indispensable value.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Coke's black U.S. employees say the Atlanta-based
company -- which has only one black senior executive and one black
board member -- discriminates against them.
</P>
<P>
   Eight current and former black Coke employees sued the company
last year alleging they had been denied fair pay, raises,
promotions and performance reviews because of their race. The
plaintiffs are seeking to add 2,000 Coke workers as class members.
</P>
<P>
   The company denies those allegations, but Daft reiterated
Wednesday that Coke is working to resolve the suit quickly. He said
he could not predict when a resolution might occur.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Larry Jones, a former Coke human resources
manager who led a five-day protest bus journey from Atlanta, called
for an international boycott of all Coke products.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who told shareholders
that Coke's board and executive offices must match the diversity of
its consumers, said his Rainbow PUSH coalition said the ''justice
riders'' had been ''pushed to the brink'' by their frustration. He
said Coke should be given more time to settle the suit.
</P>
<P>
   But without a settlement, inaction on the groups' concerns
''will grow into a boycott,'' he said. Also on Wednesday, NAACP
President Kweisi Mfume called on Coca-Cola officials to settle the
lawsuit. He did not endorse a boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Coke spokesman Rob Baskin said the company was disappointed by
the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't believe that call reflects the aggressive actions
taken by Doug Daft and his management team to equitably and fairly
resolve the lawsuit,'' Baskin said.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading today on the New York Stock Exchange,
Coca-Cola shares were down 18} cents at $49 a share.
</P>
<P>
   During the 2{-hour meeting, Coke chairman Douglas Daft allowed
Jackson and Jones to address shareholders at length.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is great hope in this new team. You inherit the burdens
of history and culture,'' Jackson told Daft, who was joined on the
stage by President Jack Stahl and Carl Ware, Coke's vice president
of global affairs; and other officers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said his group had ridden to the meeting to call attention
to their plight and to publicize their desire to share leadership
with Coke executives in a new spirit of equal partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ''How much longer do we wait?'' Jones asked. ''Three more
months? Five more months? Until the lawsuit is settled?''
</P>
<P>
   In other business, shareholders re-elected Daft to a two-year
board term and re-elected five other directors to three-year terms
on the board.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola: http://www.coke.com
</P>
<P>
   Committee for Corporate Justice, http://www.corporatejustice.org
</P>
</TEXT>
