<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blood Thinner Linked to Disease  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL Q. HANEY, AP Medical Editor
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- A widely used new blood thinner that is routinely
given to heart patients after angioplasty appears in rare cases to
trigger a deadly blood disease.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, called Plavix, prevents blood clots and has been taken
by more than 3 million people worldwide since its introduction two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, doctors have linked the medicine to
thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura, or TTP, a dangerous form of
anemia. A report to be published June 15 in the New England Journal
of Medicine describes 11 cases among Plavix users.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say the benefits of the drug still far outweigh this
risk, which appears to be remote. But they say doctors should watch
their patients closely for signs of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''My guess is that this will be a relatively rare complication,
but it's so important that everybody has got to know about it,''
said Dr. Rodman Starke, research director of the American Heart
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its medical importance, the New England Journal of
Medicine released the study early on its Web site Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Plavix is frequently given for a month after angioplasty, in
which a tiny balloon is inserted into a blood vessel to clear a
blockage. The medicine is used especially in angioplasty patients
who get wire mesh tubes called stents to keep their heart arteries
from clogging up again. It is also given longer term to victims of
mini-strokes to help prevent full-blown strokes, especially if they
cannot take aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it's a great drug. It should be used,'' said Dr.
Charles L. Bennett of Northwestern University, who discovered the
connection. ''In the past, patients got the drug but did not have
close monitoring. Our hope is doctors will be aware of this
potential side effect and follow up after a week or two to see how
they are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Plavix, which is known generically as clopidrogrel, was designed
specifically to avoid this problem. It replaced an older drug,
ticlopidine, that caused TTP in about one of every 1,600 users.
That was 100 times more frequent than in the general population,
and one-third of these patients died.
</P>
<P>
   Plavix is chemically almost identical to ticlopidine. But in
extensive testing, it appeared to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eric Topol of the Cleveland Clinic said that more than
30,000 people took Plavix in carefully conducted studies and not a
single case of TTP was seen.
</P>
<P>
   While the new report ''substantiates that it probably does occur
with clopidrogrel, the incidence is very rare, and the true
incidence is unknown,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Topol noted that another case, not counted by Bennett, happened
in Cleveland last week. A stent patient in her late 60s died a few
days after taking the drug.
</P>
<P>
   TTP destroys red cells and the blood clotting cells called
platelets. Victims can have a wide array of seemingly unconnected
symptoms, including anemia, kidney failure, abnormal heart beats
and a variety of neurologic problems that mimic strokes.
</P>
<P>
   If the disorder is not recognized, about 80 percent of victims
die. Patients can be saved by a blood-filtering process. Bennett
said some cases may be missed because doctors mistake them for
strokes and other conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett is a blood cancer specialist who first documented the
frequency of TTP among patients taking ticlopidine, Plavix's
predecessor drug. He became interested in the question after a
friend of his father developed the complication.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the seeming safety of Plavix, he decided to look for TTP
by calling those who might come across occasional cases, such as
blood specialists and directors of blood banks.
</P>
<P>
   His search turned up 11 cases among Plavix users, including 10
that began within two weeks of starting the drug. Still, this does
not definitely prove that the medicine actually causes the
complication.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Gent of Hamilton Civil Hospitals Research Centers in
Ontario questioned whether Plavix is truly the cause, since TTP
does occasionally occur for unknown reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's been seen so far is entirely consistent with what you
would see in the general population,'' Gent said.
</P>
<P>
   Gent headed the largest study of Plavix, an experiment involving
more than 19,000 people in 16 countries. It showed that Plavix is
somewhat better than aspirin at preventing strokes and new heart
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Plavix's makers, the drug companies Sanofi and Bristol-Myers
Squibb, say new technical descriptions of the drug mentioning the
possibility of TTP are being written for doctors with the approval
of the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said he hopes to get financial support from the makers
to conduct a larger study to see whether the drug actually does
cause the complication and calculate how often it happens.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: New England Journal of Medicine: http://www.nejm.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 1315 </TRAILER>
