<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another Zimbabwe White Farm Attacked  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Black squatters wielding whips, sticks
and rocks tore through another white-owned farm today, smashing
windows, setting workers' homes ablaze and beating dogs to death.
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe, who has voiced support for the
squatters, said earlier today that he had no plans to deploy police
or soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The squatters' leaders had promised Wednesday that they would
halt the growing violence but would not leave the hundreds of farms
they have occupied since February.
</P>
<P>
   In today's unrest, nearly 200 youths rampaged at a farm in
Arcturus district, 35 miles northeast of Harare. Farmer Alan
Windram had fled the property earlier after receiving threats,
neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers smashed windows, hurled rocks into the farmhouse
and attacked Windram's six dogs, according to an Associated Press
Television News report from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   APTN filmed groups of attackers beating the dogs with sticks and
throwing rocks at the dying animals.
</P>
<P>
   The assailants rampaged through a workers' village, kicking down
doors, smashing windows and burning down about 30 houses as
dismayed workers looked on.
</P>
<P>
   A man directing the attackers who identified himself as David
Mazhandu described the farm as a headquarters of the main
opposition party, the Movement for Democratic Change.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said militant squatters also marched onto a nearby
farm, forcing the owners to flee.
</P>
<P>
   Two white farmers and a black police officer have died in the
recent violence, and two opposition party activists were killed in
a firebomb attack last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the killings, several white farmers have been assaulted
by ruling party supporters who accused them of backing growing
opposition to two decades of rule by Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier today, the head of the opposition party, Morgan
Tsvangirai, said his party would not be intimidated by recent
political killings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not retreating,'' said Tsvangirai.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mugabe is history,'' he said shortly after arriving home from
a weeklong trip to Britain -- Zimbabwe's former colonial ruler --
South Africa and the United States. He called Mugabe ''a deranged
dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in an interview with the British Broadcasting Corp.,
Mugabe said the country was generally peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are many houses broken into in Britain and it doesn't
mean there's no law and order,'' he said from Harare, Zimbabwe's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed about the lack of police intervention, Mugabe retorted:
''The police want to give time for people to act on their own -- and
that's wisdom, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe and other presidents in the region were preparing today
for a summit in Zimbabwe on the civil war in the Central African
nation of Congo. The farm deadlock in Zimbabwe will also be
discussed in the summit on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest violence comes a day after landowners agreed to hold
fresh talks on demands by squatters that farmers sign over land
they have claimed on more than 1,000 farms.
</P>
<P>
   Today, ruling party militants chased reporters away from a
gathering of mourners preparing for the funeral of an opposition
party official killed in a firebombing on Saturday. Men chanting
ruling party slogans slashed the tire of a media car.
</P>
<P>
   Farm union officials advised white farmers to evacuate their
families from the western province of Matabeleland, where farmer
Martin Olds was killed Tuesday, and the neighboring province of
Midlands, the union said.
</P>
<P>
   Another 80 families remained evacuated east of Harare.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe has called the occupations a legitimate protest against
the ownership of one-third of the country's productive farmland by
4,000 white farmers. He also said that Britain reneged on an
agreement to help pay for land reform in Zimbabwe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
