<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget to include funding for farm energy aid, barns  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State legislators negotiating the 2000-01
budget have agreed to provide $2 million in a new program to help
relieve farmers from hikes in energy prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Farm Energy Assistance Program would help offset rising gas,
diesel and electricity costs farmers have to pay to keep farms
running, said state Sen. Nancy Larraine Hoffmann, chairwoman of her
chamber's agriculture committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Farmers don't have the luxury of being able to milk in
off-peak hours. Cows have a regular schedule,'' said Hoffmann, a
Syracuse-area Republican and beef cattle farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffmann said another $3 million will be spent on a new Historic
Barn Preservation Program, which would provide financial aid mostly
to farmers who are making structural repairs on old diary barns
that are part of rural New York landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The barns, which used to store hay on top and house cattle
below, can no longer accommodate new farming technology, but
Hoffmann said they should still be preserved for their historic and
tourism value. While many programs exist for preserving historical
districts in urban areas, ''rarely has there been a program
designed to do something in the historic preservation vein in rural
areas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Farm Energy Assistance Program, eligible farmers will
be able to submit their energy bills to the state and receive a
percentage of their payments back. Specific eligibility
requirements and the exact percentage to be refunded are still
being worked out, but Hoffmann said that for large farms, ''that
could mean many hundreds of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Energy and Research Development Authority will
administer the funds in conjunction with the state Department of
Agriculture and Markets. The aid will take effect in May and
farmers will receive quarterly checks. If the program is
successful, Hoffmann said she expects the program to continue in
future years.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Gregg, a spokesman for the Department of Agriculture and
Markets, said high energy prices come at an especially bad time as
the spring planting season begins and fuel consumption increases.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy farmers are even harder hit, he said, because milk prices
are extremely low. Farmers' incomes are now a third of what they
were three months ago while fuel cost nearly twice as much, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm certain that the math is not on their side,'' Gregg said.
''It's a harsh kick in the teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmers also have to pay for transporting their goods, meaning
more dollars spent on fuel, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coventry Transport Services, which hauls milk for dairy farmers
in upstate New York, has added about 10 cents per 100 pounds of
milk in surcharges to its customers since January to cover rising
fuel costs, owner Tom Tripple said. The company, based in Chenango
County, had previously charged farmers $1 for every 100 pounds of
milk transported.
</P>
<P>
   Tripple said an average-size farm transports about 10,000 pounds
of milk every two days.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Reed of the New York Farm Bureau said it's too early to
tell what impact the program will have on farmers, but added,
''Anything to help farmers is good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffmann said with farmers already struggling to make ends meet,
many don't have the resources to make capital improvements such as
restoring old barns. That's where the Historic Barn Preservation
Program comes in, she said.
</P>
<P>
   It would provide funds to farmers under a cost-sharing structure
and the renovated barn could be reused for agricultural purposes. A
point system will be established to determine eligibility, taking
into account the barn's historic value, architectural uniqueness,
vulnerability to the effects of weather and proximity to other
tourism areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''These barns are like cathedrals. They're built by craftsmen
with ingenuity ... long before there were cranes,'' Hoffmann said.
''They have an incredible amount of history embedded within them.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation
and the Department of Agriculture and Markets will oversee the
program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
