<HEADLINE> Art Director Carmen Dillon Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Art director Carmen Dillon, who won an Academy
Award in 1948 for her work on Laurence Olivier's ''Hamlet,'' has
died at age 91.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon, who created sets for many memorable British films for
more than 40 years, died April 12 in Hove, southern England, the
family said. No cause of death was given, nor were any survivors
named.
</P>
<P>
   The first woman art director in the British film industry,
Dillon joined the art department at Fox Studios north of London in
the 1930s after six years of training as an architect and an
unsatisfying stint with an architecture firm.
</P>
<P>
   In 1938, she moved to Pinewood Studios, where she worked on the
films ''The Mikado'' and ''French Without Tears.''
</P>
<P>
   When she created the set for ''The Demi-Paradise'' in 1943,
Dillon was an art director in her own right.
</P>
<P>
   She worked with Paul Sherriff on the Academy Award-nominated
design for Olivier's 1944 classic ''Henry V,'' but it was her work
on Olivier's ''Hamlet'' that won her the Oscar -- for set direction
on a black-and-white film.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon designed the films ''The Way to the Stars'' in 1945,
''The Browning Version'' in 1951, ''The Importance of Being
Earnest'' in 1952, Joseph Losey's ''Accident'' in 1967, ''The
Go-Between'' and ''Lady Caroline Lamb'' in 1972, and ''The Omen''
in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   She was born Oct. 25, 1908, in Cricklewood, northwest London,
the youngest of six children, and was educated at a convent in
southern England.
</P>
<P>
   A Requiem Mass will celebrated April 28 at The Sacred Heart
Church in Hove.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
