<HEADLINE> Bush Sticks to S.C. Flag Position  </HEADLINE>
By JIM VERTUNO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPLE, Texas (AP) -- George W. Bush stuck to his stance on South
Carolinians making up their own minds on the Confederate flag
Thursday, the day after an about-face by former primary rival John
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who took a similar position during his campaign,
reversed field and said the flag should come down from the South
Carolina Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned Thursday, Bush said anew, ''It's the right of the
state of South Carolina to make the decision on the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Wednesday that he had taken a similar position in
February because ''I feared that if I answered honestly I could not
win the South Carolina primary.'' Bush won anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Thursday that McCain's words hadn't changed his view
of the Arizona senator as a possible vice-presidential candidate, a
post McCain has said he's not interested in.
</P>
<P>
   ''My opinion doesn't change one way or the other,'' Bush said.
''He made the decision to go down there and give a speech.'' The
two men will meet for the first time since the primaries on May 9
in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Asked further about a running mate, Bush said ''I have no lists,
short or long lists. ... There will be an appointed time we'll talk
about the process and I'll be screening and eventually selecting a
vice presidential nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney would be named to
develop a list of candidates, Bush said, ''I'm not going to make
any announcements; there are a lot of rumors about a lot of
different things. I'll make the appropriate announcement at the
right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also refused to be drawn into Vermont's proposal on civil
unions, which would grant to same-sex couples some 300 state
benefits of marriage, including medical decision-making, tax breaks
and inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has opposed recognizing same-sex unions in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have a right to pass a law,'' Bush said. ''It's the right
of the state to make that decision just like it's the right of the
state of South Carolina to make the decision on the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush met with a group of gay Republicans last week in Austin and
said he was ''a better person'' for hearing their stories but still
disagreed with them on gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor answered questions after making an elementary
school appearance to promote ''character education'' on the
anniversary of the Columbine shootings.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he sat with a group of first-graders learning
about sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sincerity means honesty to me,'' Bush told them. ''It's
incredibly important to be honest.''
</P>
<P>
   The character of the current administration has let the country
down, Bush told reporters. ''The president has disappointed us.
He's disappointed a lot of Americans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
