<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 30-Yr., 15-Yr. Mortgage Rates Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rates on 30-year and 15-year mortgages crept
up this week after having edged down two weeks in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The average interest rate on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages rose
to 8.16 percent for the week ending April 21 from 8.12 percent the
previous week, according to a survey released Thursday by Freddie
Mac, the mortgage company. This time a year ago, 30-year mortgages
averaged 6.88 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-February, the rates on 30-year mortgages hit a 3{-year
high of 8.38 percent. That was the highest since a 8.42 percent
rate for the week ending July 12, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing, also
ticked up this week to 7.82 percent from 7.76 percent. This time a
year ago, 15-year mortgages were at 6.51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an
average initial rate of 6.76 percent this week, down from 6.86
percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three
types of mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the rise in 30-year and 15-year mortgage rates,
Freddie Mac's deputy chief economist, Frank Nothaft said: ''The
recent rise in the Consumer Price Index spooked the financial
market, pushing interest rates a little higher this week.'' Last
week, the government reported that the CPI shot up 0.7 percent in
March.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Mortgage Bankers Association of America said
that mortgage loan applications for the week ending April 14
decreased 4.5 percent from the previous week and were down 23.6
percent compared with the same week last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
