<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybean Prices Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Corn and soybean prices fell on Thursday for the
first time in three sessions on the Chicago Board of Trade as
heavier-than expected rains in the Midwest brought relief to dry
fields.
</P>
<P>
   Grain and soybean prices sank in early dealings after
heavier-than-expected overnight rains that soaked much of the
Midwest led to a selling surge as soon as trading opened. Although
most of the corn and soybean crops won't be planted until May and
June, traders fretted that drier weather conditions would return to
the Midwest in the next few weeks and hurt production.
</P>
<P>
   While a couple of storm systems are expected to pass through the
Great Plains next week, wheat prices lagged amid concerns over
anticipated instability in corn and soybean futures.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery declined 2 cents to close at $2.51 cents
a bushel; May corn fell 1 cent to close at $2.26} cents a bushel;
July oats rose 1 cent to close at $1.23\ cents a bushel; July
soybeans fell 1} cents to $5.49 cents a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures were on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Pork bellies dropped from a 3{-year high amid expectations for
fewer slaughters.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle rose .45 cents to 69.07 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle fell .28 cents to 84.02 cents a pound; June lean hogs
rose .65 cents to 76.70 cents a pound; and May pork bellies fell
.55 cents to 97.65 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
