<HEADLINE> Congo Airport Bomb Funerals Held  </HEADLINE>
By KAMANGA MUTOND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- In a drizzling rain, several thousand
mourners gathered at a state funeral Thursday to pay tribute to 109
people killed in a series of mysterious airport explosions last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Caskets of the victims lay covered in flags and wreaths in the
back of 40 military trucks outside the Palace of the People.
Government officials and Western diplomats were among the 1,000
people packing the hall, while thousands more huddled outside under
umbrellas and listened to the ceremony on loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   The entourage then crept through Kinshasa bound for a cemetery
some 25 miles outside the city center, where family members and
officials threw flowers and clods of dirt on the caskets after
short sermons were delivered by clergymen.
</P>
<P>
   Most shops were closed in keeping with President Laurent
Kabila's declaration of Thursday as a public holiday. Religious
music played on the state radio, furthering the somber mood.
</P>
<P>
   Explanations for Friday's blasts at the army's fuel and
munitions depots at Kinshasa's N'Djili international airport range
from sabotage to a soldier dropping ammunition while unloading a
planeload of weapons destined for battlefronts in Congo's 20-month
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Tearful relatives appealed to the government for financial
compensation or government housing to make up for the loss of
relatives in the explosions, which shattered windows and ignited
stockpiles of rockets, shells and other weapons and flung debris
for miles.
</P>
<P>
   David Kabila, the brother of a customs official who was killed,
said his brother had spoken of the danger of storing large stocks
of arms and ammunitions at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ''My brother warned the military of the danger but they ignored
him,'' said Kabila, who is not related to Congo's president. ''Now
it is too late to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 people were also injured in the explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian Ambassador Frank de Conninck said his country -- Congo's
former colonial ruler -- was investigating reports that a Congolese
dissident group in Brussels known as the Army of Public Salvation
may have been responsible for the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged dissidents were also allegedly planning to attack
the president's residence, Radio France-Internationale reported,
citing unidentified sources.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think that the disaster originated in Belgium but we
are investigating,'' De Conninck said.
</P>
<P>
   Congolese Planning Minister Badimanyi Mulumba Dilembu, who
represented Congo's president at the funeral, said: ''This misery
that has struck us can't be explained. It is God that wished it
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Air force chief Gen. Faustin Munene said the military had not
determined whether saboteurs were involved, but he said munitions
had been removed from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ''This human error will not be repeated,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
