<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Mutual Funds Cater to Muslims  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- A stock portfolio brimming with shares
of Citigroup Inc., General Electric Co., America Online Inc., The
Seagram Co. and the Philip Morris Cos. would seem like a pretty
solid investment for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   But not necessarily for devout Muslims, whose purse strings are
governed by the tenets of their religion. Such companies violate
Islamic law because of their product lines or business practices,
such as selling alcohol or charging interest on loans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of these restrictions, most practicing Muslims were
hesitant to invest their money in the international stock
markets,'' said Nizam Yaquby, an Islamic law scholar in Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
   That's changing as Europe's big banks roll out new lines of
mutual funds aimed at Muslim investors, a small market once the
domain of only niche players.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Germany's No. 4 lending institution,
Commerzbank, launched its AlSukoor European Equity Fund targeting
Muslims in the Middle East first, and later those living in Europe.
Looking to hit a volume of 100 million euros ($94 million) by the
end of the year, AlSukoor raised 25 million euros in its first
three weeks alone.
</P>
<P>
   Britain-based IslamQ.com went online last month as the first
Islamic Internet bank. Other big investment houses such as
U.S.-based Citibank, Britain's HBSC, Swiss-based UBS and Barclays
also have their own small funds mainly targeting customers in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic banking has strong roots in the Middle East and
southeast Asian nations such as Malaysia and Indonesia, but even
there only about 10 percent of the assets held by banks are
invested according to Muslim law, or Shari'ah. In Europe, it's less
than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The world's 1 billion Muslims have roughly $100 billion to
invest, an amount growing by an estimated 15 percent a year,
according to Rushi Siddqui, who tracks the performance of
Koran-safe companies for Dow Jones financial services.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a huge market demand for Islamic investing and a very
small supply,'' said Paul Brett, an executive with IslamiQ. ''There
are a lot of Muslims in the world and they control a lot of money.
Basic economics tells you that's a good position to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is finding companies in compliance with Islamic law,
or Shari'ah. Committees of Islamic scholars decide what companies
are safe by interpreting Islam's holy book, the Koran. But because
their interpretations sometimes differ, what one fund considers
acceptable may be rejected by another.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ruling out alcohol, pork products and tobacco, Shari'ah
also governs how much debt a company can carry and how much it can
earn from interest.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of IslamiQ, it won't offer interest-bearing bonds,
certificates of deposit or money market funds. Non-financial
companies are also ruled out if their debt is more than 33 percent
of total assets, if interest makes up more than 9 percent of their
income or if outstanding revenues are more than 47 percent of total
assets.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Citigroup is usually ruled out because it charges
interest, which violates Islamic law. The same goes for General
Electric, which also has a powerful financial arm.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric is further suspect as the parent company of
NBC, the U.S. broadcaster that sometimes has racy and violent
television shows. That's also a problem for America Online, whose
Internet services can allow users access to pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram would be out for its whisky business, while Philip
Morris is a no-no for cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Also off-limits are companies dealing in weapons, human cloning,
abusive animal testing and abortion -- as well as those dealing in
derivatives and futures, which are considered forms of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves most Muslim investors to focus on higher-risk
holdings in stocks and venture capital, which are balanced against
low but reliable returns in commodities, trade finance and real
estate.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in Islamic investments is growing fast, with Dow Jones
launching its own Islamic Market Index to track Shari'ah-safe
companies in February 1999. Last year, its Islamic index for U.S.
stocks climbed 26.35 percent, outpacing both the Dow Jones
Industrial Average and the S&AMP;P 500 index.
</P>
<P>
   Components of the Dow Jones indexes include many well-known
companies, including Internet network company Cisco Systems Inc.,
telephone equipment maker Lucent Technologies Inc. and the online
auctioneer eBay Inc.
</P>
<P>
   High performance isn't always guaranteed, especially with the
tech-heavy portfolios typically held by Islamic investors. Over the
last week when markets fell around the world, those funds took a
heavy bruising like other technology-rich funds.
</P>
<P>
   But to the devout Muslim investor, that shouldn't matter, said
Yaquby, himself an avid investor.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some years when you make gains, some years when you
take losses,'' Yaquby said. ''But most Islamic investors expect
that. They are in it for the long run. We consider Islamic
investing ethical investing.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: IslamiQ at http://www.islamiq.com/
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones Islamic Indexes at
http://indexes.dowjones.com/djimi/imindex.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 1615 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000420.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Realtors Sue Over 'Sold' Signs Ban  </HEADLINE>
By RON TODT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Real estate agents are suing to force the
city to lift a civil rights-era ban on the posting of ''Sold''
signs outside homes -- a law that was aimed at countering ''white
flight'' as neighborhoods became integrated.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,500-member Greater Philadelphia Association of Realtors
filed the lawsuit in federal court last month after a five-year
effort to repeal the law died in the City Council. The lawsuit asks
a judge to declare the ban unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're the last big city with that law on the books and
still being enforced,'' said Kevin Vaughan, executive director of
the Philadelphia Commission on Human Relations, which supported the
ordinance three decades ago and now favors its repeal.
</P>
<P>
   During the tumult of the 1960s, with federal civil rights laws
opening up traditionally white neighborhoods to blacks, authorities
feared an exodus of whites afraid of falling property values. They
said such fears were sometimes fanned by unscrupulous real estate
agents trying to get whites to sell out fast -- a practice dubbed
''blockbusting.''
</P>
<P>
   The City Council in 1970 passed an ordinance banning ''Sold''
signs outside homes.
</P>
<P>
   '''Sold' signs were targeted because that was the clincher for
people to kind of say, 'Look, the Browns are selling their house
because African-Americans are moving in. Maybe we should sell, too,
before the property values go down,''' Vaughan said.
</P>
<P>
   Other municipalities such as Willingboro, N.J., went even
further, banning both ''Sold'' and ''For Sale'' signs.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1977, the U.S. Supreme Court struck down Willingboro's
ban, ruling that the community was violating the First Amendment by
''restricting the free flow of truthful commercial information.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, undeterred, asked real estate agents to choose:
They could put up ''Sold'' signs, or they could put up ''For Sale''
signs, but not both. Agents decided to continue putting up ''For
Sale'' signs.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman James Kenney introduced a bill for the real estate
agents to try to repeal the ban, but support evaporated after some
neighborhood groups opposed the repeal.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Realtors organization president Frank Jacovini said
the ban on ''Sold'' signs is unnecessary because of stronger
fair-housing laws. His group also believes ''Sold'' signs actually
serve an important public purpose by informing people homes are
selling and the community is viable.
</P>
<P>
   But Christopher Artur, a longtime Philadelphia broker, said he
doesn't see any benefit from the signs and changing it in the
current strong housing market would be harmful.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I put up six sold signs on one block, what does that tell
you?'' he asked. ''That people are selling and people are
fleeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Holmen, associate general counsel of the National
Association of Realtors, said some areas still restrict or ban
''For Sale'' or other real estate signs, but Philadelphia's ban on
only ''Sold'' signs may be unique.
</P>
<P>
   Restrictions or bans are usually directed at ''For Sale'' signs,
sometimes to counter ''white flight.'' Once challenged, they fare
poorly in the courts, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 1619 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
