<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guard killed at prison where another was beaten by inmate lastweek  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   YARDVILLE, N.J. (AP) -- The death of a prison guard who suffered
a heart attack while subduing an inmate has union officials
pointing the finger at the state Department of Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   They say cutbacks at the Garden State Youth Correctional
Facility are to blame for two incidents in less than a week in
which guards were injured or died.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Michael Price, 44, collapsed Wednesday while attempting to
handcuff an inmate who had become disruptive, according to union
officials.
</P>
<P>
   On April 13, an inmate beat a guard over the head with a pipe.
The guard survived.
</P>
<P>
   Garden State, a minimum security prison with about 1,900
inmates, has about 365 guards, 21 less than is called for in the
Department of Corrections' own staffing analysis, according to
Donald Dudich, vice president of the New Jersey Law Enforcement
Supervisors union, which represents sergeants at Garden State.
</P>
<P>
   When planned staff cuts are completed, 328 guards will work
there, Dudich said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The staff is doing the best they can to deal with what they
have. But when you reduce the staff and you give inmates more
liberty, this is what happens. The inmates get more aggressive,
they think they don't have to respect the law as much,'' Dudich
said. ''This department wants us to do more with less, and that's
not a good way to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Price was serving the unidentified inmate with a disciplinary
charge when the man assaulted him, Dudich said. Struggling to
handcuff the man, Price was being helped by another officer when he
collapsed, according to Dudich.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Corrections spokesman Chris Carden would not
discuss the circumstances of Price's death except to say it
happened while he was on duty.
</P>
<P>
   The department's special investigations division is
investigating, he said. Carden wouldn't respond to the union's
criticisms about staffing, saying he would not engage ''in a tit
for tat.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the two incidents occurring so closely, he said:
''You will find that corrections officers have the most difficult
job in the world. They do a yeoman's job in protecting the state
from its worst criminal offenders. Understandably, there are
incidents that occur that are unfortunate. This one is among the
worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Carden said no one has been charged in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   In the incident last week, guard Claude Nix, 54, suffered a
fractured skull and a broken jaw when he was attacked by one or
more inmates. He was hospitalized for four days.
</P>
<P>
   Price, of Burlington Township, was a 10-year veteran who worked
at Garden State the whole time. For his family, it was the second
tragedy in less than six months. In December, his 16-year-old
daughter died in a traffic accident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
