<HEADLINE> Elian's Dad Seeks Americans' Help  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An anguished Juan Miguel Gonzalez, impatient
after a two-week wait on U.S. soil without seeing his 6-year-old
son Elian, called on the American people Thursday to contact
President Clinton and urge immediate action to reunite father and
son.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't let them continue to abuse my son,'' Gonzalez said,
referring to the Miami relatives who have been taking care of Elian
since he was found in late November floating off the Florida coast,
a shipwreck survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Spanish, Gonzalez made his plea a day after a
three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said
Elian must remain in the United States until the court decides
whether he should get an asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really wish to be with my son,'' Gonzalez said through a
translator, speaking outside the Cuban diplomat's home where he has
been staying. ''He belongs with me.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the American people should contact both Clinton and
Attorney General Janet Reno on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has vowed to take steps to reunite Elian with his father
and spent Thursday conferring with Justice Department aides on the
case, but there was no immediate word on what action she might take
next.
</P>
<P>
   ''It hurts me a lot to see what they are doing to my son,''
Gonzalez said, declining to be more specific in his brief
appearance. Afterward, he returned to his temporary residence
without answering questions.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of both Elian's Miami relatives and the
government expressed some interest in resolving the impasse though
mediation, but neither side moved immediately to take up a
mediation offer by the U.S. 11th Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Jose Garcia-Pedrosa, an attorney for the relatives,
said they had previously requested mediation and, in light of the
11th Circuit offer, ''we'll probably be pursuing that a little bit
further.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gonzalez' attorney, Gregory Craig, said he sees no
possibility for mediation of a father's claim to his son and urged
Reno to ''take immediate action'' to reunite the boy with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ''She should take whatever action is necessary to enforce the
rule of law,'' he said in an interview with CNN. He repeated the
assurance that his client is willing to stay in the United States
pending federal court action on an asylum appeal filed on Elian's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokeswoman Carole Florman said the
government has ''always been open to the family members talking
about how to achieve an orderly transfer of Elian and if they
wanted mediation for that, we would help facilitate it.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said the department has not taken a position on whether
or not mediation should be the next step in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said their fax machines had been
inundated by printed forms faxed by supporters of the Miami
relatives. These faxes have been headlined either ''Father, I do
not want to go back!'' or ''Papa, I don't want to go back.'' Their
texts are virtually identical and tell Reno in part: ''We will not
allow you to send Elian Gonzalez into bondage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
