<HEADLINE> Philippines Hostage Rescue Planned  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- Top military officials Thursday
were considering a response to a Muslim extremist group's claim
that it has beheaded two hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said that the military and
police ''have been preparing'' a response to the group Abu Sayyaf,
which has been holding 29 hostages for a month in the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   The government has rejected the group's demands to facilitate
the release of Ramzi Yousef, mastermind of the 1993 bombing of the
World Trade Center in New York, and Sheik Omar Abdel-Rahman,
accused of conspiring to blow up New York City landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection of that and other demands -- including for the
release of two Abu Sayyaf members being held in a Basilan jail --
prompted the group to behead two of its hostages, both male
teachers who were former soldiers, on Wednesday, Abu Sayyaf
spokesman Abu Ahmad said in radio interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The killings drew widespread condemnation among residents of
Basilan and the southern port city of Zamboanga.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels originally seized more than 50 people from two
schools in Basilan on March 20 for use as human shields after
attacking an army outpost. Some of the hostages have since been
freed.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf is the smaller but more radical of two Muslim
groups fighting for an independent Islamic state in the southern
Philippines. It has been blamed for numerous attacks on Christians,
including the abduction of foreign missionaries.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department has included the Abu Sayyaf in a list
of 28 foreign groups that threaten Americans at home or abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Mercado said the government will not permit attacks against the
group by vigilantes who have been holding 11 relatives of Abu
Sayyaf leader Khadaffy Janjalani in an effort to force the
extremist group to release its captives.
</P>
<P>
   The vigilantes have threatened to kill the relatives if the
hostages are not freed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
