<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Proof Yet in Osprey Crash Probe  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Investigators so far have found no proof
pointing to human error, maintenance or equipment problems in this
month's fatal crash of a Marine Corps Osprey aircraft, but still
have ruled out nothing, the corps' top aviation official said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And he dismissed the idea that there could be a cover up if
problems are found with the MV-22 Osprey, a hybrid airplane and
helicopter that critics say is technologically troubled.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can assure you that we're doing everything that we can to
make sure that the cause of the accident is found out and that our
Marines and sailors and Air Force that fly this airplane are all
going to learn from this misfortunate accident, '' said Lt. Gen.
Fred McCorkle, assistant chief of staff for Marine aviation.
</P>
<P>
   In an update on the investigation into the April 8 crash that
killed 19 Marines, McCorkle said it has been determined so far that
the aircraft's major systems -- propellers, engine and drive shaft --
all appeared to be operating normally at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, investigators so far have found nothing to indicate
pilot error or a problem with maintenance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The MV-22 Osprey crashed during a nighttime training mission
over the Marana Northwest Regional Airport in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The military is conducting the final evaluations of the Osprey,
an innovative aircraft. At a Pentagon press briefing Thursday,
McCorkle was asked for assurances there would be no cover-up to
blame the crash on human error so Marines could move ahead with
plans for producing and using the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you talk about integrity and you talk about the Marines
... I think Marines have as much integrity as anybody around,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think that you could ever cover up,'' McCorkle added
when pressed, saying there are over 100 experts from industry and
government working on the probe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
