<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CSX OKs Better Track Inspections  </HEADLINE>
By RON WORD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- CSX agreed to maintain its tracks
better in a settlement Thursday with federal inspectors who found
deteriorating conditions on East Coast rail lines used by freight,
commuter and Amtrak trains.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors recently found 47 violations, ranging from
insufficient repairs after a derailment to spreading rails that
could cause accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, effective May 1, the freight railroad
pledged to conduct more-frequent track inspections and pay
penalties for unacceptable conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our collective goal here is to make a safe CSX safer through
preventive actions,'' said Jolene Molitoris, administrator of the
Federal Railroad Administration.
</P>
<P>
   John Snow, CSX Corp. chairman and president, said: ''We all
recognize we can do better. And what this agreement is all about is
doing better.''
</P>
<P>
   Over two weeks, the railroad agency checked 15 percent of CSX's
23,000-mile rail network in response to a series of derailments on
CSX-run tracks in suburban Philadelphia in February. Three
derailments near residential areas caused no major injuries or
deaths, but one knocked out power.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with CSX tracks have outraged Darby, Pa., Mayor Paula
Brown, who was spared a jail sentence Thursday for allegedly using
her car to block tracks that run through the community. The mayor
has battled CSX for months, complaining about the derailments,
malfunctioning crossing gates and freight trains parked for hours,
blocking traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're irresponsible, very irresonsible. They've no regard
for human life,'' Brown said. But she promised not to block the
tracks again.
</P>
<P>
   Snow said Thursday that 97 percent of the defects discovered,
including the most dangerous, have been fixed and the rest would be
within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Molitoris would not say whether CSX would face fines for the
unsafe tracks, saying it was still being considered.
</P>
<P>
   CSX, the largest Eastern railroad, has faced the federal agency
before over similar findings. In 1996 and 1997, the agency cited
numerous safety violations on the network, which was considerably
smaller because the company had not yet bought 42 percent of
Conrail.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that investigation, CSX reworked some of its
tracks, instituted new safety programs and paid a fine.
</P>
<P>
   CSX Transportation, with its headquarters in Jacksonville, has
35,000 employees and serves 23 states, the District of Columbia and
two Canadian provinces.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: FRA's Web site is:http://www.fra.dot.gov
</P>
<P>
   CSX's Web site is:http://www.csx.com
</P>
</TEXT>
