<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Meeting Angers Environmentalists  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Environmentalists are criticizing a planned
meeting between state regulators and industry groups on air quality
rules as a secret attack on public health standards.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering of regulators who are struggling with the
Environmental Protection Agency over air pollution standards was
arranged by Russ Harding, the top environmental official for
Michigan Gov. John Engler, an outspoken supporter of Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Michigan Department of Environmental Quality
said next Thursday's planned meeting is simply a policy discussion
among officials who believe the EPA's air quality standards are too
cumbersome for industries to comply with or for states to
implement.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Casey, spokesman for the Washington-based Environmental
Working Group, said Harding ''is rounding up a bunch of polluting
industry lobbyists with public servants from other states to figure
out how they are going to hobble environmental health laws.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a dirty and suspicious little web of backroom
dealing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Casey said the meeting was clearly a move to drum up support for
Bush's presidential bid. Democratic Vice President Al Gore is the
administration's point man on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are fooling no one when they say, 'Gosh, we'll give these
lists of reform ideas to whoever is president,''' Casey said.
''Between the two men that are running for president right now, the
record on clean air couldn't be more stark.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Engler is a top Bush supporter, Ken Silfven, spokesman
for the Michigan environmental department, said the meeting is not
connected to any campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''It isn't a G.W. or an Al Gore meeting,'' he said. ''The fact
is that there is an upcoming election and there will be new members
of Congress, regardless of party, and a new administrator,
regardless of party, obviously the timing is right.''
</P>
<P>
   And Dan Bishop, a spokesman for Consumers Power Corp. of
Jackson, an industry group planning to attend the gathering, said
members are hoping to influence the next president's environmental
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking for a series of regulations that a new
administration, regardless of party, would find of interest and
possible use,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett, a spokesman for Bush's campaign, said officials
there were not involved in planning the meeting or even aware of it
until they got a call from The Detroit News, which disclosed the
meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Harding invited top regulators from 17 other states involved in
major policy fights with the EPA to the April 27 conference in
Detroit. Representatives of auto makers, utilities, paper and oil
industries plan to meet at the same hotel on the same day, then
come together for a brief meeting with the state officials.
</P>
<P>
   Harding had suggested the utility industry help pay for the
meeting, but backed off after several states expressed concern
about the funding.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation calls for ''a framework for this reform that can
be considered by the next U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
Administration and/or the next Congress.'' The invitation list
includes officials from seven Democratic and 10 Republican state
administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Silfven said representatives of Iowa, Kentucky, South Carolina,
Texas and West Virginia had accepted.
</P>
<P>
   James M. Seif, Pennsylvania's secretary of environmental
protection, was invited but said he would not attend because he
doesn't agree with Michigan's position on air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to strengthen clean air standards not weaken them,''
he said. ''Governor (Tom) Ridge has sued a number of states on
these issues. We just got the EPA to restore standards that several
utilities had sued to try to weaken.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.epa.gov
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Working Group: http://www.ewg.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
