<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carbon Emissions Plan Finds Interest  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY DUNPHY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In advance of this weekend's Earth Day, the
World Bank announced Thursday that a global market it established
in January to trade carbon emission credits has attracted more
money, government and corporate interest than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said about $135 million has been pledged to the
Prototype Carbon Fund by 15 companies and six countries. The fund
was started to finance projects aimed at reducing greenhouse gas
emissions in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   The primary focus is on renewable energy technology such as
wind, small hyrdo-electric and bio-mass that would not be
profitable without support from the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Fund participants receive emissions credits based on the size of
gas emission cuts achieved through the projects they finance.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank acts as a broker by helping to negotiate a price
considered reasonable to both buyers and sellers of the credits
that can be used to meet international climate control obligations.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said the money raised so far is about $15 million short
of the $150 million legal cap placed on the fund by the bank's
executive board. It will ask the board to raise the limit to
accommodate interest in the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Countries that have agreed to participate so far include Canada,
Finland, the Netherlands, Japan, Sweden and Norway. Another nine
companies want to subscribe.
</P>
<P>
   Investor companies include BP Amoco, Deutsche Bank, Gaz de
France and six Japanese electric power companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''The high level of corporate interest in this venture marks a
major shift in how companies think about their role in contributing
to new thinking about global problems such as climate change,''
said Ian Johnson , a World Bank vice president for environment
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''It also points to growing competition among corporate players
anxious to position themselves in what will likely become a highly
competitive market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fund's potential benefits for industrial countries
and companies is that emission reductions achieved from fund
projects could be counted toward meeting their targets under the
Kyoto protocol.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial countries, including the United States, agreed in
December 1997 in Kyoto Japan to reduce from 1990 levels emissions
of heat-trapping greenhouse gases, notably carbon dioxide, sometime
between 2008 and 2012. President Clinton has signed the protocol
but Congress has not ratified it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
