<HEADLINE> Evidence Found in McDonald's Blast  </HEADLINE>
By PIERRE-ANTOINE SOUCHARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Investigators have identified the likely source of
explosives used to bomb a McDonald's restaurant, a finding that
casts further suspicion on a regional separatist group, judicial
sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing Wednesday in Dinan, a town in the western French
region of Brittany, killed a 28-year-old McDonald's employee.
Explosives used in the attack were part of a stock of dynamite
stolen in September from a company in the Breton town of Plevin,
the judicial sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   After the theft, police recovered more than half the dynamite
and arrested eight Breton and five Basque separatists. Then, in
March, a small separatist group called the Breton Revolutionary
Army claimed responsibility for an attack that made use of some of
the explosives that weren't recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have pointed to the Breton Revolutionary Army as the
most likely suspect in the McDonald's attack, the judicial sources
said. The group seeks autonomy for Brittany, which has maintained a
strong cultural identity reflecting the Bretons' Celtic origins.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, authorities are expected to open a judicial inquiry
into the bombing. Justice Minister Elisabeth Guigou said Thursday
that France would do ''everything that is possible to do to shed
light on this attack and find its authors.''
</P>
<P>
   The new evidence also links the McDonald's attack with another
bombing attempt in Brittany on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Rennes, Brittany's largest city, authorities defused a small
bomb found in front of a downtown post office. The bomb, which
contained three sticks of dynamite, came from the same stock of
stolen explosives, the judicial sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
