<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDA OKs Colorectal Cancer Treatment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the first time in years, the government
has approved a new first-line treatment for patients whose
colorectal cancer has spread, saying the newer therapy could
prolong survival.
</P>
<P>
   The Pharmacia Corp.'s Camptosar won Food and Drug Administration
approval Thursday. It can be used, in combination with two standard
cancer drugs, as soon as colorectal cancer has metastasized.
</P>
<P>
   Camptosar has been sold as a follow-up cancer treatment since
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The new approval ''will likely change the way patients with
metastatic colorectal cancer are treated,'' said Dr. Robert
Justice, FDA's deputy director of cancer drugs.
</P>
<P>
   About 130,000 Americans will be diagnosed with colorectal cancer
this year. About half of the patients treated with surgery,
sometimes followed with chemotherapy or radiation, will have their
cancer spread beyond the colon or rectum.
</P>
<P>
   The new approval comes after two clinical trials studied whether
infusing patients with Camptosar in addition to standard treatment
-- the older drugs 5FU and leucovorin -- helped newly metastatic
patients. Those studies found median survival prolonged by about
three months with the newer combination.
</P>
<P>
   Side effects of Camptosar include severe diarrhea that may
require medical treatment, as well as nausea, vomiting and a drop
in white blood cells.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacia said it expects a 60 percent increase in patients
using Camptosar as a result of the new FDA approval. A course of
treatment, lasting up to six months, costs about $15,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
