<P>
   Microsoft Earnings Up 24 Percent
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp.'s third-quarter earnings rose 24
percent from a year ago amid analysts' concerns over lagging
computer sales and investor worries about its ongoing legal woes.
The software company had profits of $2.39 billion, or 43 cents per
share, on sales of $5.66 billion -- a 23 percent increase in
revenues -- in the three months ended March 31. In the same period a
year ago, the company made $1.92 billion, or 35 cents per share, on
revenue of $4.6 billion. The results squeaked by analysts
expectations of 41 cents per share, as reported by First
Call/Thomson Financial, but were likely to leave Wall Street
unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Buys Back $2B of Debt
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Treasury, its coffers filled because of
budget surpluses, bought back $2 billion of the national debt
Thursday, the latest in a series of debt repurchases. Because the
outstanding 30-year Treasury bonds carry higher yields than the
current market yield on comparable securities, the Treasury
Department paid sellers $431 million in premiums to cash in early.
Treasury bought back 12 issues of 30-year bonds maturing between
February 2020 and August 2025. The bonds carried yields ranging
from 6.250 percent to 8.750 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel Takes Toll on Airline Earnings
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Northwest Airlines posted a small net profit on
the sale of Priceline.com stock but still had an operating loss as
earnings were weighed down by greater costs for fuel. Continental
Airlines' profits fell sharply. Northwest reported net earnings of
$3 million in the first quarter as a one-time gain from the sale of
Priceline.com stock made up for losses from higher fuel costs.
Without the $44 million gain, it lost $41 million, or 51 cents per
share, beating analyst estimates of a loss of 73 cents a share.
Continental Airlines reported a 73 percent decline in profits due
to higher fuel costs, but still managed to beat Wall Street
expectations. It earned $14 million, or 21 cents a share, down from
$52 million, or $1.25 a share, in the same period last year. The
year-ago results included an accounting charge of $33 million.
Analysts had expected Continental to break even.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific Reports Income Boost
</P>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Citing service improvements after its merger
with Southern Pacific, leading railroad operator Union Pacific
Corp. reported net income of $185 million for its first quarter of
the year, a 43 percent increase over the same period a year ago.
Earnings per share increased to 74 cents from 52 cents per share in
the first quarter of 1999. Net income in last year's first quarter
was $129 million. Revenues rose 6 percent to $2.91 billion. Union
Pacific appears to be finding its feet now after troublesom years
implementing its merger with Southern Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   USX Reports Growth in Oil, Steel
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- USX Corp. reported first-quarter profits
Thursday in its oil and steel businesses, bouncing back from losses
in the same period last year, as better prices for both products
lifted results. Marathon Oil, USX's petroleum company, posted
earnings of $199 million or 81 cents a share before a one-time gain
compared to a loss of $11 million, or 4 cents a share in the same
period a year ago. The results for the most recent quarter did not
include a $55 million gain on the sale of a one-third ownership of
a Gulf of Mexico project. The year-ago results did not include $130
million in credits from adjustments to the value of inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo, SmithKline See Higher Sales
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- British pharmaceuticals companies Glaxo Wellcome
PLC and SmithKline Beecham, which are in the process of merging,
each reported strong first-quarter results. Meanwhile, U.S.-based
Schering-Plough Corp.'s first quarter profits rose 17 percent
primarily due to increasing sales of its Claritin allergy drug.
Glaxo Wellcome said today it boosted its first-quarter sales by 13
percent to 2.13 billion pounds ($3.36 billion) from 1.9 billion
pounds ($3 billion) in 1999. Sales in the United States rose 22
percent at constant exchange rates. SmithKline Beecham earned a
quarterly pretax profit of 562 million pounds ($888 million), an
increase of 12 percent from the first quarter of 1999 based on
comparable exchange rates. Schering-Plough Corp.'s first quarter
profits rose 17 percent $628 million or 42 cents per share,
compared to $539 million or 36 cents per share a year ago. Sales
rose 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   European Stocks Close Mostly Higher
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks joined Wall Street's pre-Easter
rally today. U.K., French and Swiss stocks gained momentum late in
the day as the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose more than 100
points. London's FTSE-100 Share Index rose 0.9 percent to 6,241.2.
Milan's MIBtel Index shrugged off the resignation of Prime Minister
Massimo D'Alema to end up 2.3 percent to 30,524. Frankfurt's Xetra
DAX Index bucked the trend, falling 0.8 percent to 7,157.95. SAP
dropped after a poor U.S. sales performance and DaimlerChrysler
dropped as the auto maker revealed a fall in first quarter
operating profits to 12 percent. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index
ended up 3.40 points at 426.25.
</P>
<P>
   Winn-Dixie To Cut Jobs, Shut Stores
</P>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Supermarket giant Winn-Dixie Stores
Inc. said today it will cut 11,000 jobs and close 114 money-losing
stores and other facilities. The job cuts and closings will
eliminate 8 percent of 132,000 positions in the 14-state chain
based in Jacksonville. A Tampa warehouse, detergent and bag
factories and three division offices also will be shut down. The
top-to-bottom restructuring plan will also lead to management
consolidation, the company said, beginning with the retirements of
10 vice presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate Blames Storms for Losses
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Allstate Corp.'s earnings before special items
fell 27 percent in the first quarter as the result of an unusually
high number of storms which led to large catastrophe losses and
offset higher premiums. The nation's largest publicly held
insurance company said today it earned $481 million, or 62 cents
per share, before restructuring charges and capital gains for the
three months ended March 31, down from $663 million, or 81 cents a
share, before capital gains in the same period of 1999. Wall Street
analysts forecast earnings before onetime items of 65 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Gatorade Lifts Quaker Oats Profit
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Soaring Gatorade sales helped Quaker Oats Co.
post a 45 percent increase in first-quarter profit before one-time
items. The results reported today exceeded Wall Street's
expectations. Quaker shares rose 4\ to 67 5/16 on the New York
Stock Exchange. A strong rise in sales of Gatorade, the leading
sports drink worldwide, and snacks such as Chewy Granola Bars
enabled the Chicago-based company to easily overcome a 3 percent
decline in hot cereals, including its namesake Quaker Oats.
Excluding one-time items, profit from operations was $106 million,
or 77 cents per share, up from $72.9 million, or 51 cents a share,
a year earlier. Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial
had forecast per-share earnings of 60 cents. Including the special
items, Quaker's earnings fell to $1.8 million, or 1 cent a share,
from $86.7 million, or 61 cents a share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
