<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Glaxo, SmithKline See Higher Sales  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- British pharmaceuticals companies Glaxo Wellcome
PLC and SmithKline Beecham, which are in the process of merging,
each reported strong first-quarter results. Meanwhile, U.S.-based
Schering-Plough Corp.'s first quarter profits rose 17 percent
primarily due to increasing sales of its Claritin allergy drug.
</P>
<P>
Glaxo Wellcome PLC
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo Wellcome said Thursday that it boosted its first-quarter
sales by 13 percent over the same period last year, due partly to
strong results for its new asthma drug Seretide and its HIV
treatment Ziagen.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterly sales grew to 2.13 billion pounds ($3.36 billion) from
1.9 billion pounds ($3 billion) in 1999, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in the United States rose 22 percent at constant exchange
rates. U.S. sales benefited from an encouraging debut by Lotronex,
Glaxo's drug for irritable bowel syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   A strong performance by other new products, including the flu
medicine Relenza, contributed to the result for the first three
months of the year. But so did the favorable comparison with last
year's weak first quarter, when poor sales for some drugs were a
drag on the company's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   European sales grew by 9 percent at constant exchange rates,
while sales in the rest of the world rose by 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that earnings growth, excluding costs related
to restructuring and to Glaxo's pending acquisition of drugmaker
SmithKline Beecham, were broadly in line with its sales growth. It
gave no details.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo agreed in January to buy SmithKline in a deal worth about
$180 billion. Chairman Richard Sykes affirmed that the SmithKline
acquisition is on track for completion this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Glaxo Wellcome rose 56 pence, or 3 percent, to 1,958
pence ($30.94) in London trading.
</P>
<P>
SmithKline Beecham PLC
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline Beecham earned a quarterly pretax profit of 562
million pounds ($888 million), an increase of 12 percent from the
first quarter of 1999 based on comparable exchange rates, the
company announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Strong sales of three drugs introduced last year in the United
States -- the antibiotic Augmentin, antidepressant Paxil and
diabetes drug Avandia -- helped lift earnings. However, results for
the arthritis treatment Relafen lagged in the face of strong
competition.
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline's pretax profit in the first quarter of 1999 was 510
million pounds ($811 million).
</P>
<P>
   Sales from ongoing operations rose 11 percent, at constant
exchange rates, to 1.99 billion pounds ($3.14 billion) from 1.83
billion pounds ($2.89 billion). However, sales slipped 3 percent if
the results for operations that SmithKline sold last year are
included in 1999 figure.
</P>
<P>
   Drug sales in the U.S. market rose 20 percent at constant
exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   Paxil sales rose 24 percent to 348 million pounds ($550 million)
and Augmentin sales grew by 10 percent, in spite of a dip in
European sales, to 318 million pounds ($504 million).
</P>
<P>
   Shares of SmithKline rose 28 pence, or 3 percent, to 879.50
pence ($13.89), in London.
</P>
<P>
Schering-Plough Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Schering-Plough Corp.'s first quarter profits rose 17 percent
primarily due to increasing sales of its Claritin allergy drug.
</P>
<P>
   Madison, N.J.-based Schering-Plough made $628 million or 42
cents per share, compared to $539 million or 36 cents per share a
year ago. Results matched Wall Street analysts' forecasts,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose 10 percent to $2.4 billion from $2.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company's drug sales increased by 12 percent to $2.02
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Claritin, the world's leading allergy drug, rose 18
percent to $665 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Intron A/Rebetron combination therapy for hepatitis C
rose 23 percent to $336 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company's inhaled steroid Nasonex rose 26 percent to $137
million.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the company's sun care products, including newly
acquired Ban De Soleil, rose 9 percent to $92 million. Foot care
product sales rose 13 percent to $93 million.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Schering-Plough fell 37{ cents to $40.12{ in trading
at 4:30 p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
