<HEADLINE> UPS Profit Jumps 63 Percent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- United Parcel Service Inc.'s profit for the first
quarter rose 63 percent, swelled by a 14 percent increase in
revenue and onetime gains.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the onetime items, its profit rose 35 percent and
beat Wall Street expectations. Its shares shot up $4.43}, or more
than 7.5 percent, to $63.50 at 5:15 p.m. EST on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The delivery company, which sold stock to the public in
November, also announced Thursday it plans to spend up to $1.2
billion of the proceeds from the initial public offering to launch
a share repurchase program.
</P>
<P>
   UPS earned $813 million, or 67 cents per share, in the
January-March period, up from $499 million, or 44 cents per share,
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The latest results were inflated by $139 million in
non-recurring items as proceeds from the sales of investments and a
truck leasing operation were offset partly by labor charges.
</P>
<P>
   Without the onetime items, its earnings rose to $674 million, or
56 cents per share. That beat the consensus forecast of 52 cents
per share by analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues for the quarter climbed to $7.2 billion from $6.3
billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. package operations profit rose 13.2 percent on an 11.7
percent increase in revenue. International package operations's
profits rose 23.1 percent on a 15.6 percent increase in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 65.6 percent in its non-package business that
includes a new subsidiary set up to help companies that sell their
products on the Internet and a new insurance business.
</P>
