<HEADLINE> GM Allowed To Operate Savings Bank  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- General Motors Corp., the world's largest
automaker, received permission Thursday to operate a savings bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Office Of Thrift Supervision's approval clears the way for
the Detroit-based automaker to open a federally chartered bank.
GMAC Bank will be a full-service banking operation. It will be
based in Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   OTS said GMAC will offer its services to the public through its
Wilmington office but will conduct the majority of its business
through GMAC Mortgage Corp., an existing company that OTS also
approved to be an operating subsidiary of the thrift.
</P>
<P>
   Through the arrangement, GMAC Bank will be one of the nation's
largest originators of residential mortgage loans and home equity
loans, OTS said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, a number of companies have received new savings and
loan charters from OTS, which is part of the Treasury Department.
They include agribusiness giant Archer Daniels Midland Co.,
long-distance telephone company Excel Communications Inc. and
coffin manufacturer Hillenbrand Industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
