<HEADLINE> Knight Ridder Earnings Rise 10 Pct.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Knight Ridder, the nation's
second-largest newspaper publisher, reported a 10 percent rise in
first-quarter earnings before a special gain as stronger
advertising revenues and lower newsprint costs lifted profits.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding a one-time gain from the sale of several Internet
investments, Knight Ridder, which publishes 31 daily newspapers
including the San Jose Mercury News, earned $68.9 million in the
first three months of the year compared to $62.9 million in the
same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Per-share earnings were 74 cents, edging analysts' expectations
of 73 cents, as measured by First Call/Thomson Financial. The
year-ago earnings were equivalent to 65 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Its shares were priced at $47.81\ at 5:15 p.m. EST on the New
York Stock Exchange, down 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Knight Ridder earned $92 million from the sales of two
companies, Cadabra, an Internet software company, and Prio, an
online coupon company. In connection with those transactions, the
company received stock in GoTo.com and InfoSpace.com.
</P>
<P>
   Including the gains, Knight Ridder had net earnings of $161
million, or $1.74 per share.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a solid performance, propelled by strength in our large
West Coast markets, sustained robust national advertising, strong
classified and lower newsprint costs,'' chairman and CEO Tony
Ridder said.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising revenue for the quarter was up 4.7 percent,
classified advertising was up 6.6 percent, but retail revenue fell
1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Total circulation was flat, while costs were up a total of 2.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues rose 5 percent to $808 million from $771 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
