<DOCNO> APW20000420.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State deal gives firefighters free cameras to find fires  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Fifty fire departments Thursday became the
first to collect free cameras that can spot fires -- or people --
behind walls in a $7.5 million deal that the state and the
manufacturer say is the first of its kind in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   By December, every local fire district will have at least one of
the cameras and be eligible to buy more. And thanks to the state
contract, the cost will be $7,695 -- well less than half of the
camera's $18,000 list price.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an investment. It's an investment in people's lives,''
said Department of Community Affairs Commissioner Jane M. Kenny.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras register heat rather than light so firefighters can
see fires through building walls and other surfaces. They are
sensitive enough to register body heat, allowing rescue workers to
spot people who might be trapped inside burning buildings.
</P>
<P>
   That will help save the lives of both people in danger and those
trying to rescue them, firefighters said.
</P>
<P>
   Bought individually, cameras of this type can cost between
$18,000 and $25,000. They are used like a normal video camera and
can be mounted on a helmet, with color or black and white monitors.
Some departments have purchased cameras with the help of corporate
and civic sponsors and fund-raising drives.
</P>
<P>
   And for some small fire departments, the only way they could get
the cameras is through this state program.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a word it's absolutely incredible. It's a tremendous
help,'' said Alfred Loverdi, chief of Runnemede Fire Co. No. 1, the
volunteer fire department in that Camden County town.
</P>
<P>
   Loverdi said his department looked into buying one of the
cameras but was hampered by the high price tag. Now since his group
shares services with two other nearby towns, ''we'll have access to
three at a time if we need them,'' Loverdi said.
</P>
<P>
   With the state picking up the tab, Loverdi said his town can
spend money on other needed equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Gov. Christie Whitman signed legislation authorizing
the purchase. The $7.5 million will cover the cost of buying the
750 cameras and also will provide money to reimburse some
departments that already bought a unit. Each of the state's 750
local fire departments will have at least one camera. Some will get
more, based on population.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm proud that New Jersey is the first state in the nation to
ensure that every community has access to this lifesaving
technology,'' Whitman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The state will also provide new computer software that gives
fire departments information on fires.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thermal imaging cameras and this software are two new
tools that will help make New Jersey a national leader in fire
safety,'' said William Cane, director of fire safety for the
Division of Community Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny said the potential for saving lives and property made the
decision to spend the money easy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's one of those pieces of technology that make so much
sense,'' Kenny said. ''It really is an investment. It's a good one
because its going to save lives and prevent injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer E.D. Bullard of Cynthiana, Ky., has agreed to
provide at least 100 of the cameras per month to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's contract is the biggest for the company and one of
the largest in the industry, according to Tom Kiddle, a product
manager at Bullard. The volume of the deal allows Bullard to slash
the price of the camera, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's big and big enough so we were able to get breaks from
our suppliers,'' Kiddle said. Now possibly four other states are
interested in similar packages, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
