<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Oil Smuggling on Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In enforcing U.N. sanctions against Iraq,
authorities have caught 17 ships for suspected oil smuggling this
year, nearly as many as during all of 1999, the Pentagon said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's been actually a lot of activity in the anti-smuggling
operation in the Gulf this month,'' said Pentagon spokesman Ken
Bacon -- eight ships stopped in April with a determination that oil
would be confiscated from six of them.
</P>
<P>
   Under the interdiction procedure used by a maritime force of 18
nations, ships are detained, authorities figure out whether they
are carrying Iraqi oil, and those that are would be diverted to a
place where the oil can be unloaded, confiscated and sold -- partly
to offset the costs of the anti-smuggling operation.
</P>
<P>
   In all of last year, oil from 19 ships was confiscated, but
smuggling has risen dramatically this year because higher oil
prices made it more profitable, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the effort to enforce the U.N. sanctions, U.S. officials
said earlier this year that illicit oil exports from Iraq were
averaging 100,000 barrels a day, compared with 50,000 barrels in
1998, when oil prices were much lower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
