<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bush Focus on School Safety  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LEE, N.J. (AP) -- Republican George W. Bush earned rare
praise Thursday from Democratic rival Al Gore for marking the
Columbine massacre with a focus on teaching kids values. Gore also
toned down his criticism of Bush on gun control, saying it was not
''the one main solution'' to youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   In separate forums mostly stripped of signs that they were
campaign stops, the presidential candidates presented multifaceted
remedies for the kind of teen rage that erupted into gunfire and
bomb throwing one year ago at the Colorado high school.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in Texas, suggested the Clinton-Gore White House had been
lax on gun control. ''It's important for the next administration to
do something a little different and that's enforce laws on the
books,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas governor's real focus was on character education.
He offered proposals for teaching students better values, including
giving American Youth Character Awards to honor young people and
requiring federal programs ''affecting young people'' to include an
ethics component.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can pass laws in society and enforce laws, but it's also
important to remember much of what violence takes place is a matter
of heart,'' Bush said. ''I strongly believe this kind of character
education is so important in making sure children make the right
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would increase federal grants for character
education from $8 million to $25 million and let students transfer
out of dangerous schools. He also renewed his call for any juvenile
convicted of a serious gun or violent offense to be banned from
ever buying or carrying a gun.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Gore saluted what he called Bush's talk ''about
character and spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I compliment him for doing that,'' Gore told an assembly at
Fort Lee High School. ''I think that's right near the top of the
list. I think that's a big part of this also. But if we are serious
in the aftermath of Columbine, we have to make some serious
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is counting on proposals for stricter gun laws to win
him votes over Bush, told parents and students that Bush opposes
mandatory child-safety trigger locks and, as governor of Texas,
overturned the state's 125-year-old ban on concealed weapons,
making it possible for hidden guns to be brought into places of
worship.
</P>
<P>
   ''What gives?'' Gore asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the lessons of Columbine is that we have to stand up to
the NRA and the gun industry and get guns out of the hands of
people who shouldn't have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ''I don't think that guns represent the one main
solution to this problem.'' He talked about curbing violence in
entertainment, alleviating overcrowded schools and offering
government help to stressed-out working parents.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not settled for some easy, glib silver-bullet
answer,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Tipper, appeared on CBS' ''Early Show'' and said that
''easy access to guns on the Internet'' was a frequent concern of
teens she met in recent campaign forums. ''They say they can order
guns, they can order parts to guns and put them together,'' Mrs.
Gore lamented.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and the vice president observed the solemnity of
Thursday's anniversary by toning down the fierce partisanship that
has characterized their campaign. In the Fort Lee auditorium, there
were none of the usual Gore campaign posters, only three yellow
ovals scrawled with the message ''Safe Schools.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no campaign signs in Texas either. Instead, a large
yellow paper sign with green lettering said: ''Cater Elementary
Welcomes Governor Bush.'' Student signatures and smiley faces
decorated the banner.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he was making his appearance, in part, to fulfill a
promise to the father of one of the Columbine students killed last
year.
</P>
<P>
   At a Denver-area memorial, the father ''said into my ear as we
were embracing, he said, 'Promise me that these children have not
died in vain.' And then after a moment's pause he repeated with
urgency and force, 'Promise me,''' Gore recalled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'I promise' and that's the kind of promise you take
into your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Associated Press Writer Jim Vertuno contributed
to this report from Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
