<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Incoming Steel Drops Almost 10 Pct.  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Steel imports dropped by almost 10 percent in
March, continuing a general trend downward over the last six
months, the Commerce Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 9.8 percent decrease followed an increase in February, but
the imports have been heading downward since last year, fueled in
part by the recovery of the domestic steel industry.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, steel industry officials are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The import level of 2.8 million metric tons, is a drop from 3
million in February. There have been declines in five of the last
six months and for all of 1999, steel imports fell by 14 percent.	   Greg
Mastel, an economist at the New America Foundation, a
Washington think tank, said the data indicate the American steel
industry is improving, but imports are still high.
</P>
<P>
   ''We may be past the worst of the steel crisis but imports are
still 50 percent above where they were in 1993,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew G. Sharkey, CEO of the American Iron and Steel Institute
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''AISI and its members are not out of the woods -- world steel
capacity remains a severe problem and adverse effects of the 1986
surge continue,'' he said. ''We urge all due vigilance to this
year's trends, because they are both familiar and threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Imports of cold-rolled, hot-rolled, wire rod and semifinished
steel rose from their January levels. But imports of cut-to-length
plate steel fell.
</P>
<P>
   Among the major sources of foreign steel, imports from Brazil,
Korea and Russia fell while imports from China and Japan increased.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Butler, president of the Japan Steel Information Center,
said the data indicate that imports have stabilized. He said much
of the demand for imports has come from American mills that cannot
produce enough steel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
