<HEADLINE> Duracell Drags Down Gillette Profit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Despite overall growth in revenues, Gillette Co.
reported a decline in first quarter earnings Thursday on weaker
results in its Duracell battery line.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette had net income of $258 million, down 4 percent from
$269 million a year earlier. Per-share earnings were 24 cents, two
cents above Wall Street expectations and unchanged from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues rose 5 percent to $2.05 billion from $1.94 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette reported higher sales in most of its product lines,
which include Braun products, razors and blades, and Oral-B
toothbrushes. But Duracell sales dropped 2 percent, with a 33
percent decline in profits.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette spokesman Eric Kraus said marketing costs and
unfavorable foreign exchange rates, particularly in Europe, also
dragged down earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The decline continued a recent trend for Gillette, which saw
declining profits in the fourth quarter last year as the company
worked to boost sales in underperforming sectors of its business,
including blades and razors.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's shares were priced at $37.62{ at 5:15 p.m. EST on the
New York Stock Exchange, up 50 cents or more than 1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
