<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Funds Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Assets of the nation's retail money market
mutual funds fell by $9.52 billion in the latest week to $1.004
trillion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Assets of taxable money market funds in the retail category fell
by $6.86 billion to $834.86 billion for the week ended Wednesday,
the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said. Tax-exempt fund
assets fell by $2.66 billion to $169.63 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Assets of institutional money market funds fell by $12.46
billion to $692.68 billion for the same period. Among institutional
funds, taxable money market fund assets fell by $8.45 billion to
$643.35 billion; assets of tax-exempt funds fell by $4.00 billion
to $49.33 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Total money market assets stood at $1.697 trillion for the week.
</P>
<P>
   Assets for the previous week were revised to $1.719 trillion to
reflect reporting errors and a change in the number of funds
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 5.47 percent from 5.45 percent the
previous week, said Money Fund Report, a service of iMoneyNet Inc.
in Westboro, Mass. The 30-day average yield rose to 5.44 percent
from 5.40 percent, according to Money Fund Report.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-day compounded yield rose to 5.62 percent from 5.60
percent the previous week, and the 30-day compounded yield rose to
5.59 percent from 5.54 percent, Money Fund Report.
</P>
<P>
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds
remained unchanged at 48 days, said Money Fund Report.
</P>
<P>
   The online service bankrate.com said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks
in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the annual percentage
yield available on money market accounts rose to 2.04 percent as of
Wednesday from 2.03 percent a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based unit of Intelligent Life Corp.
said the annual percentage yield available on interest-bearing
checking accounts kept at 0.83 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bankrate.com said the annual percentage yield was 4.96 percent
on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 4.94 percent the
previous week. Yields were 5.34 percent on 1-year CDs, down from
5.36 percent; 5.64 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 5.61 percent;
and unchanged at 6.00 percent on 5-year CDs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
