<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pippen: Blazers Hungry for Title  </HEADLINE>
By LANDON HALL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUALATIN, Ore. (AP) -- They all came to Portland with their best
days behind them, hoping to give the young Trail Blazers enough
leadership and veteran guile to win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after their first regular season together, Scottie Pippen,
Steve Smith and Detlef Schrempf get to see whether all their
experience will be enough to get the Blazers close to their goal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're a very hungry team,'' six-time champion Scottie Pippen
said before Thursday's practice as the Blazers prepare for Sunday's
Game 1 of their best-of-five series against Minnesota. ''These
players have a chance to do something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland advanced to the Western Conference finals last year,
only to be swept 4-0 by the San Antonio Spurs. The seasoned Spurs
exposed the Blazers as a temperamental bunch that wilted under
pressure despite their talent.
</P>
<P>
   When the unpredictable Isaiah Rider is your best player, there's
only so far you can go. With billionaire owner Paul Allen's vast
resources and his deep desire for a title, big changes were on the
way.
</P>
<P>
   In came Pippen, who was traded from Houston for six Blazers --
one of whom, Stacey Augmon, was waived and wound up back in
Portland; next was Smith, who was traded for Rider and Jim Jackson;
and then Schrempf, signed as a free agent after being discarded by
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Their salaries caused the Blazers' payroll to balloon to almost
$74 million, and what Allen really bought was the kind of
experience the Spurs had.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, Smith and Schrempf have appeared in 331 playoff games,
led by Pippen's 182. The other eight players in the Blazers'
rotation have 322 postseason games, and 98 of those belong to
backup point guard Greg Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   ''You want to come to an organization that has a window of
opportunity better than others, and I think we have that,'' Smith
said. ''We have a good chance, and we're probably one of six teams
that really have a legitimate chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen and Smith have had mixed results. Each has played
brilliantly at times but also wallowed in terrible slumps. Pippen
seemed to score only when he had to, or when he had a lane to the
basket and wanted to show he still could cut and slash at age 34.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf has been a dependable reserve, but has talked of
retirement after 14 seasons. He averaged 7.5 points, his lowest
since his rookie season, and saw his minutes cut from 35.3 last
season to 21.6.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Schrempf, Pippen and Smith welcomed their reduced roles.
Pippen averaged 33.5 minutes, down from a career-high 40 last
season. And Smith's minutes (32.8, down from 36.5 last season)
allowed him to keep his bad knees healthy and play in all 82 games
for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ''They all accepted and wanted reduced minutes, and they all had
very good years,'' said Blazers president and general manager Bob
Whitsitt. ''It allowed us to get some of the younger guys minutes
and let them play.''
</P>
<P>
   Second-year shooting guard Bonzi Wells appears to be the next
Blazers' star. The 23-year-old player averaged 8.8 points this
season, double his average from last season, and will make his
first playoff appearance Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bonzi's grown up,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his advice regarding the playoffs was, Pippen
replied: ''You just relax and play hard. It's like the regular
season; the games are just a little bit more intense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 1917 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000420.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> As health insurance costs rise, employers begin trimming coverage  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Despite New Jersey's booming economy and
historically low unemployment, the number of uninsured residents is
growing, partly because employers facing rising premiums are
starting to scale back coverage.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the number of Garden State residents covered
by government health insurance programs fell about 20 percent from
1995 to 1998, as welfare reform resulted in thousands of poor
people losing Medicaid coverage. Together, those factors left an
estimated 1.3 million people, or 16.4 percent of state residents,
without health insurance in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Health coverage provided by New Jersey employers peaked in 1997.
That happened after two years that saw extremely low increases in
health insurance premiums as managed care companies infiltrated the
market following the state's 1993 deregulation of hospital rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we're entering a period where premiums are going up faster
than income again, so I think we can expect further erosion of
employer-sponsored coverage,'' Joel Cantor, director of the Rutgers
Center for State Health Policy, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That situation leaves many low-income working families unable to
afford their portion of the premiums, and nudges some employers to
raise salaries, at least for low-paid workers, rather than provide
health insurance, Cantor explained.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, employers in New Jersey were hit with the biggest
jump in health insurance premiums for their workers since 1996, an
average of 6.6 percent, according to the survey by the New Jersey
Business &AMP; Industry Association, the nation's largest statewide
employer association.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10 percent of its 16,000 member companies responded, and
43 percent reported double-digit increases in health plan costs in
1999. Worse yet, 36 percent said they expected their costs to rise
10 percent or more this year. The average premium cost per employee
last year was $5,214, or 13 percent of the members' average payroll
cost of $40,138.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the percentage of employers providing health
insurance to full-time workers and their dependents dipped to 74
percent in 1999, down from 78 percent a year earlier and 80 percent
in 1997. The survey also found a tiny decline in the percentage
covering just full-time workers, from 94 percent in 1997 and 1998
to 93 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the labor market as tight as it is and with the
difficulties employers already have attracting talented workers, if
they give up health benefits they've lost half the game,''
association spokesman Christopher Biddle said Thursday. ''I think
that's why we haven't seen a more dramatic increase'' in employers
eliminating coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the survey found 50 percent of companies are shifting
more cost onto their workers, through higher premiums, copayments
or deductibles. Already, 90 percent of the employer-sponsored
health plans in the state are some form of managed care, making it
tougher for companies to cut their premiums by changing insurers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Profitability has been strong, but the only way employers
today can improve their profitability is to increase productivity
and cut costs,'' because stiffer, sometimes global, competition
makes it difficult to raise prices, Biddle said.
</P>
<P>
   Data from the state Department of Health and Senior Services
show that the number of people covered by employer-sponsored plans,
5.025 million in 1998, and the number of people buying their own
health insurance, about 528,000 that year, were inching up from
1995 until 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But over the same period, the number of state residents insured
through the Medicaid and Medicare programs fell from 1.472 million
to 1.21 million and the number of uninsured New Jersey residents
rose to 1.329 million.
</P>
<P>
   The rising health care costs and health insurance premiums here,
as well as the slight pullback in employer coverage, both follow
national trends that began around 1996, Cantor said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're right in the middle of the pack in the percentage of our
population uninsured, but we're No. 2 in (per capita) income,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   That high income, however, is offset by the fact that New Jersey
companies pay the nation's second-highest health insurance
premiums, after Massachusetts, Cantor noted. Data from a Census
Bureau survey found the average premium companies paid for family
coverage in 1996 was $5,846 in New Jersey, compared with $4,954
nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-20-00 1918 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000420.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Avs Determined To Eradicate Coyotes  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MOSSMAN, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Having won eight straight games to end the regular
season and the first three games of their playoff series with
Phoenix, the Colorado Avalanche perhaps forget how they had
fashioned such a streak.
</P>
<P>
   Not by being outplayed in the first period and falling behind
3-0, that's for sure.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche couldn't overcome that early deficit Wednesday
night, falling to the Coyotes 3-2 in Game 4 thanks to superb
goaltending by Sean Burke.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of gaining a sweep of the first-round, best-of-seven
series, the Avalanche return home Friday night for Game 5 in what
they regard as a must-win mode.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want to go back to Phoenix'' for Game 6, Avalanche
wing Dave Andreychuk said Thursday. ''They've got some momentum
right now, and it would give them a lot of momentum if they win
another game.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got a good lesson last night, that if we're not ready to
play, that team can beat us. They came out flying in the first
period and put us back on our heels. We came back and dominated in
the second and third periods, when we had a lot of chances. But the
bottom line is we didn't win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got to be ready to play in Game 5, especially in our own
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Avs defenseman Aaron Miller agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we learned a valuable lesson,'' Miller said.
''Hopefully, it doesn't cost us too much. I don't think anyone in
here thought we were going to win 16 games straight and win the
Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   If they did, they were awakened from that dream quickly.
Outplayed in every department, the Avalanche were outshot 15-6 in
the first period, during which the Coyotes grabbed a 2-0 lead on
goals by rookie Trevor Letowski and Travis Green.
</P>
<P>
   Just 38 seconds into the second period, Mikael Renberg's goal
made it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado outshot Phoenix 32-16 over the last two periods,
putting constant pressure on Burke and peppering him with shots.
But a second-period goal by Andreychuk and a third-period score by
Adam Deadmarsh were all the Avs could muster.
</P>
<P>
   ''They came out the way we expected in the first period, and we
didn't match their intensity,'' Colorado captain Joe Sakic said.
''The goal they got on the first shift of the second period hurt
us, and the way Burke was playing, it was too much to come back
from. A two-goal lead is one thing, but three ...
</P>
<P>
   ''We had tons of chances, but Burke played very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke, subjected to months of speculation that the Coyotes would
be better off yielding to the salary demands of holdout goalie
Nikolai Khabibulin, finished with 36 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could sense a little bit more of a purpose in our dressing
room,'' Burke said. ''That team over there has so many talented
players. If we have anybody take a night off or even a shift off,
it's going to hurt us.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was a great game for us. If we can go into Colorado and
play like we did in Game 4, we can win another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Letowski said Burke was ''huge. Here's a guy who's been doubted
a lot. We can't say enough about Burkie. He was the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix coach Bob Francis promised a repeat performance by his
team on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of pride on this team and, believe me, you're
going to see the same type of effort in Colorado,'' he said. ''We
realize we've got our work cut out for us, but we're going in there
with all guns firing and try to get this series back to Phoenix for
our fans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
