<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Researcher Doubts Royal Remains  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A skeleton identified for decades as that of
Macedonian King Philip II, father of Alexander the Great, may be
actually the remains of Alexander's half brother, a new study
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   In a study appearing Friday in the journal Science, a Greek
researcher said that bone scars once used to identify the body are
natural features of the skull.
</P>
<P>
   Antonis Bartsiokas of the Anaximandrian Institute in Voula,
Greece, said his analysis of the remains from a royal tomb at
Vergina, a town in northern Greece near the site of the ancient
Macedonian capital, suggests that the skeleton is that King Philip
III Arrhidaeus.
</P>
<P>
   King Philip II was a noted fourth century B.C. military leader
from Macedonia who took control of Athens and Thebes. He was
assassinated in 336 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   In a famous battle in 354 B.C., Philip was hit in the right eye
by an arrow, but recovered to win many more battles and rule for
another 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   Philip's successor, son Alexander, went on to conquer most of
the known world, stretching from Greece and Egypt eastward across
Asia to India. Alexander died in 323 B.C. and his body was buried
in Egypt and has since been lost.
</P>
<P>
   A research team in 1977 found a tomb containing a royal couple
at Vergina and identified the male remains as King Philip II. The
identification was based mainly on what experts said were healed
bone scars from the arrow wound to the right eye.
</P>
<P>
   But Bartsiokas said in his Science report that the marks on the
skull are actually natural anatomical features, not the result of
wounds. The researcher also said he found of no evidence of healing
in the bone.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, artifacts found in the tomb were dated at about
317 B.C., a generation after the assassination of King Philip II in
336 B.C. Bartisiokas said this suggests the royal remains are those
of the king and queen who ruled after Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   King Philip III ruled for six years after Alexander's death and
was murdered in 317 B.C.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 1933 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
