<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Platinum, Palladium Prices Fall  </HEADLINE>
By BENNIE M. CURRIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Platinum prices fell to the lowest level in more than a month
Thursday amid profit-taking as investors prepared for a shortened
week due to the Easter holiday.
</P>
<P>
   In other commodity markets, coffee futures closed higher, while
pork bellies and palladium fell.
</P>
<P>
   Traders have been awaiting activity in Russian exports since
last month when that country's leader, Vladimir Putin, signed a
much-anticipated quota for metal exports. Russia is the world's No.
1 exporter for palladium, which is in heavy demand to make cars'
catalytic converters and semiconductors, and No. 2 for platinum
behind South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, platinum for July delivery fell $9 to $462.80 an
ounce on the Comex division of the New York Mercantile Exchange.
June palladium dipped $12.20 to $562.10 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   Metals prices had been soaring during Russia's strategic absence
from the market. Russia has been promising for weeks to clear up
supposed bureaucratic red tape and resume exports.
</P>
<P>
   But market observers said Thursday's activity was due more to
profit-taking than to rumors circulating about the possible
resumption of exports.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rumors that the Russians may resume shipments have made
the market pretty tight, but what we saw today was probably based
more on profit-taking,'' said Vanessa Motto, a metals analyst for
the CPM Group in New York. ''With the Easter holiday approaching,
you do see some weakness around that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffee closed $2.05 higher at 97.75 cents a pound Thursday on
New York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange as the market rebounded
from last week's six-month low. Typically, spring coffee prices
rise amid concerns of frost damage to May and June crops in Brazil.
Investors were also speculating that recent increases in coffee
stocks would soon level off.
</P>
<P>
   Pork futures were down on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Pork
bellies dropped .55 cent to 97.65 cents a pound, down from a
3{-year high amid expectations for fewer slaughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
