<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First-round Playoff Sweep for Kings  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Kings got a new arena, a new
coach and some new players that helped them return to the playoffs
this season. But the result was the same: a first-round exit for
the second time in three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Red Wings swept the Kings in four games, the same
thing that happened to Los Angeles against St. Louis in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four games with Detroit were close -- a 2-0 loss in
the opener, then a 2-1 defeat in Game 3 and a 3-0 loss in Game 4.
But the Kings hurt themselves by going 0-for-23 on the power play
and never playing with a lead in the four games.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a lot better team than we did in '98. Everyone's
trying to compare it and saying, 'Well, you got swept again,' but
this team was much, much better,'' captain Rob Blake said. ''That's
what makes it so frustrating, that we didn't get a win in this
series.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake didn't score in the playoffs against a Detroit defense
that played him tightly. He was limited to four shots in 31 minutes
of the series finale Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Also shut down were Glen Murray and Bryan Smolinski, neither of
whom had a goal or an assist in the playoffs. Jozef Stumpel didn't
score, either, and Luc Robitaille, who had 37 goals in the regular
season, was held to two in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We lost to a very good team,'' said Andy Murray, who had a
39-31-12 record in his first season as an NHL coach. ''We feel we
didn't play up to our normal standard of play and we're
disappointed by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray consoled himself by noting that the Kings had a 6-5
scoring advantage when playing even strength against the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did a lot of positive things. We played some pretty
exciting hockey, we scored some goals this year,'' he said. ''We
couldn't seem to generate them here in the playoffs, but our team
played real hard this year.''
</P>
<P>
   One area in which Murray believes the team succeeded was in
playing hard consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right from day one of training camp we tried to instill a new
attitude, a new work ethic, a new level of commitment on the part
of our players,'' he said. ''It's all about eliminating excuses and
making commitments, and our team did that from day one this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 2007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
