<DOCNO> APW20000420.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Just Phil Jackson and the Trophy  </HEADLINE>
By JIM LITKE, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Stern is apparently busy plotting how to broadcast NBA
games on the backs of fans' eyelids. In the meantime, someone has
to say a few good words about the upcoming playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So here are seven of them: Come for basketball, stay for Phil
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he figures to be around at the end. For another,
he will have the league's most entertaining team in tow. Need a
3-point play? Watch Phil teach Jack Nicholson how that
rather-be-lucky-than-good grin is supposed to look.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is easy to underestimate. He almost seems to prefer it.
He will be the first to say the Lakers aren't the Bulls, just like
L.A. isn't Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are comparisons. The Lakers play defense, they score
fast enough to bury opponents and they've learned to like winning --
tearing off consecutive streaks of 16, 19 and 11 games on the way
to 67 regular-season wins.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson never forgets the difference between this team and
that one, either. That's what makes this such a good story.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers could stumble anywhere along the way and next season
half of L.A.'s celebrity row will be looking at Jackson and swear
it's Del Harris with a supply of ''Just for Men.'' Or the Lakers
could win it all. And then this time, when Jackson has his picture
taken with the NBA trophy, Michael Jordan won't be anywhere in the
frame.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's genius is not inspirational leadership. He doesn't
yell at (or choke) players to get their attention. He whistles. But
if his own ballplayers ever caught Jackson on ESPN Classic or were
old enough to have seen him play, they'd know why he talks so much
about ''energy.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jackson did get off the bench for the great Knicks teams of
the late 1960s and early '70s, he had only a few minutes to make a
difference. And so he attacked the ball from every conceivable
angle, all elbows and knees, happy for the chance to sacrifice.
Nobody ever tried harder.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jackson sat down again and paid attention. It didn't take
him long to figure out that despite those brief mood swings, the
teams with the most talent on the floor almost always won. When
Doug Collins got axed in Chicago, Jackson was on his staff, lucky
enough to be in the right place at the right time. Keeping his
place, though, was another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson learned to respect talent by respecting the best. That
quality cuts to the heart of his credibility with kids the same age
as his own. He can watch Kobe Bryant and Shaquille O'Neal do their
best and honestly say he's seen better. Because he has. He learned
how to coax that effort out of others. It wasn't a coincidence that
Jackson walked in the door and stories of the Shaq-Kobe feuds dried
up.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lakers went on that first unbeaten streak, they arrived
in Milwaukee at 15 and counting on a midwinter night. In the
hallway before the game, Jackson said it wouldn't break his heart
if Los Angeles lost, because defeats made for better teaching
tools. In the locker room, meanwhile, the same bunch known for
years as underachievers was actually sweating out how it was going
to win one more.
</P>
<P>
   They won No. 16 that night, but lost the next game in
Indianapolis. Seven teams already had been on win streaks of 16
games when this Lakers team did it. But Jackson knew that only two
of those teams -- the 1971-72 Lakers and his 1995-96 Bulls -- went on
to win championships. A month later, Jackson came through Chicago
and said his new team still had plenty to learn about closing
games, especially come playoff time. Thus nudged, the Lakers ran
off two more double-digit win streaks.
</P>
<P>
   At practice Thursday, Jackson even provided the introductions
for one of those up-close-and-personal segments they often show
before games. It's not as compelling as the material that would
have been available if the coaches weren't so darn stubborn about
wearing the mikes Stern bought on another one of his technology
jags. But it isn't half-bad, either.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here it is, the moment we all play for,'' Jackson said. ''We
all feel real positive going into the playoffs. There are no easy
routes. Now, the next step is here.''
</P>
<P>
   All season long, the tributes have been piling up, but Jackson
moved them to the corner of his office and talked around them,
trading on his reputation as an eccentric. But the underlying
lesson his players should have grasped by now sounds like something
he picked up along the waterfront in his New York days: All that
smooth sailing didn't mean a thing if the ship doesn't make it into
the port.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
