<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Town makes new history with convictions of officers  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW MILFORD, Conn. (AP) -- When Mario and Vera Sinapi moved here
from New York City 25 years ago, they never expected the town with
its quaint, historic Main Street and town green would be rife with
big-city controversy.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, two police officers have been convicted on
charges related to separate civilian deaths and earlier this year,
a police sergeant was charged with drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very unusual,'' said Mario Sinapi, a retired New York
deputy fire chief. ''The town is becoming a city. It's changing, no
doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Incorporated in 1712, New Milford now has about 24,000
residents, making it one of the largest towns in the state. Still,
much of the rural, New England atmosphere permeates as residents
try to accept the change that creeps in amid the well-preserved,
18th-century buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I first came here, it was great,'' said Emily D'Alessio,
who moved from Brooklyn, N.Y., 35 years ago. ''But these things do
happen-- you can't say when, or how, or why. It's everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Officer William Scribner, a 14-year veteran of the
police force, was convicted of negligent homicide stemming from the
June 1998 death of 17-year-old girl whose car was struck by his
speeding cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks ago, former officer Scott Smith was convicted of
manslaughter for fatally shooting an unarmed suspect at point-blank
range. He faces 5 to 40 years in prison when he is sentenced May 5.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Sgt. James Duda was charged with drunken driving
following a November accident in which he crashed his personal car
into a utility pole. A month later, the state Department of Motor
Vehicles ruled that Duda could keep his driver's license so he
could continue to work.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the police department-- particularly Smith-- is
evident throughout the town. A bright blue pickup truck parked
outside the police station carries a large sign proclaiming ''We
Support Scott Smith.'' Other vehicles bear bumper stickers with the
message ''Scott Smith Not Guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the M&AMP;B Market, Lorri Barker accepts donations in the
form of clothes, furniture and other goods for a tag sale to
benefit the Scott Smith Legal Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most people are outraged. I mean literally outraged,'' said
Barker, of neighboring Roxbury. ''I'm just mad about the whole
thing. I think Scott Smith is being railroaded.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting Police Chief Colin McCormack says the town has been very
supportive. The 19-year veteran of the city force took the helm
after Chief James Sweeney left the post in August to take a job at
a private school.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack maintains a professional and polite demeanor when
speaking about the strife surrounding the officers' convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, it has an effect on people,'' he said. ''But we're
a professional law enforcement agency and we must move ahead. ...
It's a challenge, but we'll persevere.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hanzelko, who says he has friends on the police force,
acknowledges the widespread support for Smith and Scribner, but
does not share the sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what Smith did was wrong. I don't think his life was
in danger,'' said Hanzelko, who moved here from the Bridgeport area
three years ago. ''It just seems like police can get away with
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sinapis had differing perspectives on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''Years ago, they didn't investigate it,'' said Vera Sinapi.
''It was just a man doing his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he stands behind the police, Mario Sinapi said, ''You've
got the other side, too. Some guys are cops just for the
authority.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, residents seemed confident that the rash of woes was
not evidence of a larger problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's bad luck,'' said Hanzelko. ''Most of it's
coincidence, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman at the mayor's office said Arthur Peitler was too busy
Thursday to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sylvie Kirkwood enjoyed a late morning stroll along
the town green.
</P>
<P>
   Do the headlines tarnish her image of this town?
</P>
<P>
   ''No,'' she said with a smile. ''I don't think so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
