<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, April 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Leaves Elian Case To Reno
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- While tempers flare and passions rise in the five-month
Elian Gonzalez custody case, President Clinton is standing back and leaving the
decisions to Attorney General Janet Reno. ''The attorney general is leading the
effort,'' presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart said. Clinton said today that the
boy should be promptly reunited with his father, now that a federal court has
ruled that Elian must stay in the United States until the court decides whether
he should get an asylum hearing. A hearing was set for May 11.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Family, Friends Mark Columbine Anniversary
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- At private ceremonies and public remembrances all
day and into the night today, students, staff, survivors and strangers came
together to remember the first anniversary of the Columbine High School
shooting. Coloradans fell silent while a church bell tolled 13 times at 11:21
a.m. today, the precise moment Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris began the
bloodbath, killing 12 students and a teacher and wounding 26 before taking their
own lives.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Documents Reveal South Korean Killings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DOKCHON, South Korea (AP) -- According to declassified U.S. military
documents, South Korean soldiers and police, observed at times by U.S. Army
officers, executed more than 2,000 political prisoners without trial in the
early weeks of the Korean War. Supreme commander Gen. Douglas MacArthur became
aware of at least one of the mass shootings, according to documents originally
classified ''top secret.'' The new information, detailed in reporting by The
Associated Press and a Korean researcher, substantiates what some historians
have long believed: Large numbers of South Korean leftists arrested by the
right-wing regime were secretly killed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
No Smoke, Dementia Prevention Link
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The most rigorous study ever to investigate the link between
dementia and Alzheimer's disease has concluded that cigarettes provide no
protection against mental decline. In research published this week in the
British Medical Journal, scientists from Oxford University found male doctors
who smoked were just as likely to develop dementia and Alzheimer's as their
counterparts who had never smoked or had quit years before. Earlier studies on
the relationship between smoking and dementia, a major component of Alzheimer's,
produced conflicting results, with some showing an apparent benefit.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Govt: Overweight Need More Exercise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The vast majority of overweight adults trying to shed pounds
aren't getting enough exercise, the government said today. A 1998 national
survey by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention found that 53.8 percent
of American adults reported being overweight and that half of them were trying
to lose weight. Most of those trying to lose weight -- 62.7 percent -- were
exercising, but only 28 percent said they exercised 30 minutes a day at least
five days a week, the minimum government recommendation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Zimbabwe White-Owned Farms Rampaged
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Nearly 200 attackers rampaged through a white-owned
farm Thursday in northern Zimbabwe, beating dogs to death and burning down
workers' homes a day after a leader of the farm occupations promised to end
hostilities. The attack was the latest violence by armed squatters who have
occupied nearly 1,000 white-owned farms across Zimbabwe over the past two
months. In the past week, two farmers have been killed, six others have been
abducted and beaten, and several farmhouses set ablaze.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tentative Northwest Air Deal Reached
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EAGAN, Minn. (AP) -- Northwest Airlines and its flight attendants union
reached a tentative contract agreement today. ''We have reached a tentative
agreement, subject to ratification, with Local 2000 regarding a new contract for
our 11,000 flight attendants,'' said Doug Steeneland, executive vice president
and chief corporate officer. On a recorded hot line, Teamsters Local 2000
President Billie Davenport said an agreement was reached in Seattle, Wash., but
didn't provide details.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 169; Nasdaq Falls 62
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks rose sharply today and technology stocks
ended modestly lower as investors took some profits from big gains Monday and
Tuesday and struggled to chart a course in the volatile sector. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 169.09 to close at 10,844.05. The Dow ended the four-day
week with a gain of 538.28 points, or 5.2 percent. The Nasdaq composite index
fell 62.53 to close at 3,643.88.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jordan Takes Stock of Wizards Season
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Michael Jordan went one-on-one with each member of the
Washington Wizards today, promising changes and a whole new attitude. The
Wizards finished the season 29-53. Jordan, who become the president of
basketball operations and a part-owner of the team on Jan. 19, has said he wants
to hire a coach within a month and overhaul the front office.
</P>
