<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tentative Northwest Air Deal Reached  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAGAN, Minn. (AP) -- Northwest Airlines and its flight
attendants' union, which has been seeking a new contract for 3{
years, reached agreement Thursday on a tentative deal.
</P>
<P>
   Ballots to 11,000 flight attendants, who rejected a tentative
agreement last August, will be mailed next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are pleased to reach this agreement and believe it is a
fair one for all parties,'' said Doug Steeneland, the company's
chief corporate officer.
</P>
<P>
   On a recorded hot line, Teamsters Local 2000 President Billie
Davenport said an agreement was reached Thursday in Seattle, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ''They offered us increases in pay and pension that we thought
were good enough to take to our members,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a statement posted on the union Web site, the
tentative deal includes:
</P>
<P>
   --Industry-leading pension rates, increased from $35 to $65 per
month per year of service, which is nearly an 86 percent
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   --Stronger work rules.
</P>
<P>
   --Full domestic partner health insurance benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ''The members made their voices heard loud and clear,''
Davenport said. ''I believe our negotiators achieved an agreement
that meets flight attendants' needs. No longer will Northwest
flight attendants stand on the bottom rung of the industry
ladder.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, pay for flight attendants at Northwest starts at
around $16,000 and rises to more than $40,000, with the average pay
in the mid-$30,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants at the nation's fourth-largest airline
have been seeking a new contract since September 1996. Tensions
have remained high since Northwest sued the union over an alleged
holiday sickout.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest fired 18 flight attendants for calling in sick during
the Christmas-New Year's holiday period, and the union filed
grievances. Northwest canceled about 300 flights over the period.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides had agreed before Thursday that the company's lawsuit
would be dropped if the flight attendants ratified a tentative
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants took pay cuts for three years beginning in
1993 to help keep Northwest out of bankruptcy, and until early this
year wages were only 3 percent higher than before the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Northwest gave flight attendants a 4 percent raise,
just a day after giving its mechanics, custodians and cleaners the
same pay hike.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest pilots went on a 15-day strike in 1998 that crippled
the airline for weeks and cost the company millions in lost
profits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 2104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000420.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Completes Fund-Raising  </HEADLINE>
By CONNIE CASS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore won't be doing the
dinner-and-a-donation bit for his presidential campaign anymore.
The vice president is allowed to spend only $9 million more before
his nomination in August, and he's just about raised it.
</P>
<P>
   Unbound by the spending limit Gore faces, Republican George W.
Bush plans to keep doing the dinner circuit even though he has
raised a record $80 million and spent more than $73 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is limited to spending $40.5 million because he is
accepting federal matching funds. Bush is not taking taxpayer
money, so he can spend as much as he can raise.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, Gore has more cash: $8.7 million, including
taxpayer matching funds, to Bush's $5.7 million, according to
finance reports filed Thursday. The figures take into account debt
of about $1 million for each.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush expects to catch up quickly and outspend Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway said they weren't worried about
being down to $9 million because Bush spent vast sums during the
early primaries ''only to lose a nearly 20-point lead in the
polls'' over Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''We understand that we'll continue to be outspent, but we'll
use our resources wisely and beat him on the issues,'' Hattaway
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan noted that the Texas governor
added another $1.8 million in the first half of this month, and
plans another fund-raiser in Greensboro, N.C., next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have plenty of resources to continue spreading
the governor's compassionate conservative message,'' McClellan
said. ''Al Gore needs to explain his administration's fund-raising
excesses, including his visit to the Buddhist temple, before he
attacks the spending practices of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Each candidate will receive $67.6 million in federal funds upon
receiving his party's nomination, and will then be prohibited from
raising more campaign cash. The Republican convention is July
31-Aug. 3 in Philadelphia; the Democrats meet Aug. 14-17 in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will keep raising cash for the Democratic Party even though
he's appeared at his last presidential campaign fund-raiser -- a
$100,000-plus event last weekend at the home of computer company
executive Jesse Singh in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not holding any more events. We will be doing some
fund-raising through direct mail and via the Web site,'' Hattaway
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Bush added another 15 names to his list of 156
''Pioneers'' -- fund-raisers who have brought in $100,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway said Gore, who last year released a list of 25
top-level fund-raisers, doesn't plan to give out any more names.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's big donors included millionaire developer George Argyros
of Costa Mesa, Calif., former owner of the Seattle Mariners;
Gregory Slayton, chairman of the Palo Alto, Calif., tech company My
Software; and Jim Haslam, a Knoxville, Tenn., founder of a chain of
convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Huizenga, founder of National Heritage Academies, one of
the nation's largest chains of for-profit charter schools, and Mark
Guzzetta, a fund-raiser for Bush's brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush,
were also on the list.
</P>
<P>
   In March, as Gore put away a challenge by former Sen. Bill
Bradley, he raised $1.9 million and spent $4.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway said Gore expects to qualify for a record $15 million
in federal matching funds for the primary season, surpassing 1996
Republican nominee Bob Dole, who received about $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers match the first $250 of each individual contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Bush raised $5.9 million and spent $10.1 million in March as he
finished a tough primary race against Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
