<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tribe Places Sandy Alomar on DL  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Sandy Alomar, the Cleveland Indians catcher who
spent nearly four months on the disabled list last season following
knee surgery, was placed on the 15-day DL Thursday because of a
pulled right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar played in a career-low 37 games in 1999 after having a
bone spur removed from his left knee in May. The 33-year-old
catcher lost 15 pounds over the winter and arrived at spring
training in great shape hoping to catch 100 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   But just 14 games into a new season, he's back on the DL for the
eighth time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's never easy to deal with going on the DL,'' said Alomar,
who was batting .310. ''But I've had some practice with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar began having spams in his hamstring during Tuesday
night's game against the Oakland Athletics and left in the fourth
inning. He underwent an MRI exam Wednesday, which revealed the
pull, an although it's not considered serious, the Indians didn't
want to take any chances and decided to place him on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   ''The doctors said he will be out anywhere from 10 days to two
weeks,'' Indians manager Charlie Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians purchased the contract of catcher Bobby Hughes from
Triple-A Buffalo to take Alomar's roster spot and back up Einar
Diaz. With Alomar sidelined last season, Diaz, 27, batted .281 with
three homers and 32 RBIs in 119 games.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, 29, was released by the Milwaukee Brewers on April 3. In
two seasons in Milwaukee, he batted .238 with 12 homers and 37 RBIs
in 133 games. At Buffalo, he was hitting .310 with six RBIs in
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got some power for a catcher,'' Manuel said. ''He's got a
good arm. (Buffalo manager Joel) Skinner tells me he throws good
and he's got a chance to hit the ball out of the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes was activated just before Thursday night's game against
the A's. To make room for Hughes on their 40-man roster, the
Indians designated outfielder Scott Morgan for assigment.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland has 10 days to trade, release or outright Morgan, who
was the Indians' minor league player of the year in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar's 11-year career has been riddled with trips to the DL,
including two stints when the six-time All-Star tore the webbing on
his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   ''A couple of times I've gone on for freaky things,'' Alomar
said. ''There could be 50 guys standing around and the bomb would
hit me.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar is the second All-Star to be placed on the DL by the
Indians this week. Cleveland's No. 1 starter Bartolo Colon could be
out for three weeks with a pulled rib cage muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland was decimated by injuries last season, using the DL a
total of 22 times with 16 different players. Because of injuries,
the Indians were only able to field their opening-day lineup four
times all year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
