<HEADLINE> Notes from Thursday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Royals-Twins:
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Starter Jose Rosado is one of just four returning
pitchers from Kansas City's 1999 opening day roster. ... The Royals
have been over .500 for 12 days this year. Last year they were over
.500 for just nine days. ... Johnny Damon had his sixth stolen base
Thursday. The Royals have been successful on 17-of-18 in steal
attempts this season.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Fifteen members of the Uruguay national under-18
basketball team were in attendance Thursday afternoon as they
concluded their two-week trip through Minnesota. The team, from
Minnesota sister city Montevideo, played 10 games against various
high school teams.
Devil Rays-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: Dave Martinez has four straight multi-hit games and
has hit safely in nine of 10 starts. ... Reliever Albie Lopez has
issued at least one walk in each of his seven appearances.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: Scott Erickson, who had bone chips removed from his
elbow on March 3, will get his first rehabilitation assignment
Tuesday for Class A Frederick. ... Closer Mike Timlin made his
season debut Thursday, allowing a two-run homer in the seventh
inning. He was out with a torn muscle in his side. ... After the
game the Orioles recalled RHP Jason Johnson from Triple-A Rochester
and sent RHP Al Reyes to the minor league club. Johnson will start
Sunday in Oakland.
Athletics-Indians:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: C Bobby Hughes, called up from Triple-A Buffalo when
Sandy Alomar went on the disabled list, got word he was going be
activated while on the Bisons' team bus en route to Scranton. ...
Manager Charlie Manuel said he'd like the Indians to be more
aggressive on the bases, especially leadoff hitter Kenny Lofton.
The Indians have two steals as a team through 14 games. Last year
they had 13 in their first 12 games. ''I'd like to see Kenny run
more even if he gets thrown out,'' Manuel said. ... The Indians
traded minor league OF Dan McKinley to Montreal for OF Scott
Hunter. Hunter, drafted by the Dodgers in 1993, was batting .200 in
seven games for Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Right after hockey, Matt Stairs' favorite subject is
hockey. Following Wednesday night's win over the Indians, Stairs,
who is from Canada, chased reporters away from his view of the St.
Louis-San Jose game on the clubhouse TV. ... John Jaha returned to
the A's starting lineup after missing six of the last seven games
with a tender left shoulder. ... The A's, who were just 2-10
against Cleveland last season, were looking for their first sweep
in Cleveland since Sept. of 1989.
Angels-Blue Jays:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: Manager Jim Fregosi said Shannon Stewart may have to be
placed on the 15-day disabled list. Stewart's pulled right
hamstring is not getting any better. He's missed four games. ... SS
Alex Gonzalez was given the day off. ... 2B Homer Bush, who sat out
Toronto's previous five games because of a pulled quad and strained
left hamstring, returned to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: The 10 earned runs allowed by Ken Hill on Wednesday
night, equaled his career-high. ... C Matt Walbeck made his fourth
start of the season.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Cubs-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Sammy Sosa started in center field for the first time
this season. Roosevelt Brown made his first start in right field.
... The Cubs have lost four straight for the second time this
season. They also lost four from March 30-April 6. ... Eric Young
entered Thursday night's series finale just four steals short of
300 for his career. ... Also entering the game, Chicago starters
had gone at least six innings in 11 of their last 12 games. ...
Ismael Valdes threw 61 pitches in 4 1-2 shutout innings over 4 1-3
innings Wednesday during an extended spring training game. Valdes,
acquired with Young from Los Angeles last Dec. 12, has been on the
15-day disabled list since March 20 with tendinitis in his right
shoulder. ... The starting time for the Cubs' April 26 game in
Houston has been changed to 6:05 p.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: The Expos have won five straight home series from the
Cubs since June 6-9, 1997. Montreal was going for its first
three-game series sweep over Chicago since May 6-8, 1996 at Olympic
Stadium. ... Vladimir Guerrero, who entered the game just one RBI
short of 300, needs three more homers for 100. Guerrero struck out
for the first time this season Wednesday night. ... At 8-6,
Montreal is off to its best start since 1996. The Expos didn't win
their eighth game of 1999 until May 4, when a 2-1 win over Los
Angeles gave them an 8-18 mark. Montreal hasn't started a season
9-6 since 1993.
Pirates-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: The Pirates purchased the contracts of RHPs Brad
Clontz and Jose Parra and recalled RHP Mike Garcia from Triple-A
Nashville. To make room on their roster, the Pirates optioned LHP
Chris Peters and RHP Marc Wilkins to Nashville and placed RHP Jason
Schmidt on the 15-day disabled list (retroactive to April 15) due
to an inflammation in his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: With a win Thursday, the Marlins will equal the best
start in the team's eight-year history. The 1997 World Series
championship team started 10-7 before losing two straight. ...
Thursday's starting pitcher Ryan Dempster will have a diary on the
Marlins' new Web site at www.floridamarlins.com. Considered one of
the team's most colorful players, Dempster will provide insights
into the daily nuances of a major leaguer.
Giants-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: Barry Bonds came down with the flu Thursday
morning, causing him to miss a game for the first time this season.
That was a big break for Reds starter Denny Neagle: Bonds is
13-for-37 (.351) career against the left-hander with five homers.
... Livan Hernandez (0-4) is in a four-game losing streak that
matches the longest of his career. He also lost four games in a row
from Aug. 21 to Sept. 12, 1998, with Florida.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: The Reds ended their streak of 11 straight games
with an error, their longest since 1974. ... SS Barry Larkin (.344)
has hit safely in 14 of the Reds' 16 games this season and is off
to his best start since 1995, when he won the NL Most Valuable
Player award. ''Throughout my career, every other year I get off to
a good start,'' Larkin said. ''This happens to be one of those
years.'' ... The Reds will be trying for their first three-game
winning streak on Friday against Los Angeles.
Mets-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   BREWERS: Milwaukee will be happy to leave New York, where it has
not only had trouble with the Mets (losing 15 of 18 meetings since
1998) but also the Yankees before the switch to the NL in 1998...
Milwaukee is 3-16 in games against the two teams in New York since
1996. ... RHP Jim Bruske (whose number, 88, is the highest ever for
a Brewer) has won his last six decisions dating back to Sept. 10,
1997, when he was with San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Opening day CF Darryl Hamilton, scheduled to come off
the disabled list Saturday with this sprained left foot, is not yet
physically able to play. ... RHP Rick Reed reported progress but
discomfort on the bruised left thumb hit by a line drive Wednesday
night off the bat of Brewers Marquis Grissom. He is expected to
make his next start Monday against Los Angeles in New York.
Phillies-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: After Atlanta, the Phillies traveled to Florida
for a four-game series. Philadelphia dominated the Marlins in 1999,
going 11-2 overall and 5-1 Pro Player Stadium. That was their best
overall and road record against any team. ... Ron Gant's error in
the eighth inning Wednesday night snapped a streak of 62 innings
without an error. The Phillies had committed a league-low three
errors through their first 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: New hitting coach Merv Rettenmund has made his presence
felt with the Braves, who used to be known as a free-swinging team
that relied on the three-run homer. Entering Thursday's game,
Atlanta had the fewest strikeouts in the majors (5.2 per game). The
Braves averaged 5.9 strikeouts in 1999, when now-Cubs manager Don
Baylor served as hitting coach, and 6.6 in '98, when Clarence Jones
handled the job. ... Nineteen-year-old Rafael Furcal made another
start at shortstop. Baseball's youngest player is virtually sharing
the job with Walt Weiss, having started six of the Braves 15 games.
... Kevin McGlinchey, one of the team's most valuable relievers in
1999, has been the forgotten man this year. Going into Thursday's
game, the 22-year-old right-hander had not pitched in eight days.
Overall, he worked just 2 2-3 innings through the first 14 games.
Padres-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: Tony Gwynn was out of the lineup Thursday, a day
after making his first start in eight games due to an injured left
knee. He said he felt fine aside from a lack of strength in the
knee, but ''they're taking the cautious route with me.'' The Padres
have lost each of Sterling Hitchcock's four starts by one run. ...
Trevor Hoffman entered the game with 33 straight save conversions,
the longest active streak in baseball. He had converted 122 of his
last 127 opportunities. ... The team optioned C Ben Davis, who was
1-for-16, to Las Vegas of the Pacific Coast League and purchased
the contract of RHP Vicente Palacios from Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Mark McGwire returned to the lineup after missing
seven games with a lower back strain. ''Now we can start talking
about how I play instead of that,'' McGwire said. ... Manager Tony
La Russa is tired of Ray Lankford's streaky nature, noting this is
his 10th season as a regular. ''He's not a young hitter anymore, he
knows how to make adjustments,'' La Russa said. La Russa benched
Lankford, who entered the game in a 1-for-26 slump, on Wednesday
and moved him from third to fifth Thursday. ... The Cardinals have
hit back-to-back home runs six times this season and Fernando Tatis
has been involved on three occasions. The NL record is 15
back-to-back homer games by the 1997 Colorado Rockies. ... C Mike
Matheny got only his fourth day off in 16 games. He has thrown out
eight of 11 baserunners.
Rockies-Diamondbacks:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Larry Walker, livid over suggestions that he purposely
had ducked facing Randy Johnson, asked manager Buddy Bell to put
him in the lineup against the Big Unit on Thursday night. Walker
had never played against Johnson in three previous opportunities.
Bell did so. ... Going into Thursday night's game, the Rockies had
scored 33 runs without a homer. The last Colorado player to hit a
home run was Todd Helton on Sunday in the first game of a
doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Closer Matt Mantei, on the disabled list since April 2
with biceps tendinitis, will be activated on Friday. ... Entering
Thursday night's game, Randy Johnson had struck out 33 since his
last walk. In all, he had 34 strikeouts and two walks in his 3-0
start.
</P>
</TEXT>
