<DOCNO> APW20000420.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Staffs Up for General Election  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore is adding new faces to his
presidential campaign and stocking the Democratic National
Committee with loyal aides in preparation for the November showdown
with Republican George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fabiani, a former Clinton White House aide who helped the
president weather the Whitewater inquiry and other high-profile
controversies, is joining Gore's team this week as deputy campaign
manager for communications, according to top campaign advisers Tony
Coelho and Donna Brazile.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from their Nashville, Tenn.,
headquarters, the pair said Fabiani will oversee the press,
research, message and issue teams at both the campaign and the DNC.
He will become the most visible face of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Fabiani's hiring coincides with several promotions and additions
at the campaign, including:
</P>
<P>
   -- Lisa Berg, deputy campaign manager for scheduling and advance.
</P>
<P>
   -- Chip Smith, deputy campaign manager and chief of staff who
will conduct the campaign's day-to-day coordination with the DNC
and other party affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   -- Heather Marabeti, deputy chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   -- Janet Murguia, deputy campaign manager of public liaison,
making her the point person for Democratic constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   -- Elaine Kamarck, policy consultant with the campaign and the
DNC.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sarah Bianchi, policy and communications under Kamarck. She is
a health care specialist at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Whouley, the political strategist credited with helping
to build Gore's teams for the New Hampshire and Iowa elections,
will become senior political strategist as a consultant to both the
campaign and the DNC. Donnie Fowler Jr., field director at the
campaign, will coordinate his efforts with Whouley.
</P>
<P>
   Changes at the DNC include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Laurie Moskowitz will work on the coordinated campaign
efforts. She was a political operative at the DNC before heading
Gore's delegate process.
</P>
<P>
   -- Laura Quinn will move from Gore's White House office to be
communications director at the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mike Mathews will move from the AFL-CIO to be senior political
adviser at both the DNC and the campaign on labor relations and
policy.
</P>
<P>
   -- Kikki Moore, a top Democratic communications specialist, will
be a senior adviser and frequent spokeswoman for both Gore and the
DNC.
</P>
<P>
   -- Celinda Lake, a Democratic pollster, will join the DNC to help
Gore and other party candidates target female and elderly voters.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gore, Bush is tweaking his Austin, Texas, staff and placing
advisers at the Republican National Committee
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
