<HEADLINE> Scuffle at Galatasaray-Leeds Game  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEEDS, England (AP) -- Leeds fans smashed the window of a bus
carrying Galatasaray officials to Thursday's UEFA Cup semifinal, a
2-2 tie that advanced the Turkish team to the championship game on
4-2 aggregate.
</P>
<P>
   Galatasaray, the first Turkish team ever in a European final,
will play Arsenal, which won 2-1 at Lens to advance on 3-1
aggregate. The championship is May 17 in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Three buses carrying Galatasaray officials arrived at the
stadium to jeers and chants of ''scum'' from hundreds of Leeds
fans.
</P>
<P>
   An object was hurled at the front coach, smashing one of the
windows, and some Leeds fans drew their finger across their neck in
a mock gesture similar to that given by Turkish fans toward Leeds
supporters two weeks ago. Several coins were also thrown at the
buses.
</P>
<P>
   Galatasaray striker Hakan Sukur was struck by an object thrown
by a fan toward the end of the game in which he scored his team's
second goal.
</P>
<P>
   Police reported 23 arrests, but there were no immediate reports
of any injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents came on a night of high tension surrounding the
game following the killing of two Leeds supporters in Istanbul two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans throw coins at the police outside, and the game began
10 minutes late. The bus taking the Galatasaray team into the
stadium grounds entered through a side entrance to avoiding the
Leeds fans waiting at the main gates.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Galatasaray's fans banned from the game, there were
350 police, twice as many as normal.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the stadium and when the Galatasaray players ran out to
warm up for the game, they placed flowers at several parts of the
field as a mark of respect to the two Leeds fans who were stabbed
to death in Istanbul two weeks go before the first leg of the
home-and-home, total-goals series.
</P>
<P>
   At first some of the Leeds fans began to boo the players, who
were also deliberately wearing black warmup suits, but that changed
to applause.
</P>
<P>
   Yildirim Akbulut, the speaker of the Turkish parliament, sports
minister Fikret Unlu and former premier and leader of the
opposition True Path party Tansu Ciller were among the party of 35
who arrived at Leeds, some of them in Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit's private jet.
</P>
<P>
   Galatasaray went ahead in the fifth minute when Gheorghe Hagi
converted a penalty kick after Hakan Suker was pulled down by
Jonathan Woodgate. Eirik Bakke's header tied it 11 minute later,
</P>
<P>
   Suker put the Turkish team back ahead in the 42nd minute, and
Bakke scored again in the 68th.
</P>
<P>
   At Lens, the Gunners got goals from Thierry Henry (43rd minute)
and Nwankwo Kanu (86th), while Pascal Nouma (73rd) scored for the
home team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
