<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dayne Attends Giants Minicamp  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- While they probably know what Ron
Dayne can do on a football field better than most, Robert Reid and
Ron Hopson prefer to talk about the Heisman Trophy winner and New
York Giants' first-round draft pick in other terms.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of discussing the tailback's ability to cut or his
speed, quickness and power, they like to talk about the other side
of Dayne, the part only friends and family see off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Reid helped raise Dayne, taking his 13-year-old nephew into his
home after Dayne's mother went through a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Hopson was Dayne's principal and mentor at Overbrook High School
in southern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   At Dayne's first local news conference since being taken by the
Giants with the 11th pick in the NFL draft, both men stood in the
back of the room Thursday, enjoying every moment.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has a hunger and sense about him,'' Hopson said. ''He knows
what he needs to do and he always gets it done. He has that kind of
intelligence. You could sit down and talk to him. He won't talk
back, but he's listening all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid said that being almost twice as big as his friends somehow
made Dayne mature even before high school.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ron had a mystique growing up because people always thought he
was older, because he was always the biggest kid in the class,''
Reid said. ''He was always respected as a mature kid. You never
knew what to expect out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates might also be surprised, Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a jokester, a comedian more than anything else,'' Dayne's
uncle said. ''He's a fun-loving guy, a prankster enjoying life,
having a tremendous desire to play football.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Giants will expect out of Dayne is a halfback who can
restore a running game that averaged less than 90 yards last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the numbers he produced at Wisconsin, where he broke
the Division I rushing record, Dayne should help. But some experts
have questions about his weight (255 pounds) and how much wear and
tear his body has taken.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said there wasn't any wear-and-tear until Dayne got to high
school, because he wasn't allowed to play when he was 11, 12 and
13. He already weighed around 250 pounds at that point, well over
the 135-pound midget limit, Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   ''All his nephews and cousins were achieving, doing real well on
the football field and here he was being relegated to soccer,''
Reid said. ''It was eating him up on the inside and he couldn't
wait until he was a freshman in high school and could play.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne broke records in high school and didn't stop in college.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants seem to be expecting more. When they handed out
uniforms on Thursday, Jim Fassel handed Dayne No. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The last Giants player to wear the number was Rodney Hampton,
the team's leading rusher with 6,897 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne had wanted No. 33 -- his number from college and high
school -- but second-year halfback Joe Montgomery has the number
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't make a difference what number I have,'' Dayne said.
''I just want to come out here and give it my best and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants linebacker Pete Monty, Dayne's teammate at Wisconsin,
thinks Dayne will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He didn't get a shot early on at Wisconsin and he kept
fighting to get playing time,'' Monty said. ''Eventually he did,
and he kept running from there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 2143 </TRAILER>
