<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Hopeful on Mideast Peace  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Citing the ''risks and difficulties'' inherent
in achieving peace, President Clinton on Thursday greeted
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat with hope that he can help Israel
and the Palestinians meet a September deadline for a final
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   After a nearly three-hour meeting, the White House said that
Israel and the Palestinians will resume negotiations later this
month in the Middle East region. A senior administration official,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said the United States would
take on ''a more intensified role'' at the request of both Israel
and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the talks are now turning to the most complex
emotional issues, such as settlements, borders, refugees, even
Palestinian statehood -- matters at the core of a final status
agreement -- and expressed optimism that a framework for an
agreement might be reached by the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the issues between the two sides are ''difficult,
but I think they can be bridged.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There are risks and difficulties involved,'' Clinton said. ''I
believe they are not nearly as great as the risks and difficulties
of not making a peace agreement. So I hope they will do it. ... I
will do everything I can to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat arrived at the White House by car Thursday evening.
Clinton received Arafat exactly as he received Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak last week -- meeting him at the White House's
South Portico and strolling together across the Rose Garden to the
Oval Office. Clinton spoke briefly with reporters, Arafat did not.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Arafat talked for a half-hour along with nine aides
each, then pared that group down to themselves, two notetakers and
an interpreter for discussions that went on for more than an hour.
Then Clinton and Arafat shared a dinner of red snapper, salad,
mixed vegetables and saffron potatoes, and Arafat left.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin also reaffirmed that
the United States is prepared to play a more active role in
recognition not only of the September deadline but also of others
that are approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone is agreed that we will play a more involved role by
being at the table, trying to be creative, trying to help each side
figure out what its needs are,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat met with Clinton a few hours after a luncheon meeting
with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart said the Palestinians
and Israelis face ''a very tight time line'' and Clinton wanted the
face-to-face sessions to see how the United States could keep the
negotiations on track.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton met with Barak last week, the discussion focused on
the need for an accelerated pace, and that appeared to be at the
center of Arafat's talks here as well. Lockhart said Clinton wanted
to ''take stock of where we are'' without offering new proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The talks on a treaty framework are to begin after the Jewish
Passover holiday, which ends April 26. Negotiators will meet in
Israel and the Palestinian areas, rather than in Washington, as
they have done in two previous rounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have said no progress has been made since talks
on a blueprint for a peace treaty began in November.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said he was not aware that there are any new U.S. ideas
that were being presented on Thursday or any time soon. This did
not rule out the possibility of ''creative suggestions'' at some
point, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel and the Palestinians face a May deadline for a treaty
framework, and a September target for a full accord.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said Sunday he would turn over West Bank land that would
give the Palestinians the territorial contiguity they need for
statehood, and assured his hard-line Israeli critics that Jerusalem
would remain united under Israeli sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, Palestinian suburbs just outside the city, claimed
by both sides as their capital, would be handed over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-20-00 2146 </TRAILER>
