<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Subway Fire Prompts Evacuation  </HEADLINE>
By RON VAMPLE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fire in a tunnel between two Metro subway
stations forced the evacuation of a train and the two stations at
the height of the evening rush hour Thursday, stranding thousands
of commuters and tourists.
</P>
<P>
   No serious injuries were reported, but paramedics treated a
dozen people for smoke inhalation as the Farragut West and Foggy
Bottom stations were emptied. The stations, which carry the Blue
and Orange lines that ferry passengers to and from the Virginia and
Maryland suburbs, were reopened and service resumed at about 9
p.m., after about four hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was scary for a while,'' said Ann Wright of Calgary,
Alberta, a tourist who was on the train that was evacuated. ''Smoke
filled one of cars and people started screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wright, traveling with her three sons, said a man on the
train calmed everyone down.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told us not to panic and cover our mouths with our
shirts,'' she said, adding that people followed his directions.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was thought to have started in a power cable in a
tunnel as a train neared the Foggy Bottom station in the heart of
George Washington University campus, said Capt. Brian Lee of the
District of Columbia Fire Department. Farragut West is about four
blocks from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers who were trapped on the train for two hours had to
walk through the tunnel to the Foggy Bottom platform after the fire
was put out.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic also was snarled on streets around the stations with
emergency vehicles blocking them as firefighters dealt with the
blaze.
</P>
<P>
   Some shuttle buses carried passengers from the two shut stations
to the Rosslyn station in nearby Arlington, Va., the closest
station that carries the Blue and Orange lines. But commuters piled
up there because of a shortage of buses to allow commuters to
continue their rides home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
