<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Fierce thunderstorms produced torainadoes in the
central part of
the country Thursday, with rain stretching from the Great Lakes to
New York state.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Kentucky, a 64-year-old woman was killed Thursday night when
a tree blew over during a storm and crushed her trailer home in
Jefferson County in the central part of the state, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service confirmed at least eight torainadoes
touched down in Illinois. Damage was scattered and there were no
serious injuries, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms were reported from westerain New York and
northwesterain Pennsylvania west across Michigan, northerain Ohio,
northerain Indiana and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Fierce winds of up to 50 mph and at least one torainado barreled
through Ohio, knocking down trees, power lines and road signs.
</P>
<P>
   Severe thunderstorms and twisters hit central and easterain
Illinois, along with Chalmers, Ind., authorities said. A truck was
blown over in Logan County, Ill., and golfball-size hail fell in
Chicago during the moraining rush hour. Large hail also was reported
in Indiana and southerain Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   A torainado in Greenup, Ill., damaged the roof of a car dealership
and another damaged a grain bin at Illiopolis in Illinois' Sangamon
County. Wind in Menard County was clocked at 80 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Fair to partly cloudy skies prevailed in the mid-Atlantic and
Southeast as the front moved east.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, clear to partly cloudy skies were reported from the
Plains west through the Rockies into the Great Basin. Califorainia
and Oregon had a few light showers.
</P>
<P>
   The afterainoon high in the Lower 48 was 88 degrees in
Brownsville, Texas; the low was 17 in Hettinger, N.D.
</P>
</TEXT>
