<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protester Injured in Whale Hunt  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEAH BAY, Wash. (AP) -- A woman on a jet ski was injured Thursday
as she tried to disrupt a whale hunt by members of the Makah tribe
and collided with a Coast Guard boat. The hunt was unsuccessful,
but tribal members said they would not be deterred by protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Erin Abbott, 23, an anti-whaling protester from Seattle, was
listed as stable Thursday at a Port Angeles hospital with a
shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   Television video showed Abbott swooping in on her watercraft as
the tribe's carved wooden canoe closed in on a gray whale. The
Makah had just thrown a harpoon, which did not stick in the whale.
</P>
<P>
   As the Makah attempted to maneuver for another shot, Abbott
rushed by the canoe, spraying those aboard with her wake. As the
watercraft turned, it was overtaken by the 21-foot inflatable Coast
Guard boat.
</P>
<P>
   The two collided, and both the watercraft and Abbott appeared to
go under the Coast Guard boat. Abbott surfaced a moment later about
20 feet from her watercraft.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't believe she wasn't killed,'' said Julie Woodyer of
World Whale Police. ''This aggressive behavior by the Coast Guard
is unprecedented -- this is our worst nightmare come true.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters are required to stay 500 yards from the Makah whalers
and their canoe.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope she's OK, but it's unfortunate that she would violate
the exclusionary zone'' around the canoe, said Makah Whaling
Commission Chairman Keith Johnson. ''She'll have to accept the
consequences of her actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard Cmdr. Ted Lindstrom said the agency regretted that
Abbott had been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard officials said a second protester, Erin O'Connell,
was arrested Thursday morning and a second personal watercraft was
confiscated. Protesters said they would resort to using larger
boats to interfere with the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to keep fighting. It's not going to deter us,''
said Jonathan Paul, a spokesman for Ocean Defense International.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday afternoon, the Makah hunters had closed in on at
least one other whale, which dove before they could throw another
harpoon. They quit hunting late Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal leaders say the seasonal hunt, a centuries-old tradition
that resumed in the fall of 1998 after a 70-year hiatus, is vital
to preserving the identity of the tribe at the tip of Washington's
Olympic Peninsula. Anti-whaling activists fear it could open the
door to a worldwide renewal of commercial whaling.
</P>
<P>
   A whaling crew with representatives from several families took
the tribe's first whale last May 17. Now the hunts are being
conducted by individual Makah families, as tradition dictates.
</P>
<P>
   Five families have been preparing to hunt as the gray whales
migrate from birthing grounds in Mexico to feeding grounds off
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The International Whaling Commission has allocated the Makah 20
whales through 2004, a maximum of five per year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
