<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violent Threats Close U.S. Schools  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE GUTTERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Classes were canceled or security was stepped up
at many schools around the country Thursday because of a rash of
threats and rumors tied to the anniversary of the Columbine High
bloodbath.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of violence or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   School violence experts said it was natural that threats and
hoax calls would increase on the anniversary of the deadliest
school shooting in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are more likely simply because of the awareness people
have of the Columbine anniversary,'' said Pamela Riley, president
of the Center for the Prevention of School Violence at North
Carolina State University. ''It seems like an anniversary of
something like this is a time to remember by doing something that
is good, but unfortunately, that's not what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   No threats were reported at Columbine or any other Jefferson
County school, a sheriff's spokesman said late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Schools in Epping, N.H., were closed Thursday after someone
scrawled a message on a high school bathroom wall that said ''4/20
everyone will die.'' Officials said a boy confessed and told them
it was a prank.
</P>
<P>
   California's Santa Barbara High School District planned
additional security after notes threatening certain students were
found recently. One note said, ''We will finish what Hitler,
Columbine started.'' April 20 was Adolf Hitler's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, schools ''have all been walking the
tightrope all week, trying to keep their guard up and react to
incidents and track down rumors while at the same time not
overreacting and creating the type of situation they are trying to
avoid,'' said Kenneth Trump, president of National School Safety
and Security Services, a consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   Schools were closed Thursday in Port Edwards, Wis., after a
bomb-like device was found near the front doors of a high school.
An Army bomb squad determined that the device -- a propane tank with
a timer, batteries and wires -- could not have detonated.
</P>
<P>
   Security was tightened at Encinal High in Alameda, Calif., where
three students were in custody for allegedly creating ''hit lists''
naming 105 students to be killed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Westerville North High School and Heritage Middle School in Ohio
were closed after a bomb threat was found in a bathroom. A threat
found at Walnut Hills Middle Schools in Ohio prompted officials to
send students to a neighboring church until the time listed in the
threat had passed. Classes then resumed.
</P>
<P>
   In New Mexico, Springer Municipal Schools classes were canceled
because of a threat the superintendent said was called in Wednesday
and was related to the Columbine anniversary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
