<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Welcomes Israel Withdrawal Plan  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council said Thursday it
welcomed news of Israel's plans to withdraw from southern Lebanon
and gave the go-ahead to draft plans for a U.N. role in the
pullout.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement adopted by the council, ambassadors formally
acknowledged a letter received Monday from Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy to Secretary-General Kofi Annan informing him that
Israel would withdrawal by July 7.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Security Council shares the view expressed by the
secretary-general .... that cooperation by all parties concerned
will be required in order to avoid a deterioration of the
situation,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and has occupied part of southern
Lebanon since 1985 as a buffer against guerrilla attacks on
northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Security Council resolutions call for Israel's withdrawal and
the establishment of a U.N. peacekeeping force to confirm the
pullout.
</P>
<P>
   Annan told reporters on Wednesday that the United Nations may
need to strengthen its peacekeeping force in southern Lebanon to
monitor the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has pledged to withdraw
Israeli troops from Lebanon by July, preferably as part of an
agreement with Lebanon and Syria but unilaterally if necessary.
Syria is the main power broker in Lebanon. Talks between Israel and
Syria, however, have stalled since January.
</P>
<P>
   Israel believes the U.N. force, now numbering about 4,500
troops, will be enough to patrol the Israel-Lebanon border if
expanded to its full mandate of 7,000 soldiers, a senior Israeli
official said recently, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But the secretary-general said the United Nations has not
determined how many troops will be needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
