<HEADLINE> 2 US Boxers Qualify for Olympic Team  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) -- Brian Viloria and Dante Craig earned
berths in the Olympic Games at Sydney, Australia with victories
Thursday night in an Olympic boxing qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   Viloria, 106 pounds, defeated Domenic Filane of Canada 10-2 and
Craig, 147, beat Yovanny Lorenzo of the Dominican Republic 16-3 in
the semifinal round of the second of three Olympic qualifying
tournaments. Viloria and Filane earned berths in the Sydney
Olympics regardless of the outcome of the final bouts on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, Olanda Anderson, 178, was scheduled to try to
give the United States the last victory it needs to send a full
team to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Viloria got his berth in the Olympics by bouncing back from a
loss to Puerto Rico's Ivan Calderon in the first Americas Olympic
qualifier at Tampa, Fla., three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was real down following my loss in Tampa,'' Viloria, the
current 106-pound world champion, said. ''But I knew that I had to
get right back in the ring and start all over again. I'm just
relieved that I don't have to go to Argentina'' for the last
qualifier May 29-June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, a surprise winner over two-time U.S. champion Larry
Mosley, had no international experience before the qualifiers
began. With two bouts in Tampa and four in Mexico, Craig has the
experience he will need to structure his training regimen toward
defeating international opponents in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew deep down inside that coming to Mexico was best for
me,'' Craig said. ''It has been a grueling experience, but I know
that I'll come out better because of it. I've been dreaming about
this for a long time, and I just had to wait a little bit longer
before it came true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
