<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
Carmen Dillon
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Art director Carmen Dillon, who won an Academy
Award in 1948 for her work on Laurence Olivier's ''Hamlet,'' died
April 12. She was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon, who created sets for many memorable British films for
more than 40 years, was the first female art director in the
British film industry. Dillon joined the art department at Fox
Studios north of London in the 1930s after six years of training as
an architect.
</P>
<P>
   In 1938, she moved to Pinewood Studios, where she worked on the
films ''The Mikado'' and ''French Without Tears.''
</P>
<P>
   She worked with Paul Sherriff on the Academy Award-nominated
design for Olivier's 1944 classic ''Henry V,'' but it was her work
on Olivier's ''Hamlet'' that won her the Oscar -- for set direction
on a black-and-white film.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon designed the films ''The Way to the Stars'' in 1945,
''The Browning Version'' in 1951, ''The Importance of Being
Earnest'' in 1952, Joseph Losey's ''Accident'' in 1967, ''The
Go-Between'' and ''Lady Caroline Lamb'' in 1972, and ''The Omen''
in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Andrew J. Karpinski
</P>
<P>
   DOVER, N.J. (AP) -- Andrew J. Karpinski, the former state
insurance commissioner who was forced out in an ethics controversy,
died Tuesday of a heart attack. He was 59.
</P>
<P>
   He was nominated by Gov. Christie Whitman on March 1, 1994, to
serve as insurance commissioner after a 30-year career as an
insurance agent. He resigned in October 1995 over charges he used
his personal insurance license to sell three policies for his
former insurance agency in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general's office said Karpinski acted
''improperly'' but did not recommend criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, Karpinski was president of the New
Jersey Title Insurance Co. in Parsippany.
</P>
<P>
John P. McLaughlin
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO (AP) -- John P. ''Jack'' McLaughlin, retired president
of Northern California's largest Teamsters union local, died
Tuesday of a heart attack. He was 62.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin retired in 1992 as president of Teamsters
Professional and Clerical Local 856 after a 32-year career, during
which he negotiated contracts in the car rental, freight, parcel
delivery and hotel industries.
</P>
<P>
   He studied for the priesthood for seven years and said his
religious studies fueled his strong social ethic.
</P>
<P>
Jack Page
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Jack Page, who taught journalism for
several decades at Oakland's Merritt College, died Saturday of a
heart attack. He was 71.
</P>
<P>
   Page, who also taught English and photography in his 30 years as
a Merritt professor, was known for his outspoken defense of his son
Bradley Page, who was convicted of voluntary manslaughter in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Page was convicted of the 1984 killing of his
college girlfriend, Roberta ''Bibi'' Lee. His father ardently
maintained his son was wrongly convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Page then worked as a reporter in Minneapolis and an editor for
the weekly Arizona Record, and later joined the Merritt College
faculty, where he taught until his retirement in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Page is survived by a daughter; three sons; and five grandsons.
</P>
<P>
Dr. J. Eugene Smith
</P>
<P>
   WINDHAM, Conn. (AP) -- Dr. J. Eugene Smith, a former president at
what is now Eastern Connecticut State University, died Thursday. He
was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was hired in 1937 to teach social sciences at the school,
then known as Willimantic State Teachers College. He was named the
school's second president in 1947, a position he held until 1966.
The school became Eastern Connecticut State University in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also served as executive secretary to the Board of
Trustees for the Connecticut state college system from 1967 to
1972.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the school dedicated its library in Smith's honor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
