<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinals 14, Padres 1  </HEADLINE>
By R.B. FALLSTROM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Eli Marrero hit a grand slam and later combined
with pitcher Rick Ankiel for back-to-back home runs Thursday night
as the St. Louis Cardinals beat the San Diego Padres 14-1 to
complete a three-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Ankiel (2-1) worked around seven walks in a five-inning
scoreless outing. He also went 3-for-3 -- the rookie pitcher is
5-for-9 with a triple and two RBIs this season.
</P>
<P>
   Marrero capped a six-run first with his first career grand slam.
He and Ankiel hit consecutive homers off reliever Vicente Palacios
in the fifth as the Cardinals continue to pace the majors in run
production.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis is averaging eight runs per game after topping their
previous high of 13 runs, have homered in 12 straight games and
lead the majors with 39 homers.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Tatis had four RBIs, two of them coming on bases-loaded
walks, and Ray Lankford broke out of a 1-for-26 slump with two hits
and three RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire returned to the lineup after missing seven games
with back problems and was 0-for-2 with two walks and two runs
scored, leaving for a pinch-runner in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Not many Padres made contact against Ankiel, at 20 the
second-youngest pitcher in the majors, who also had four
strikeouts. He walked the bases loaded in the first and got out of
it by striking out Ed Sprague and getting Bret Boone to foul out.
He walked two more in the fifth and again escaped a bases-loaded
jam by getting Sprague to ground out.
</P>
<P>
   The first inning lasted 41 minutes as Ankiel threw 36 pitches
and Padres starter Brian Boehringer (0-3) threw 44, including four
consecutive walks. Lankford and Tatis both walked with the bases
loaded and Marrero, making only his fourth start, hit his grand
slam on a 1-0 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have hit 30 homers during their 12-game streak,
which is five games shy of the team record set in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Padres cleanup hitter Phil Nevin and manager Bruce Bochy were
ejected in the middle of the third disputing a called third strike.
On his way off the field, Nevin threw his glove and hat in the air
and made a gesture in Young's direction with his arm, then took off
his jersey and dropped it in foul territory.
</P>
<P>
   Young was the first base umpire on Eric Davis' controversial
two-run bases-loaded infield hit on Wednesday night, ruling him
safe when replays indicated Davis was out by a half-step.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Cardinals have had back-to-back homers seven times
already. They did it only four times last season. The NL record is
15 by the 1997 Colorado Rockies. ... Cardinals manager Tony La
Russa, who twice insisted that Davis was safe Wednesday, admitted
Thursday he hadn't seen the replay until later and had been taking
the word of a Cardinals player or coach. ... Palacios made his
first major league appearance since 1995 when he pitched for the
Cardinals. He allowed six runs, four of them earned, in 1 2-3
innings. He was called up Thursday when the Padres demoted C Ben
Davis, who was 1-for-16. ... The Cardinals are 10-2 the last two
seasons against the Padres, although the first two victories in
this series were by one run. ... The Padres' run came on a
groundout by Chris Gomez in the sixth.
</P>
</TEXT>
