<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell
Friday morning on selling of shares in companies to be replaced in
that index. The dollar was higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The index, which was up some 300 points earlier in the session,
reversed into negative territory to shed 91.51 points, or 0.48
percent, to 18,867.81 points at the end of the morning session.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the average closed down 127.30 points, or 0.67
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 105.76 yen in late morning, up 1.01 yen from
late Thursday and also above its late New York level of 105.73 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the Tokyo stock market, prices started higher as investors
were cheered by the Dow's 169.09-point rise Thursday, leaving the
New York index at 10,844.05 at the market's close.
</P>
<P>
   But investors later began selling industrial stocks which will
be removed from the Nikkei index's stocks starting April 24.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty of the index's stocks will be replaced to better reflect
changes in Japan's economy, the Nihon Keizai newspaper, a major
Japanese financial daily and the administrator of the index, said
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Removal of stocks from the index tends to lower their prestige
and makes them less attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 21.41 points, or 1.31 percent, to 1,650.41
points. The TOPIX closed up 9.18 points, or 0.56 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar was supported after a top
government official said Japan will maintain its policy of
near-zero interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before Japan's Parliament, Bank of Japan Governor
Masaru Hayami said Thursday that the central bank will keep its
current policy until deflation concerns have subsided.
</P>
<P>
   Lower interest rates tend to make a nation's currency less
attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 99.36 yen, up from
98.30 yen late Thursday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond
stood at 1.7350 percent in late morning, unchanged from Thursday's
finish. Its price remained 101.42.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Japan's Tokyo Stock Exchange: http://www.tse.or.jp./
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
