<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Starting date for the EPIC expansion seems to have changed  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- What advocates had presumed to be an Oct. 1
starting date for an expansion of the state's prescription drug
program for senior citizens could now be delayed for months,
legislative sources say.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and Gov. George Pataki had initially talked about the
Oct. 1 date when reaching a deal to expand eligibility under the
Elderly Pharmaceutical Insurance Coverage (EPIC) program, but aides
acknowledged Thursday that the start-up date may change.
</P>
<P>
   ''All kinds of details relating to EPIC are under discussion,
and discussions are ongoing,'' Pataki spokesman Charles Deister
said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Burgess, executive director of the New York StateWide
Senior Action Council, said he was told by top legislative aides
that a starting date of Jan. 1, 2001 is under serious
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, eligible senior citizens would have to wait
longer before they can get reimbursed for prescription drug
payments, Burgess said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can see no reason why -- other than fiscal and political
reasons -- for doing this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To receive reimbursements under EPIC, senior citizens would
first have to pay a deductible, starting at $530 for a single
person with an annual income of $20,001. So if an individual with
that income spends about $200 dollars a month on drugs, it would
take three months before the first reimbursement check comes in, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement to expand EPIC, to be included in the 2000-01
state budget, is designed to increase the number of participants in
the program from the current 115,000 to an estimated 215,000 within
three years. The expansion will also cost the state an extra $180
million when fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing forward the effective date for an expansion of the
program would likely save the state millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hansen, a spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Joseph
Bruno, said that while Oct. 1 had been discussed, ''the effective
date has not been resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver's office would not confirm the
possible starting date delay.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't comment on it,'' spokesman Charles Carrier said.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators in both chambers have begun their traditional
Passover-Easter holiday and will not be back in session until
Monday, May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Under the revised EPIC program, annual income limits for
eligibility under EPIC will be expanded from $18,500 to $35,000 for
senior citizens living alone and from $24,400 to $50,000 for
married couples. Copays and fees charged seniors to enroll in EPIC
will also be reduced, and the complicated rules of the program will
be simplified.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers must be 65 or older to qualify for EPIC.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, state Sen. John Marchi said he is introducing a bill
to create an interstate compact to monitor prescription drug
prices. The bill would establish a commission composed of attorneys
general from compact states and make it a felony to charge a higher
price for drugs to any compact state than that sold to anyone
outside the compact.
</P>
<P>
   Marchi, a Staten Island Republican, said such a commission is
necessary to the combat the high prices for prescription drug sold
in the United States. U.S. prices sometimes run as high as two and
a half times as much as their Canadian counterparts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The compact would take effect when it becomes law in at least
two states. It would apply to New York seniors not covered under
EPIC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-20-00 2354 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000420.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-20 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A first: A judge now heads the state's judicial watchdog panel  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Odd as it may seem, an actual judge has
become chairman of the state's judicial watchdog commission for the
first time in its 25-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Salisbury, a prominent Buffalo lawyer specializing in
labor issues, has also been village justice in Blasdell, in Erie
County, since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   His elevation to the chairmanship of the 11-member Commission on
Judicial Conduct came in his 12th year on the panel, a long tenure
for judges who are appointed to the commission. Usually, sitting
judges serve for one four-year term and then step down from the
commission due to the assumption of other judicial posts or other
opportunities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Salisbury has stuck around long enough to win the
chairmanship in an election by members of the commission. He
replaces Henry Berger, a New York City election lawyer who will
retain his seat on the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the commission are not paid but they do get expenses
when on official business.
</P>
<P>
   Appointments are made to the panel by governors, legislative
leaders and, in Salisbury's case, the chief judge of the state
Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is not without controversy, both within and
outside the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Judges preside over matters of often great import to people's
lives, be they a stiff fine for speeding in a traffic case or, for
superior-court judges, criminal cases where a defendant's liberty
for many years or even life is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   As such, their work is constantly being criticized.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 25 years, the commission has received more than
25,000 complaints about judges in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Salisbury termed the bulk of the 1,400 cases the commission
looks into each year ''one-time accidental conduct'' which does not
result in the formal punishment of judges.
</P>
<P>
   But when the commission finds recurring, serious misconduct it
holds formal hearings and has the power to admonish or censure
judges -- two forms of public rebuke -- or to recommend their removal
from the bench. Once ousted, a judge can never hold judicial office
in the state again.
</P>
<P>
   In its history, the commission has deemed 131 judges unworthy of
serving on the bench any longer. Of those, 28 have been removed
from county courts or higher judgeships.
</P>
<P>
   It has also admonished 162 judges, censured 191 judges and 299
others resigned while the commission was looking into the
misconduct charges against them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the commission focuses on misbehavior by prominent
jurists. It was in the news earlier this month when the state's
highest court upheld its recommendation to remove Onondaga County
Court Judge J. Kevin Mulroy -- one of central New York's most
prominent judges -- for making insensitive remarks about blacks and
women.
</P>
<P>
   Far more of the judges the commission punishes sit on lower
courts, and Salisbury acknowledged that the panel still receives
criticism for ''going after'' the state's 4,300 town and village
court judges and not scrutinizing higher-court jurists more
closely.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, town and village judges are not lawyers and they
are sometimes elected to their posts with only rudimentary
knowledge of courts and law. The state mandates that they undergo
training on legal procedure, proper handling of fines and other
aspects of being a judge.
</P>
<P>
   New York also requires judges at all levels to take three hours
of ethics training each year. Salisbury is one of the instructors
in the special classes for judges offered by the state Office of
Court Administration.
</P>
<P>
   He said the extra training has ''gone a long way'' to instilling
ethics and knowledge in judges.
</P>
<P>
   But Salisbury said the pedigree of a judge or the loftiness of
his or her bench is not a factor when the commission looks into
misconduct charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a case, it is assigned a case number, and obviously we
know who it (the alleged wrongdoer) is,'' he said. ''But it
(judicial office) doesn't make any difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Salisbury and others associated with the Commission on Judicial
Conduct say they take the result of appeals of commission
determinations before the state's highest court, the Court of
Appeals, as confirmation of the soundness of their rulings.
</P>
<P>
   The high court has upheld 55 of the 68 recommendations it has
been asked to hear on appeal. Of the others, the recommended
punishment was reduced in nine of the cases and, twice, censure was
increased to removal.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in
Albany. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station,
Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
